[{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"It wasn’t the question of morality at the time. It was the question of survival. No one knew the right way out, we only knew how to fight to go on. There are no cats in Hillstead town and dogs turned against people to survive in the woods along with wolves. It all happened five years ago, when a great famine hit the city and people inside turned on their trusting pets to find means to survive. When that source ran out they turned their eyes upwards and, like so, they ended up purged in the name of peace and a chance for the city to move on.\n\nKara opened her eyes with a strange calm. There was nothing more she could lose in this world, but her life. Five years of senseless work in a secret forest potato garden rounded up in ashes and she herself was captured as an exotic beast to present to another senseless project of a surviving mind much larger than her own.\n\nIt was a summer rain, heavy and refreshing. The only thoughts that flooded her mind was how grateful she was to have something to put out the fire in the woods started by the police to burn all traces of her presence. There was something to cling on to, to fantasize about the return, to thank for the mercy. Glimmer of hope blinded her senses of being cold, wet and surrounded by people who were clinging to the little hopes of their own. People whom she would not fight for and people who would not fight for her either. Water soaked her clothes and hair and she welcomed every drop of it, ready to give up her life in accidental sickness. Casualty she completely redeemed if it meant that a little sprout would survive the fire. There was nothing else left.\n\nGreen eyes and long straight brown hair, how much would it be worth if buried in the ground or given up to flames? Somehow the worth was equal to a little hope. Little sprout that might survive and go on unnoticed, outliving the power that stomped around blindly destroying anything that crossed its path.\n\nOne cent. That is how much they would pay for a sprout in the market and that’s being generous.\n\nIt was only a matter of time when the world would catch up to her and force itself to change her path. It was only a fair exchange for 5 years of freedom. At least that’s what they said and there is no questioning their words. It’s either that or death. And yet she was alive. Empty, cornered, but alive. And staying alive was what she chose herself - the only choice that was left for her to make. The only choice that gave her a chance to return to that little grove in the forest.\n\nShe looked around for the first time to look into faces that surrounded her to try and find another soul that shares her pain. Her blind and irrational sense of loss of a bunch of potatoes. Maybe there was enough to feed this group for a month, but Kara would never let anyone eat them. She was selfish. She would go around the town, seeing starving children and yet refusing to share what she had. These people cared about something more than that, Kara did not have the right to compare her loss to theirs. She lost too little and yet everything. She wept silently and praised the rain for hiding it and giving her this brief moment all to herself.\n\nA tear slid down her face, warm and burning with salt, it made its way to her lips. She reached with her tongue to capture its taste. Mindlessly, almost breaking the point of insanity, Kara thought that it tasted sweet. The acidic and bland taste of polluted rainwater seemed to perfectly complete the sensation of bluntly salty tears. It reminded her of the taste of moose she killed for attempting to breach her garden and destroy her work. The beast was almost ten times her size, but it didn’t stop Kara. Life was the least of things she could lose that day. How funny that it meant nothing today, as she was held to the ground unable to do anything while being forced to watch it all burn. So justly helpless. Was she being saved from her own irrational attachments? Maybe it was the only way back to normal, the gratifying chance to redeem her worth. Maybe it was her chance to stop throwing her life away trying to protect something so worthless as potatoes. Chance to be worth more than one generous cent.","n":1},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"It was a gloomy day to start with a sunshine. When Kara saw clouds approaching from the south she didn’t think much of it. It only meant that her garden would need some aqueducts to get rid of excess moisture, but it barely was something worth worrying about. She sat in the midst of her little groove that she opened up to sunlight three years ago, as her little potato plantation outgrew its old little spot.\n\n- So yeah, I already told you about the Milligans. They are the worst at making a bargain, but I guess that bunny was quite a skinny one, - Kara lightly touched the closest plant, checking for any dust. She examined her fingers and clapped the dust off, - Well I guess it is a good time for a shower after all. My lucky day, I guess. Right, Persival?\n\nShe gently smiled and returned to sunbathing. The ground was pleasantly warm and Kara tried to enjoy every extra second of it being dry, before the storm hit. It could have taken a whole week for the ground to be as dry as it was today and Kara rarely allowed it to be. It was a special day afterall and, though it was fated to be cut short, there was a lot to tell.\n\n- You know, my parents would probably not be happy to know that I am out here with you. I bet I am breaking some big rules or something, not like I care, really, - She smiled and layed down on her back, letting the leaves briefly brush her hair before springing right back up to hide her face from the blinding sun, - I am not mad, not anymore at least. Not like they had a good plan for me anyway. Or do you think they did?\n\nKara listened intently to the silence, expecting some answer. Light wind ruffled the leaves of the forest, but the little garden was unmoved in its sheltered grove, - You are right, I shouldn’t overthink it. It’s not like I could do much, I would definitely not want to go down in mines. It’s dark and hot and you never know if you are going to spend your last few hours stuck suffocating. Probably with your friends. You definitely would not want to grow there, Vincent, - Kara focused on observing the underside of the leaves checking for any mites. It looked healthy, she only washed them last week, so the infestation should have stopped, - You know I never saw Rein after he left to work there. There have been so many accidents, they would never allow me to get anywhere close to those sights. Do you think they know the names of the corpses they take out? What is this?\n\nKara gently tore off a browning leaf from the plant close by bringing it closer to her eyes. It started to curl up on the edges, but overall looked healthy, - Teresa, could you just wait for two hours or so? I promise that even if it’s not going to rain I will make sure you get some water. It’s too early for you to go to hibernation, - Kara released the leaf and gently floated down landing on her cheek, before reluctantly sliding down to earth. She dropped her hand to the ground in tired motion and leaves ruffled in agitation.\n\n- No Bork, I am not upset with you. I just want to lay down in peace for once and I can’t chase away these stupid thoughts. Just let me be, I’m not in the mood today.","n":2},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"Kara remembered every moment before she was striped from her little heaven. How funny that she regrets having these little arguments with objects that don’t even have the capability to listen or answer. She knew that it all was just a game she played in her head, the only game that gave her life ephemeral importance. She knew that it would end some day, but she didn’t know that it would hurt this much. It shouldn’t have, that was the whole purpose of it.\n\nShe sat in the middle of the medieval looking cage. Not that hard to get out of since it served a more decorational purpose of exposing criminals, however even the slightest attempt would end up with a bullet. In your head if you are lucky, otherwise they will bring you back in health for more vivid execution.\n\nKara carefully glimpsed at the lock and quickly shifted to the closest human figure to avoid suspicion. Metallic with wooden frame, if she really wanted she could charge to break it. Useless action. There were two guards for every one criminal in the cage. It was a gamble to even try to choose death, so she looked into the face that was right in front of her. She recognised it and in that recognition was shock, confusion and even deeper regret that she ever knew.\n\n- Rein? - Her voice sounded desperately strong, in disbelief and uncertainty. It almost took all her strength to push those words out. There was nothing to gain from knowing for sure, but it would have been good to know. Figure shuffled begrudgingly, annoyed at weird disturbance and Kara let out a sigh of mixed relief. This was the last place she would want to meet her old friend. Though it would be nice to know that he didn’t die in the mines. What would they talk about? He had a little sister, they could talk about her. If she survived.\n\nWhat if it was him? Would he even remember her? Life separated them almost instantly, either of them could be dead by now. But if he didn’t remember, why did she? Was it because she was so stuck? Was he really her last best friend? If you think about it, he was the last one that she trusted for sure. Not now maybe, but back then for sure. How much did he know about the world by now? How deep could he have explored the abyss of the inevitable control of the state that governed them?\n\nKara looked away with disinterest. What could a miner and a girl from the slumps talk about? He was working and she was… Surviving? She wouldn’t call it that. She didn’t regret a second spent in the illegal forest garden that she cared for. Well maybe not the burning part, but Kara knew that she was happy. Selfish, alone, but happy.","n":3},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"- I told mom about Fluffer, - Little Kara looked down at the purring kitten with pain in her eyes. She kneeled down and reached out for a pet. It was a shame that she couldn’t take him back home.\n\n- Oh, I called him Huggins, - boy with dark hair and blue eyes uncomfortably shrugged. They found him together, so it doesn't really matter who named him.\n\n- So Fluffer Huggins it is then, - Kara smiled for a second before frowning, - We can’t take him home, right?\n\n- No, - Rein sighed. His fingers curled around tiny ears as a ginger kitten purred with ever increasing intensity.\n\n- I got him some milk though, - Kara took out a tiny bottle out of the pocket with milky substance, - Sorry, that was the only bottle I could find, mom would kill me if I took a plate for a stray cat. It is better than nothing.\n\nShe looked around hastily looking for any metal scrap then an idea struck her mind. She poured a tiny amount from the bottle on her palm.\n\n- Kara, what are you doing?! - Rein sprung to his legs, afraid that his friend would spill precious milk on the ground.\n\n- Don’t worry Rein, I saw my mom doing it with oil, - Kara stood very still as if performing a surgery. She dipped her finger into the milk puddle in her palm and it caught a tiny droplet, - Food is food. It will take longer, but he needs it now, - She carefully moved her finger to the kitten's muzzle and it quickly licked the milk of his fur. She repeated the motion two more times before Rein broke the silence again.\n\n- Well he won’t survive here alone, - Rein hesitantly looked at the bloodied cardboard and shifted his view on the road, - Doesn’t look like his mother is going to make it. I don’t even know if he will survive the night.\n\n- What if it’s a she? - Kara didn’t seem to be phased by the inevitable truth. Bearing the thought of what might come tomorrow somehow seemed irrelevant. Kitten clinged on to every drop of milk that she dropped on his muzzle and Kara could not focus on anything else in order to make sure that nothing was wasted.\n\n- I don’t know, i didn’t check, - Rein suddenly grew pink in embarrassment at the idea that their street is going to be home to a cat named Fluffer Huggins, - You were the one who called him Fluffer!\n\n- I guess she could be a Fluffgilda, - Kara finished the last drop and offered her palm to a kitten that quickly followed the scent of milk and started intensely licking it clean.","n":4},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"The cart was moving at a steady pace. Rain reluctantly dropped last drops as horison showed a clearing and a hint of sunlight slowly taking over again. They were approaching the central town of the area which was dwarfed by a giant concrete stadium talling above simple wooden buildings of the town’s administration.\n\nAs they entered the city the streets moved slowly, with people barely lifting their eyes to see what was passing by them. Every once in a while a random glance would linger for too long and the guards would quickly tell them to move along. Kara heard stories of grand executions performed by the greatest warriors of the state three months before their grand tournament as a gift of freedom from crime. Warriors with great mythical powers, born and raised to live and die for the glory of the country. Something about the power of gods and their gift to this world. Kara didn’t believe in much of it. Not like anyone came back from being captured or had any better theory. Gods were plentiful in the world and so were their values and motives.\n\nDid Kara believe in God? Not really, if it was her day to die today she would rather cease to exist and never set foot on this forsaken land ever again. Potatoes could survive without Kara, but she wasn’t sure if surviving without her garden was worth it or not. The absurdity of the thought amused her, maybe that’s why her heart didn’t stop the second she saw them all burn in flames. She had something left to reflect upon before passing on to the great nothingness. How merry was the thought that it was all soon to have an end.\n\n- Get out, this is your stop, - The cart suddenly stopped abrupting the fleeing thought and pulling Kara back to her body, clothed in drenched muddy scraps and sudden crawling soreness of sitting down in a suddenly uncomfortable position. The cold air filled the lungs like a muddy river water stirred by a sudden deep sigh as Kara stood up to her feet. She followed the crowd not really paying attention to the directions by the officers.\n\nThey were not the only ones. Multiple carriages started unloading, Kara didn’t even know where they came from. All she could see were dozens of people pouring out to the loading area, looking equally disoriented.\n\nThey were led through a hallway that ended in a bright light almost making Kara chuckle at the almost biblical reference. Is there a God at the end of a tunnel? Surely the creators of this structure didn’t think about such stupid details. Why would someone care about making the prisoners feel the relieving touch of divinity? They sure didn’t bother about these details when shooting down mobs in the mud and rolling their dead bodies with kicks into burial pits.\n\n- Surely, - Kara mumbled ironically, looking at the light in a slight hesitation. She wished her thoughts were false for a second, as the blinding rays slowly grew closer. It was amusing to believe that the next moment is going to follow regardless of her choice. It was even more so amusing to believe that it won’t.","n":5},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"- Fluffer Huggins! - Kara stepped to her yard and called out for her pet. Quiet thump landed somewhere from behind and the girl quickly turned around. Large tom cat jumped down from the pile of wooden scraps and Kara quickly rushed to greet her friend, - You my little hero, mom found a gift you left for us yesterday! She was so happy she even cried! - Kara dropped to the ground to hug her friend, - If you can, can you catch one for Rein too? Mom said that it was too small to share. Kara sat there for a second, hanging on to the fur and feeling how it was slowly warming up under her fingers.\n\n- Just be careful out there buddy, - She started crying, - I heard some cats are going missing, but you are smarter than all of them, right? - Kara shook at the thought of what happened to those cats and suddenly she realized a grave mistake she made a year ago. Who would have known that the supply line would shut down leaving their town stranded for the winter. Now Kara was back to square one. Fluffer Huggins might not survive the night outside.","n":6},{"chapter":"Prologue","text":"The light blinded Kara as she stared directly at its source. The sun shined like it always did, surrounded by dull blue fog. Kara almost could feel the mountain breeze awaiting for her ahead, but as her gaze dropped down it was a concrete coliseum wall and tens and hundreds of empty tribunes. Guards stopped at the entrance letting the crowd dissolve in the huge area. Kara didn’t stop looking around as she continued making her way to the center in amazement. When she stopped right in the middle she suddenly found herself standing alone with multiple guards pointing their weapons right at her as if she did something wrong. The rest of the crowd seemed to have stopped a long time ago.\n\nWhy didn’t they shoot? What was the instruction? Kara was the last person who entered the cart, maybe they instructed people before she arrived? Was she even supposed to be there? Kara looked intently at one of the guards. Straight into eyes, as if waiting for him to pull the trigger. There was no escape from this coliseum. At least no one lived to tell about it. People killed in the coliseum would be killed anywhere else. They were persecuted criminals and any contact with them was dangerous. Police made sure that streets were as safe as possible.\n\n- Sorry, - Kara clumsily shouted, once it was obvious that no one was going to shoot her. Guards twitched to aiming position for a second, before dropping their guns. Kara felt as her heart skipped a beat. Her actions seemed stupidly reckless. She knew a perfect way out. Scream, shout, disrupt the order. Combinations of all three would be easily achievable and highly effective at reaching the forever blissful embrace of death. Kara thought about it for a second, but nothing would come to her mind. She didn’t want to scream, that would hurt her ears. As for the shouting, nothing really came to mind as a good line to go out on. The most interesting was the order. Whom to go for first if nothing would be enough? They were all dead anyway after all.\n\nThought was abrupted by the loud voice.\n\n- Welcome to the criminal feast day! Among you, criminals, are the six chosen heroes to bring glory and peace to our state. They will surely end you all, but this year our heroes generously offered to spare those who believe they are innocent. Please raise hands and head to the exit where your case will be reviewed by state officials.\n\nBefore Kara could start contemplating her chances, people started moving. Silently and compliantly, ready to continue fighting for their innocence. Then the impatient ones followed, Kara looked in a straight disbelief. How many of these hypocrites truly believed there was a chance for a police officer to make a mistake. The chance that they would admit it.\n\nKara stared as a good third of the hundred people walked out the same way they walked in. As the last one of them escaped the view line there was a silence and then the guns fired. Kara almost jumped. But no one in the coliseum moved. It was over in a second. That could have been an easy death.","n":7},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"Potato show was a hit. 8 billion random combinations of thoughts and none of them were expected to carry the implication that this combination would be their last. And yet by pure chance it could have been.\n\n- Now my heroes, for that we revoke your godly gift of power, - The voice above sounded just and calm. No one even flinched. Kara looked around and caught the stare from the crowd. It was the same hooded boy. There was concern in his eyes, almost fear. The realization struck like a pinecone. It was the hit of emotion and then the feeling of ultimate defeat. None of these people knew who was a hero. None of these people were innocent. None but six. Kara looked like one as she was standing all alone in the middle. How did she end up there?\n\n- The blessing cannot be one sided, - The voice persisted. Kara just realized that it was female. Low, formal and yet the way she said the phrase left no doubt in girls mind, - For our country favors all of our citizens. Redemption, although, must be earned. Heroes, for the sin of discriminating upon personal choice, you will bring the criminal feast to the gods as a criminals. As someone who you decided to side with by giving them this choice.\n\n8 billion people, there are 8 billion people in the world. That’s what they taught Kara in school. How many people did Kara meet in her life? How would she even count? By heads or by faces? Or by how many of them she knew? People die and people are born. That’s why it’s 8 billion, always. Well, sometimes it drops here and there. But always stays close to 8. Did it stay at 8? Kara hasn't heard this number in a long time. She never asked the question whether that number ever changed.\n\nShe looked down at the ground deep in thought. She felt how more and more gazes from the crowd turned to her. Dark forest theory would suggest that she would be the first one to die in a carnage. Why would they teach that to kids? Extraterrestrial survival techniques. An interestingly weird read for a language project. People have been to space. Kara knew exactly what was about to happen.\n\n- Before we commence, there is a gift to you all, - woman in the speakers sounded excited. Like a kid who was excited to show something to her parents. It was almost as if she wasn’t speaking to the crowd in the pit. The air started buzzing as a swarm of small helicopters erupted from the tribunes carrying small parcels on the strings. Parcels dropped in front of each member of the crowd, many of them visibly carrying weapons. The one in front of Kara carried her lumberjack ax. What a way to knock those nails into the coffin, it was the largest weapon on the floor. Cleaned of all ashes and dirt, the only possession Kara was left with after that fire. Forty dollars on a good day. Was it worth fighting for?\n\n- Now my little criminals, let me tell you the rules to your redemption, - The voice suddenly became quiet and speakers slowly died down as on one of the tribunes appeared an olive skinned woman in a simple outfit but it almost shined as the sunlight lightly danced on its surface. Like a flower after summer rain. If she was among the crowd such an effect would be negated due to shadows of the people around.\n\n- Beautiful, - Kara watched the woman get on the pedestal that would be reserved for emperors. The only spectator truly present to the spectacle being a spectacle herself. To the only audience present, - Criminal sacrifice, am I right?\n\nKara spoke mindlessly, getting ready to die any second now. Did anyone hear her? If she is to fight, would she want to fight for the ax that laid in front of her? What would be the benefit of keeping this ax? She can always get one better.\n\n- Six heroes entered the pit, six heroes must emerge. As the heroes chose to fight for their redemption, they granted you a chance to fight for yours, - woman shouted from the pedestal. Her voice echoed off the walls and it seemed as if she was somewhere on the other side of the pit. To everyone, but Kara. For Kara she was everywhere. In every corner of the pit, suddenly she felt scared. She felt all 8 billion eyes focused on her. What did they want? What were they looking at?\n\nSudden impulse, almost an instinct, a muscle memory. Kara preemptively grabbed an ax and the parcel thumped to the ground. It was as if Kara felt the presence of the wolf in the forest. Thump struck her back to senses. There was something else in the parcel.\n\n- Now, - speakers spoke again with an olive skinned woman's voice.\n\nKara kneeled down and rested the ax on her shoulder.\n\n- Let’s start this annual criminal feast!\n\nHer hands rashly opened the parcel to reveal four pale yellow shapes inside.","n":8},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"- You know Persival, if I ever disappear, I think you are too spoiled to survive. I hope you are stocking up for this winter, - Kara laid down in the garden feeling the mud sinking into her shirt. She was exhausted after a long day of plowing out a large puddle of water, - I don’t know, you would have to grow legs or something. At least this way you would be able to run away like people do. If you really try, maybe you could even fight.","n":9},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"Potatoes, the damned parcel. Kara did not believe her eyes. They were personal belongings, not weapons. Kara raised her eyes on the people in the crowd. It was a massacre, people were swinging at each other in a cacophony of blows and a small mob was already rushing towards her armed with cutlery and instruments. There were no heroes among them.\n\nShe sprung to her feet and dodged a first attack, hitting a man in a checker shirt straight in the middle of the back with an ax like she would a wolf or a dog. He tumbled by her side after a swing. She grabbed the parcel and booked it to the least crowded area. She was a murderer, but she could have been murdered. Her heart pounded in her head as she heard the steps behind her. Humans cannot outrun a wolf.\n\nShe stopped and rapidly spun around swinging her ax blindly. Too early. Blade went inches away from the man's torso, as he stopped just in time. Humans are not wolves. The rest of the gang catched up to her and she chuckled as she counted seven of them. 8 if you would count the one laying with a cut open back.\n\n- So now what? - Kara stood menacingly, collecting all her courage to not show fear to the wild beasts in front of her. It was a fragile stalemate held by tiny fears of both sides. Men feared that Kara was a hero and she was ready for this fight more than they were. Kara feared that with every second passing the men would crack her little bluff and attack. She had to pick a side.","n":10},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"- You know it would be a real deal if you would be able to stand up for Teresa, - Kara twisted around to her belly, now being completely covered in mud. She was whispering now as through the undergrowth something big was making its way. Kara recognised the heavy footsteps of the moose. It was heading her way.","n":11},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"She swinged. Silently, rapidly and without hesitation. Like a cornered animal would do, she swinged the second time and felt a burning slash on her side. Deer do not attack from the back. Two men down and one girl hit. Only Kara knew this would not be the end of it. Kara sprung back and had to dodge two more men swinging at her with something in their hands.\n\n- Look, I solved the problem for you, - Kara tried to stand upright, but received a hammer to a rib, knocking the air out of her lungs.\n\n- Wait, let her speak, - Older man spoke up and hastily intervened and the men stopped to reflect on what just happened.\n\n- Now there are six of us, - Kara finally pushed out slowly recovering after a hammer blow, - I am just a forester, - The world pounded with screams. Three men down, five remaining and had no better weapon among them.\n\n- Ok, but I take the ax, - The man reached out his hand and Kara readily surrendered her weapon to him and he exchanged her a dagger.\n\n- Good deal then, - Kara tumbled a humble dagger and wondered how it ended up in her hands. It was the stupidest exchange of her life. How stupid it was that it was at the same time for her life. The difference would be thirty dollars. Kara could not but question if the lives of the men she recklessly slayed were worth the other ten.\n\nThe mob dissipated and now most of the crowd were playing out a weird version of a tag game. The five men moved forward and Kara unwillingly followed, though at a much slower pace. Two moments have passed before the man who carried the ax was slain. Kara wondered if she killed that one too by accepting the trade. A fight broke out, no one knew who was who, as they swung around trying to get to the ax. Kara retreated to the wall, feeling not in her best shape. Blood was dripping from her side, and she was walking almost aimlessly.","n":12},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"- Though now that I think about it, you could give Vincent a hard time. Afterall, I think he and Teresa will be great parents, - Kara chuckled to herself, imagining how Percival would be jealous of his sister's boyfriend, - Can’t wait to see you all bloom","n":13},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"No one was really trying to hit her anymore. She was holding on to her side trying to stop the blood, but for people around her fate was almost determined. Kara wasn’t fighting.\n\nShe stopped as she reached the wall. This was the end of her plan. She had no other ideas in her head, wondering yet again why she was still standing. Was it the damn four potatoes in the bag that gave her comfort in such puny existence? What was she clinging to? A moment? She reached out into the bag and picked out the biggest potato of the bunch. The one that she could never fail to recognise.\n\n- So you say we fight Percival? - Kara felt increasingly stupid talking to a root of a dormant friend. She looked up to the wall and turned around. There were maybe twenty people still scattered around the area. Six would survive. Her mood has changed. Still holding her side she quickly surveyed the survivors and found a hooded boy back to back with the man in his thirties. Maybe they were friends.\n\nKara slowly started moving towards them, suddenly gaining substance to her silhouette. She saw a woman readying a swing of an ax at the hooded figure. Kara’s ax. And just like that Persival was sent on his last flight and crushed into pieces. Woman collapsed right as the boy turned to notice her swing. As she fell down Kara would meet Reins eyes. There was no time to doubt it. Kara broke into a run as she pounced on the woman, nesting the dagger into her back.\n\n- Kara, - Rein sounded sorry. He could have been a hero, - Thanks.\n\n- Rein? - Kara suddenly realized how little she believed the coincidence. It was close to impossible. She looked for clues in the boy's eyes, but he did not seem to recognise the name and turned back to facing the combat. Who else could it be?\n\nShe ripped her ax from under the body and regretfully looked at the remains of Percival. She chose his death for him. Was it a fair exchange? A friend for a friend? Kara stood up and felt tired of questions. It wasn’t a time and place for them and she already made the choice. Now holding the same ax with, weirdly, a different intent. She looked around as she saw people running away. The weak links had to go if she was going to make a good team.\n\n- I have a minute, maybe two, - That’s how much Kara hoped to be able to move, but she was just a very hopeful teenager, not a medic, - Sorry, if I hit your friends, - She spoke to a boy and a man and without hearing their reply she booked for the closest target. It was a quick swing, but she definitely felt her side wobble as she delivered a hit. She felt her blood dripping down her leg as she struggled to gain her balance. She fought a black out right as she was knocked down to the ground by the woman who was chasing the man. Her ax was even bigger than Kara’s and she broke into a cold sweat as it dug into the ground right next to her arm. Woman tripped at the last second as the guns fired, unable to stop the motion.\n\nKara looked into frustrated eyes with a pure terror. She was looking at a straight up warrior who was happy to fight and kill. The sole reason why most people from the crowd didn’t all rush at Kara. It was because in the crowd they must have seen the giant battle ax drop in front of this beast. So there was one hero among them after all. Hate to wonder what happened to the rest.\n\n- Congratulations, all six of you just granted yourselves redemption and now may rise as heroes! - Woman on the pedestal started speaking yet again. Her voice was ever so lively as if the result pleased her beyond expectation. Kara stayed down as the warrior woman stood up visibly upset. Kara was alive and that means that at least one of the heroes died in the carnage.\n\n- It must be your lucky day, - angrily spitted out the woman on her way up.\n\nIt was her lucky day. Lucky enough to lose her best friend in a blood bath. Did potatoes bleed? Hundred or so people and one potato. Instructions only intended that only people had to die. Kara made the choice, Kara suffered alone for her mistake. No one else saw betrayal in that. It was only rational. Throw an object to save a friend. Hopefully the last one survived.\n\n- Are you going to lie down there all day, mighty hero? - the beast woman stared at Kara as her extended hand was hanging in the air waiting for a response. Kara wondered if she did it straight away. Did she not know that Kara wasn’t a hero? Could be, but that would mean that heroes didn’t get a say in the matter at all. They were just plunged into a bloodbath unprepared. Quite a sadistic way to initiate someone into their positions.\n\n- Is that a new word for a murderer? Call me Kara, - Kara let go of her ax and grabbed a reached out hand. She felt her fingers struggle to tighten, but, before she could get it right, a woman jerked her up right to her feet pulling her from under a corpse with a remarkable force, - Thanks.\n\n- Now my birdies, - olive skinned woman screamed in a more relaxed way from the pedestal. All speakers were off, - Let’s go, we have tons of most exciting work ahead! We are going to get even better powers!\n\nKara didn’t know where to go, but the beast woman knew for sure as she headed to the entrance to the pit and tugged Kara with her. Kara barely caught her footing as the force jabbed her to the side of a dead corpse. Hopefully the man is dead. She grabbed on to her side expecting one heck of a bumpy road as the beast ahead was merrily jumping over the bodies almost in a rush. One clumsy jump too many and Kara lost her footing and fell to the ground. Unphased beast grunted and jolted her back upright with barely a moment to catch balance before continuing the way.\n\n- Easy there, I am kind of hit, - Kara felt the pain shock coursing through all of her body paralyzing any attempt to resist. Legs moved almost freely, but anything above refused to cooperate, punishing any extra muscle movement with pain. In comparison, of course. Kara thought about just giving up and letting the women drag her intentionally numb body, but a thought of pain that it would cause kept her upright. There were weapons in the sand. Kara didn’t want to end up with a dagger in the hip. Though at the moment she really didn’t know why. Was it the fact that she didn’t want to die or the fact that she didn’t want to die in even greater pain? That’s right, it was the four potatoes in the parcel. Now three. Still enough to start a garden, but without Percival.\n\nThey left the sun behind as they exited the pit, where the woman finally let go of Kara’s hand. Legs barely managed to catch Kara’s fall to the ground, but not without the help of the now released hand. The sudden sensation of freedom almost made Kara turn around and run, but her wounds took precedence and kept her in place.\n\n- Thanks again, I guess, - she tried to gather her strength to stand without an arm on the ground, but muscles felt weak and almost concussed. She looked up and saw two men without military uniforms standing in front of her and the rest of the heroes were slowly making their way to the exit. Kara used that moment to catch a breath.","n":14},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"The sound of steps now was accompanied with a light grunting. Moose was following some scent. Did he smell potatoes? Kara squeezed the ax in her hands and started crawling up towards the ledge. As long as she didn’t sound any bigger than a bunny, moose would not pay attention to her. She made her way all the way up and sat ready in the bush. What happened next was a surprise to forest peace. Kara never fought a moose before.\n\nSo in a jolt of energy she swinged as hard as she could, reaching as high as her strength would allow. She hit its chest and her hands slipped from the handle scratching her palms on the splinters. Moose jumped in shock away, but soon enough turned around to face the attacker. Kara instinctively backed out and regretted it instantly. Moose didn’t back down as the ax was slowly losing its hold to flesh. As soon as the moose shaked of the annoying tool it charged Kara as she ducked back behind the bush, booking it for the gorge. Ledge was an easy terrain for her to tumble over, but not for the moose. In a wild charge moose plowed through the bush, losing it’s footing and somersaulting down bringing Kara down with him. Kara got stuck in mud half way down, under the pressure of a moose rolling over her entire body. She didn’t look to see where the moose had landed. She knew exactly what she would do to him regardless.\n\nScrambling to her feet, Kara booked it back up on the ledge and retrieved the ax. The shuffling behind her suggested that the moose got up on his feet again. She could hide out until he left, but he was wounded and trampling her potatoes. Task seemed easy in the heat of the moment, moose meat would pay nicely for a new ax.\n\nShe stalked the edge of the ledge. As soon as she could see the head of the potato ravager she charged in a head on attack, jumping her blow straight to the target. Reckless, but proven efficient. Moose rarely need to deal with attacks from above, maybe that’s why an enraged mammal turned body straight into Kara to meet her with his horns ready. Ax connected right in the middle of the skull, crushing through it with just enough force to hit the vital organ. It was much tougher than Kara expected. Motion continued and she felt the horn jolting her to the side knocking her right out of mid air and straight to the ground, trampling the potato overgrowth. Ax got stuck in the skull for good.\n\nKara laid on her back hearing moose collapse over more potatoes and kicking the ground with last pulses of his nervous systems shutting down, - Oh, shut up Bork! You go and try to kill a moose.","n":15},{"chapter":"Chosen Heroes","text":"Kara wondered what saved her that day. The fact that she killed people or the fact that she had an ax to do so. Was there a chance for her to survive barehanded? She could run faster that way. There was no point for her to kill anybody, unless he was a hero. But why would she want to take his place? Kill a hero for a promise of power? Why would she even need that power? She has already defeated moose once.\n\n- Kara, are you alright? - the man in a neat suit asked as if he knew Kara for years now, but only intended to politely check in. There was no real concern in his voice, but Kara already hated the fact that he knew her name. She felt the rest of the heroes drilling her with their eyes. Hooded boy the most. He survived, Kara forgot to remark that as a weird achievement. She hesitantly looked around seeing that most of them carried a wound or a blood stain of some sort. Yet only Kara seemed to struggle with hers. Everyone was slightly glancing at her, but him.\n\n- I guess it could have been worse, - Kara made a direct effort to stand up and barely managed to fight the pain, - Just an annoying combination, - broken rib and slash on the other side. Maybe a cracked hip. Nothing lethal if she doesn’t push her luck any further.\n\nThere was a weird feeling of safety ever since Kara got the title of a hero. She didn’t even flinch when the man in a suit proceeded to touch her side. A blow of a warm chill passed through her hand, still desperately holding the wound closed. Like a warm water to the freezing skin. Pain subsided and Kara did not feel the cut with her fingers anymore. It was the legendary hero power that everyone talked about. There were 8 heroes in the hall. Her legs felt limb as she rocked away in a shocked disbelief. There had to be six, will they have to fight again?\n\n- Stay away from me, - reaction was late and there was nowhere to go. Voice sounded more spiteful than anything, - Sorry, I meant thanks, - Kara didn’t know what to do with the energy that was returned after the release of the looming fear of blood loss and exhaustion. She wondered if she sounded silly to the rest of the heroes.\n\n- Sooner you get used to it, the better, - Man sounded impatient, as he returned to his spot without giving her another glance, - As sad as it is to admit, two of the selected heroes didn’t make it out of the pit. However, that also means that two of you earned your place on your own, - he looked over each of the heroes and moved on, - My name is Taric and this is your second coach Victorian, - they wore the same black suits, but looked completely different. Taric was a grounded man with a weathered intent of being here and tall Victorian looked like he just came by to check out new source material.\n\n- Yes, yes, this and that, - Victorian rolled his eyes, - They can learn all about it tomorrow. Sooner we got them through the procedure the better, Tarik, - Victorian patted on his partner's shoulder and Kara noticed that his hand was shining in pale blue hue in the light of dim lamps. It almost didn't look human, - Let me go and then you will have them all to yourself, - Victorian gestured with his hand command to follow and Kara moved with everyone. It was the last day of summer.","n":16},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"Kara always wondered what gods the heroes believed in. If the gift of powers was bestowed on them by a godly force, did it mean that all heroes believed in one god? If yes, she never heard about that one. Discrimination upon religion was eliminated as illegal propaganda. Government refused to compromise for power with some fictitious characters from an old book. Even if god’s children did ever walk among mortals, they would stand no chance against modern heroes. And none of the heroes were the children of gods. Unless they actually believed in it, but everyone has the right to that.\n\nHallway seemed never ending to Kara. They climbed the stairs up and then down to what looked like a medical center.\n\n- So I heard this procedure is quite a ride, - the man in his thirties, now one of the heroes, caught up to Taric and Victorian, - Maybe you can tell us a bit more while we walk? - Kara couldn’t tell if he was serious or just friendly.\n\n- Yes, it can be quite painful if you choose it to be, - Victorian almost smiled with pride. Taric sighed with annoyance, - If pain is something that you truly wish, you will be granted plenty of it, - Victorian chuckled softly remembering something in his own head. It was almost as if he knew someone who would crave pain and mock him. Or her. Kara hoped that it wasn’t it.\n\n- Well that sounds ridiculous, - man in his thirties chuckled at Victorian, - Who would wish for that? - him and Victorian exchanged an amused look as everyone stopped.\n\n- Now, there are six rooms here, - there was indeed. Kara just finished counting the moment Taric announced it, - Pick one and enter. We will meet after the procedure ends, - he gestured at the doors and left the room.\n\n- Rude as always, - Victorian rolled his eyes and smiled at the heroes, - Don’t worry they are all the same, it’s just for private space, - he moved out of the way, waiting for everyone to pick their door.\n\nKara walked straight and had to scooch over from the third door that she initially picked. Beast woman has beaten her to it. That left her at the fourth door. She thought about switching to fifth for good luck, but the hooded boy already grabbed the handle to open that one too. It didn’t matter. Kara glanced at Victorian for the last time and caught the man in his thirties standing by him asking something. He caught her stare and smiled politely, so she entered the room.","n":17},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"- You know what power a true hero would have? - little Kara spoke to Rein as they were walking down the sidewalk after school. They were chuckling about the latest movie they watched in school. Teacher asked them to pick a hero and describe his best skills, - Save anyone he wanted with a sole power of will. Even from the claws of death.\n\n- And cure all diseases, - Rein caught up to the answer excited to add on to the details.\n\n- Of course! It would be as if he was saving them from the disease! - Kara clenched her fists in an ax grip and swished the air as if it was the pneumonia that Reins sister suffered from.\n\n- And do it in style with a magical dance, - Rein laughed as he imagined the battle of his own.","n":18},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"The room was bare. A table with a glass of water and a medical couch with a simple pillow. Kara drank the water and sat down waiting for the nurse. Two minutes later she heard the last door close.\n\nFrom the world's perspective she was just a girl from the street, when her parents died the state revoked their property and sent Kara to the orphanage, which was easy enough to escape unnoticed. Kids there got picked up every day by good people, sometimes on a pure whim. Kara ran away after one night there. She looked for her parents and learned where they went, so she decided to do what she never got to do. Live like she wanted somewhere in the woods, with no rules to be broken. There she saw a potato plant for the first time. Was it such a big crime? Did they know that she wasn’t growing these potatoes for food? And technically they grew themselves, Kara just assisted slightly.\n\n- What did you do to them, Vincent? - Kara bursted in a teary laughter as she realized that she was finally alone for the first time, - That is so ridiculous! I wasn’t selling you guys! Unless you guys are some criminals, there was literally no reason for the arrest! How did they even find us?!\n\nMath didn’t add up. With a hunting license any meat could be sold and everything else could go under the counter with not much of a consequence. The product would be burned, but nothing more. There was a demand for it and people could always hunt for their own food. Who knows, maybe some kid just needed a rabbit for a science project and you would catch it with purest samaritan intention. It just didn’t make sense. Kara didn’t break any law when her potato garden was burned to ashes, but how stupid it was that it looked like she did. Illegal farming of potatoes. Hunting was acceptable with some seasonal changes. However, owning a farm of any sort required a license. She had no license for potatoes. For the moose yes, but not for potatoes. It wasn’t food for her.\n\n- Now you can rest heroes, hope you are ready to get your powers, - The soft voice sounded from some speaker in the room and Kara felt a weird smell of mint. The room must have been filled with some gas, but Kara did not hear anything actively pumping it. Maybe something in the room smelled like mint and Kara just noticed.\n\nNext thing she remembered was how soft the pillow felt after a sudden fall. Kara was blacking out and feeling a feverish pain on her side as she recognised that she landed on her broken rib. She tried to scream in pain, but a bruised muscle got struck by a cramp and must have driven her into a shock of some new sort. She curled and twisted on the couch trying to find the right stretch position, all while her mind was fighting the darkness creeping into her eyes. What was Kara fighting for?\n\nThe door swung open and doctors must have rushed in, one of them stretched her out on the couch and the jolt of pain sent Kara into a knock down.","n":19},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"Kara saw a dream, a nightmare to be precise. People in the street were burning the fire and twisting Fluffer Hugging on the stick above it. There was nothing she could do, he was dead. She woke up in a cold sweat after seeing it. She was in her room with the lights off.","n":20},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"Kara opened her eyes as she was being locked into some armchair. She felt no pain in her rib and she wasn’t quite sure how long she was out for. She felt surprisingly calm, right until the moment she started looking for her parcel and couldn’t feel it in her hands anymore.\n\n- Where is my parcel? - Kara felt as if the whole ground was spinning around her. She didn’t know how to return to that room and she didn’t know where she might have dropped them along the way. As she started twitching in agitation she felt something sting her wrist from the armchair.\n\n- It is safely stored, - Victorian was standing by the wall as a doctor was preparing something on the computer, - Sorry, usually we don’t show this part, but apparently Tarik wasn’t watching the screen as tentatively. Can’t really blame him, I thought you were done for after I saw that stab too.\n\n- Are you sure it’s safe? - Kara felt her body relax into the chair.\n\n- Of course, my dear. It is a simple procedure, really. It is only as bad as you imagine it to be, - Victorian replied readily.\n\n- I mean the potatoes, they should be properly stored for the next Spring, - Kara guessed that she was still a bit drowsy after the battle. Why would she ask about it right now? - Sorry, they are quite special for me, - Kara scrambled to recover, feeling a second sting of the needle.\n\n- Don’t worry, we know, - Victorian stood patiently as Kara started drifting away. How would they know?","n":21},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"There was something Kara could do to prevent the imminent demise of their street companion, given he was still alive. She jumped off the bed in a feverish rush and headed straight outside.\n\n- Fluffer Huggins! - She screamed in a hushed voice and waited. A minute has passed, - Fluffer, come out! - She was insisting now. Tom cat waited another ten seconds before reluctantly exiting his regular hiding spot. Kara rushed to him and hugged tight, - You are giving me a heart attack, buddy.\n\nPurring commenced almost immediately and Kara felt her anxiety dissipate into night air. Only now she realized that she was still in her nightgown and if her mother would see her she would get told off for hugging a dusty cat. Kara was about to lift Fluffer Hugging off the ground and bring him inside, but she feared what would happen if she did. She would never be able to hide Huggins in the box. He was a live animal, not a toy. Plus nighttime is his time to find food, no point in safety if they could not feed him. They could run away together into the woods. Kara would live by hunting and provide them both with plenty of food. It would be cold and tough in the winter, but at least there would not be hungry people searching for an easy meal. Kara could protect her fur ball from animals, but people would not tolerate seeing their lives being outvalued by one of a cat. The situation was looming over menacingly. She could risk it all for Fluffer and dedicate her life to his salvation or she could let fate take its course with a tiny chance that a miracle would save him every day. She was scared to make the right choice.\n\n- Sorry Huggins, can you please stay safe and fight for your life with all you have? - Kara was tearing up. Hope was never her greatest strength, the world around changed fast as people were growing more angry and desperate. She would not be surprised if someone in the city would disappear without any trace of existence. Their relatives would go around asking where they went and the answer would be obviously deceiving. Police could take anyone away without the need to justify their choice. Police, however, would never touch cats or rats. Only people did, - I will miss you very much if you disappear.","n":22},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"Kara opened her eyes again, sitting in the same armchair. She was comfortable enough to stay motionless, as she slowly recognised the room. Victorian was sitting in front of her visibly frustrated.\n\n- Do you remember your name? - A concerned look on his face confused her. She was feeling great and her mind was clear to the point of suddenly realizing that she killed a total of 5 people in the arena. Four with an ax and one with a dagger.\n\n- Yes, Kara Toham, - jolt of a cold breeze passed through her body as she spoke her name. It was like something was grappling with every cell of her body. The sensation stopped as she finished speaking.\n\n- Well that's progress, - Victorian brushed his hair in some sort of relief. Kara didn’t understand his frustration.\n\n- Was I out for long? - Every word seemed to send pulses through her body, like a clockwork. It wasn’t unpleasant, but was getting more annoying with every new pulse. It seemed to be easier to stay silent.\n\n- Well, this is our fifth conversation like this, - Victorian was being vague, - Now tell me, what power do you want as a hero? - Kara vaguely remembered this conversation, but wasn’t sure if it happened in this room or not. No, the question was definitely different the last time.\n\n- You mean, - Kara hesitated to finish a sentence and felt the pulse of an anticipated word boil inside her spine ready to explode if not released. She panicked, - something, - pulse struck her body like an ant swarm and she could already feel the next one getting prepped up, - useful?\n\nVictorian placed his face into his arms for a second. He looked like he was fighting some inside anger as he thought carefully about the next question.\n\n- Looks like we haven’t moved much after all, - Kara attempted to chuckle, but the pulses ringing through her body advised against it.\n\n- Interesting that you care, - Victorian looked up in tired unhopeful surprise, - You are impulsive, insane, unpredictable. And for what? It’s not like you want anything at all. I am tired of answering the same stupid questions about potatoes. It’s not like you would ever tell us as much as which one of them is Vincent.\n\n- I don’t care, I was being polite, - She wasn’t and with that the last pulse seemed to burn a hole in her chest as she fought the restraints to curl up in pain. She couldn’t scream.\n\n- Remarkable stupidity, I don’t even know which one of those was a lie, - man relaxed back into his chair, - Maybe your power is to lie to yourself endlessly? I thought Tarik was insane to torture you here for so long, but now I see that you are just hopeless. Who in the world lies about wanting a potato garden?\n\n- I don’t want it, I need it, - Kara tried to correct Victorian, but suddenly noticed a weird absence of a heartbeat in her chest. The pain was probably excruciating, but she almost didn’t feel it as she noticed a hand on her shoulder. It was the same chilling warmth that seemed to keep her stable, as the pain slowly subsided until she felt normal again.\n\n- Sorry, Kara, just a bit more, - Taric was in the room this whole time, standing silently in her blind spot. If he was a wolf she would be dead, - Victorian let’s step outside and let Kara rest for a second, - he let go of her shoulder and walked to the door. Victorian said nothing as he stood up and compliantly followed.\n\nNow that she was finally alone she could hear a quiet fire crackle behind her, so quiet that it could have easily been there from the start. It almost breathed like an animal would do.\n\n- You know it would be nice if I could see you, - Kara spoke freely, feeling completely helpless against whatever beast stood behind her. The restrains held her tight and she could only look straight. She wondered how many times she actually saw this beast to feel so calm in its presence. It just felt familiar.\n\nFor a second the room exploded with flames, but Kara felt as if she wasn’t truly there to feel the heat of the flames.","n":23},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"Kara stood in the middle of the overgrowth looking at the weirdly bright green leaves of the potato plant. She only saw pictures of it once or twice before, there was only one way to know for sure. Kara got to her knees and started digging. There was no doubt in it, there were potatoes in the ground. It was a fascinating discovery, no more than that. Girl didn’t eat potatoes. The thought of eating what she just found was almost criminal in her mind. The puny vegetable wasn't even native to these places, it must have been dropped by some campers who visited the bonfire sight just twenty or so yards away. Who knows, maybe someone threw it at a friend during a silly exchange. Maybe they threw it to scare a wolf. They didn’t pick it back up, so it stayed there. Saved from being devoured by a reckless action of his predators. How lucky for this potato it was that wolves do not eat potatoes. Especially not the ones that fly through the air like rocks.\n\n- Well, I guess that makes two of us misfits in the forest, buddy, - Kara looked around. She was still quite close to the city. She had to keep going.","n":24},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"The shape appeared in front of her out of flaming air landing its paws on the floor almost without a sound. It looked like it was made of some light chunky clay. Kara stared into the shape of its head and saw two animated holes where the cat eyes were supposed to go. Deep and dark. They looked at Kara with a blank expression, as if she wasn’t even in front of it.\n\n- Whatever this is, it’s pretty messed up, Victorian, - Kara sounded absolutely terrified. She now saw perfectly why these sessions didn’t go well all of the other times. It was Fluffer Huggins. Giant, burning and somehow not dead. Kara started convulsing in an attempt to get free, but to no avail. The door to the room shot open and Taric rushed to Kara as the creature angrily roared and bursted into even more intense flames preparing some sort of attack. Suddenly all sounds of fire disappeared and Kara only saw this big cat spit out a flaming ball that crushed into some sort of invisible wall engulfing the entirety of the view to the other side of the room with fire.\n\n- Kara, calm down, - Taric touched her shoulder again and her whole body stopped as if paralyzed, - It's the spirit you summoned, it will not hurt you, - Beast did direct his attack on Taric, but Taric was the only one really moving.\n\n- I know that, - Kara felt her chest burning again, but there was no way she could react to it. How did she know that? - He was attacking you, right?\n\n- Don’t worry, Victorian knows what he’s doing, - Taric sounded tired, but content. The beast reappeared on the other side of the invisible wall as the flames died down. Kara noticed how empty the room was, - Now you should calm down.\n\n- Don’t want to, - Kara looked at the beast behind the wall with weird curiosity, - You said it’s my spirit, why does it look that way? - Talking suddenly was easy as the pulses became more and more familiar.\n\n- Well that you ask yourself, - Taric patted her shoulder, - I would ask you to tell us, but last time you lied it almost broke out, - man shrugged his shoulders, - You really need some boundaries, if you want to get out of this room.\n\nKara felt red in her cheeks. How many times she got stuck in the same embarrassing situation and didn’t remember about it? How much did she tell them? She knew one thing she never would, but what about the rest? Why couldn’t she remember any of it?\n\n- How long have I been here, Taric? - Kara felt as the flames on the giant cat grew stronger. She had to get out of the room. Whatever circus they were playing out here waiting for the best shoot had to end, it was stupidly infuriating. Should have been infuriating.\n\n- Calm down, being angry will just cause another reset. It’s been three weeks, - Taric sounded concerned, but truthful.\n\nKara did not like that answer. The other side of the wall got engulfed in the flames and a giant cat reappeared behind Taric with a low growl. Man took a step forward and turned around with a concerned expression. Kara finally saw his face.\n\n- Well at least now I see you, - she felt surprisingly calm, considering the fact that the flaming beast was right behind her casting flickering shadows on the walls, - Hard to stay calm when you can’t move or see the face that you are talking to.\n\n- Kara, we have been through it before. You can’t defeat us, - Taric sounded ready for the attack, but they already said that this procedure is completely safe. She never had a reason to attack them. Why would she?\n\n- I would ask how many times I tried, but I think I know the answer better than you do, - she felt a sting of the needle, - I’m more interested in how many times I burned the entire room before you called in Victorian, - she felt her body dozing of, - twenty one minus five. Sixteen times? You are quite insane yourself.\n\nLast pulses run down through her body as Kara now was only able to stare straight ahead. She didn’t hear the flames anymore.","n":25},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"- Oh my god, Kara, don’t look, - Rein stepped suddenly into her eyesight, covering something from it with his hands, - It’s a dead cat.\n\nKara grunted in displeasure, but looked away. Dead animals were never something that sparked interest in her mind. It was just sad, that's all, - Oh common Rein, I am not that impressionate, - She stood still inspecting a random dandelion sprouting out of the cracked pavement. Rein moved ahead to inspect the area.\n\n- There are kittens, - Rein reached into the dirty box and took out a dirty kitten with an orange pelt, - Well, there is one that looks alive still, - he presented the dusty furball to Kara.\n\n- He will die alone, - cold truth pierces the mind like water. It was just a fact.","n":26},{"chapter":"The Power","text":"- Well this is ridiculous, - Victorian entered the room in a fury, - It started to adapt against us, Kara you better get yourself together.\n\n- I hope you realize that she can’t answer, - Taric must have dusted his suit, as Kara heard a slight clap on the fabric. Maybe it was something else. It’s not like she expected to remember anything.\n\n- Of course I know that, I triggered it myself, - Victorian stopped by the chair and kicked it with spite, - She is a smart one, she will figure it out. Rest of the group had a three week head start in training, if they can’t survive her fits we should really be looking for other material anyway. And if she gets killed, well, good riddance!\n\nKara listened, unable to react. She was glad she couldn’t, Fluffer Huggins would not like the last sentence. She wondered how many times they had to replace heroes before the actual tournament. No one ever talked about that. Heroes always participated in criminal feasts, but rarely their identities would be known before the tournament. Funny how no one ever thought that heroes could die in training. Kara simply didn’t care.\n\n- Get her packed up and sent to the polygon. We are done here, - Victorian stormed out of the room. Taric followed without a word of objection. Kara liked the outcome quite a bit too. Well at least before the light shut down again. She could have fallen asleep.","n":27},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"Kara didn’t see any dreams. When she woke up she felt herself in the bed, so nicely tucked that Kara almost jumped out to get ready for school. That’s right, it’s her senior year. It’s the start of fall semester. Almost. The sensation was interrupted by a sudden realization that Kara lived in the woods. Quite comfortably at that, but this bed was definitely alien to her scenery.","n":28},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"- Sir, Rein will not come today to class. His father died in the oil rig accident, - Kara hated the fact that she had to say it out loud. These accidents were quite uncommon lately, but more terrific by the day.\n\n- Well, I hope soon we won’t even need this profession at all soon, - Teacher wanted to sound sorry, but brief pause gave his flaws away, - Thank you Kara, now sit down.\n\n- Easy for you to say, - Kara sat down looking at the chalkboard. Barely anyone in the room had a good meal for weeks now, insensitive comments here and there were expected. No one really had the energy to fight, so they left a lot of open statements open to misinterpretation. It would have been better if Kara stayed silent. Not like the teacher had energy to care that another student went missing for a day.\n\n- Does anyone remember how plants contribute to the water cycle? - Teacher started the class. Kara knew the answer, but her hand didn’t rise. No one wanted to answer, the teacher would go and correct or repeat them anyway. Waste of energy.","n":29},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"The room burst into flames as Fluffer Huggings appeared out of thin air. Bedding caught fire almost instantly as Kara jumped out of the spreading fire’s way. Whoever was stupid enough to give her this luxury for sure would frown upon what happened to their efforts. The fire alarm went off and in a matter of seconds the room was soaking wet. Fluffer Huggins stood still emotionless, as the drops of water evaporated upon touching him filling the room with a somehow cool fog. Kara didn’t feel the heat of the flames at all.\n\n- Ok Fluffer, new house rule, - Kara stood up still wobbly on her feet as if she hasn't used them for a long time. The sensation was so startling that she had to grab on to a chair as her legs gave up on waking up, - Don’t set the house on fire.\n\nGiant tom grunted, turned to Kara and sat down. She was glad it wasn’t their first rodeo, otherwise she would probably run away instantly. How weird that she only saw him once before. Well, she remembered only that once.\n\n- I know, it sucks Fluffer, - Kara straightened up feeling all stiff muscles unpack from the three week slumber. She was surprised that they didn’t feel weak at all, just a little drowsy. She sighed and walked up to the door, still in her nightgown. Well, she assumed that now it was hers.\n\nThere seemed to be a commotion in the hallway. People were grunting and walking by as if everything was normal, beside the obnoxious ring of the fire alarm. Kara tried to open the door, feeling the lack of oxygen in the room. It smelled like wet fire. Kara wondered if that’s how she will remember the scent of a wet cat from now on. Like swampy burned potatoes.\n\nThe door was open. The steam rushed into the corridor as Fluffer Huggings followed Kara outside. She coughed lightly at the smell of fresh air chilling her lungs. It didn’t feel cold, it was more of a minty sensation. The corridor had a long window that curled around the wall opening the view to a large arena maybe even bigger than the capital’s coliseum. Kara stumbled her way to the light and took a closer look at where she was. It was a giant stadium with multiple sections. Nine to be precise. State Novem held the highest number of hero survivors and so it took up the spotlight section, decorated by gold and black webs of ornaments. On a fresh bright blue color. It looked like this for a long time now. Their heroes would win often with minimal losses, but never managed to save all six. Must have been quite the bad luck. It looked really sad too, their compilations would usually come up with good stories to go with it. If not for the stupid favor dagger given to the other team. Slipped and fell into fire. Bravely offered his team to eat him to save them from poison. Last one was kind of sick, but his power did make him a healing gingerbread man. Poor man was obsessed and suffered anyway. He lost his mind after he realized he would never be human again. Kara shivered. It was twelve years ago, she was maybe six back then. She remembered giggling at almost cartoon-like features of the man that jumped around with his friends. She didn’t even know that he was dead back then.\n\nShe must have stood there for a long time examining the area. She heard a nervous shuffle on the ground, it stopped right by Fluffer Huggins. Kara heard the low growling.\n\n- Can you move him a bit? - voice sounded shorter than Kara expected, - I need to go through this corridor.\n\n- Sorry, - Kara panicked as she turned around and saw Fluffer Huggins growling at a short man that was beginning to look visibly concerned, - Fluffers, calm down and let him through? - Kara wasn’t sure if the spirit understanded the commands, she didn’t really do it before. She just knew that she might be stuck watching over her back to see what this cat was doing. Probably for the rest of her life. Potentially short one.\n\nTom cat compliantly retreated closer to Kara opening the clear gap for the short man. He looked like Tolkien's hobbit.\n\n- Sorry, where are we supposed to go? - Kara had a feeling that the man was one of the chosen heroes of her state, his face did look familiar. Shape shifting was quite common among the hero powers. Sometimes shifts became permanent. Sometimes it could even cause a retirement among surviving heroes.\n\n- I don’t know, did they say that you join us today? Taric said that you might need some time to stabilize, - he briefly looked at Kara. She wondered how many days, - My name is Haderach, - Kara wondered why he introduced himself, but remembered that he must have been one of her teammates.\n\n- Kara Toham, - she reached out her hand and they shook it. Fluffer Huggins chirped lightly and shook letting the excess water evaporate from his flaming fur. The corridor filled with fog. It took a second for it to dissipate, but Kara felt Haderach rushing off and covering his face, - Sorry? Are you ok?\n\n- Can you not control that thing? - Haderach struggled to talk through the suddenly very damp air. Kara looked at the flaming tom cat and realized that his flames looked twice as big.\n\n- He’s a cat, he does what he wants, - Kara felt uneasy saying these words. Fluffer Huggins never disobeyed her. She just couldn’t predict him and he did act impulsively. She could have predicted that he was wet, but he wasn’t a real cat. The water didn’t put out his flames either, so he isn’t real fire, - I called him Fluffer Huggins and that’s about all I know about it for sure.\n\n- Well that’s cool, - Haderach was holding his face, visibly red, - Do you heal?\n\nKara thought that the question was stupid. Heroes powers were unique and hers were a totally unpredictable cat thing. Its healing just didn’t compute with total destruction in her head, - No, I don’t think so. I don’t know, I just met Fluffers maybe yesterday.\n\n- Well here is a crash course on how to check if you do, - halfling approached Kara and took her arm and placed it on his cheek. It felt surprisingly burned. Kara didn’t feel any heat in the room, she only felt it on Haderach.\n\n- My roots and leaves, you are quite burned, - Kara felt a weird tingle in her chest. She didn’t usually speak to adults like that. She must have acted on impulse given the man was quite short and too lean to be a midget, - I’m really sorry, - it was weirdly disgusting to touch burnt wet skin, but it would be rude not to try to fix it. Haderach looked pretty convinced she could do just that. She felt a slight burn on her arms and the skin under her hand seemed to move. It was a soft orange glow.\n\n- Well, look at that, - Haderach smiled and clapped on Kara’s side, - Already being almost useful. If you could save the time and energy you have wasted fixing your mistake you would have nailed it, - she couldn’t tell if he was being helpful or sarcastic. It sure sounded helpful, he did say that she is making progress. She really needed that after being called a failure for three weeks. Well, for two days. Well, for twenty minutes she remembered. She could have sworn she was in the coliseum yesterday. Memories were a blur as they rushed through her head searching the reason why she was here.\n\n- Give me a second, - She returned to the room leaving Fluffer Huggins with Haderach. Kara looked at the chair and sure thing potatoes were lying there all wet in a neat hip bag, - No no no no! We need to get you dry! - She grabbed the bag and fastened it around her waist. It was around then she realized that she was still wearing that grayish simple nightgown. Whatever else she might have had was probably somewhere in the closet. She checked and sure thing it was, - I might need a minute!","n":30},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"Kara walked for a long time. Hour, maybe two. Forest seemed to be a fascinating place that she never explored alone. She wished Rein would be able to come with her, but deep inside she knew that it would be different if he could. There was a weird serenity in being completely alone. There was nothing in this forest that would not hurt her if provoked. Step into the wrong territory and get jumped by a cougar. Make too much noise of distress and attract the wolves. Hit a tree and get a pinecone to a cranium. She did plan to survive there alone, with Fluffer Huggins. She did explore some options with Rein last summer when they just found Fluffers.\n\nShe stopped by the river suddenly realizing that it was the same one that ran through her town, only now it was much smaller and completely wild. It was clean, untouched by hands ever since it left the ground as it has evaporated into the skies. Like the potato was tossed back into the wild to grow on its own, this water had escaped the earth only to rain down back on it. Kara loved how calm it felt. She could have stayed here, but water attracts insects and makes too much of a noise. Kara would not be able to hear things coming from behind. She can always come and visit.","n":31},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"It took Kara a total of maybe thirty seconds to change into dry clothes, but the hip bag left a wet stain on the red t-shirt. Maybe she could stay closer to Huggins to dry it up, but it could damage the potatoes. She walked out of the room with a high ponytail and a smile like she would wear in the school.\n\n- Are you ready? - Haderach looked like he was waiting only because Huggins would not let him leave, - You know this cat of yours is kind of aggressive.\n\n- Realy? He was nothing but nice to me so far, - Kara felt an umph of doubt in her chest. Stability of this creature was nothing, but questionable. If Kara wasn’t immune to his fire, she could have been dead. Maybe Huggins just gave up after some point. Plotting some form of revenge for her resilience to his destructive power, - I bet others have no problems relying on their powers by now.\n\nHaderach thought for a second, almost as if he was holding back some hurtful comment. Kara wondered what it was, - Well, it is a learning curve at first. They don’t exactly give much time to get into gears here. But, I guess, you got a good head start. Even if you can’t control it yet.\n\nIt was nice to have a calm conversation for a change. Ever since Kara left the forest there has been nothing but stress. For three weeks, she had to continue reminding herself that whatever happened wasn’t yesterday. Though the memories of fire did associate more with Fluffer Huggins now. She didn’t want to forget about what happened, but she couldn’t deny the fact that there was nothing she could do by now. It was coming to the end of September, - So I guess we go this way?\n\nShe pointed into the direction where halfling was trying to go before a flaming spirit appeared in front of him. Kara still didn't understand much of what happened. She didn’t feel bad for the people who died in the pit anymore, not even the two heroes that went down. She knew nothing beyond the fact that they were meant to die there. Well, all except two. If she was one of the imposters, who was the other one? It didn’t look like Haderach seemed phased, did he know that she was a criminal? Did he know how stupidly mindless and crazy her crime was?\n\n- Yes, I guess others would be happy to know that you are finally joining, - Haderach shrugged his shoulders and took the lead walking towards the stairway. He walked quite hastily, but Kara did have longer legs and easily kept at pace.\n\n- How did the team training go? - Kara tried to stay calm, but the silence was too awkward. She had zero idea how anything works and felt awfully underprepared. It almost felt funny, when she realized that it was like walking into a class having no idea what the homework was reading about.\n\n- I don’t know if you can call it training, - Haderach sounded quite grim. He wanted to add something else, but couldn’t find the right words.\n\n- Hey, don’t worry, - Kara smiled uneasily, - I am just asking because they didn’t tell me anything that was happening, - If Kara was innocent before she was thrown into the pit, that definitely changed when she killed the first man in there. Well he did try to stab her, so did the next two dead to be. However the last two died on her initiative. Right after she threw Persival at that woman who stole her ax. Six casualties and Kara still didn’t understand why out of them all she grieved the most for the potato. She wasn’t innocent for sure, she knew that much.\n\n- Sorry, they just throw us on some field trips to fix their problems, but we haven’t seen these things before, - Haderach clenched his fists, - We got maybe one or two personal training sessions, but that’s about as far as their instructions go. Everything else we catch on the fly, - he didn’t seem to know much and Kara wondered if he was the other imposter. Would it be too awkward to ask it though?\n\n- Ok? So what field work for example? - now Kara was just curious. The government never really went into the details of the arising issues. The news consisted of simple one line announcements of accidents and their locations and nothing more. Just so that families would not worry about waiting for their loved ones to return and be quick to move on. They would rarely announce the singular disappearances, in fact Kara didn’t remember any in her town. She wasn’t really big on listening to the announcements or watching TV lately.\n\n- Well, last time some cows ran away from Quintus, - Haderach shivered, - to say the least, those were definitely their cows. Can’t believe they feed the entire country with these. No wonder they want to keep it a secret.\n\nKara pondered on a thought. Food is food, no matter where it comes from. What could have been so shocking about those cows? Last time she saw the meat on the shelf it looked perfectly red and fresh. Much better than the wild catch she was killing in the forest. There would be no way for her to make money if the markets had enough of this stuff.\n\n- Well, that sounds like a Quintus problem, - Kara shrugged and looked back at steadily walking Fluffer behind her. She wondered if she would need to feed him soon. He didn’t look hungry at all and, now that she thought about it, neither did she, - Why would they send Septum heroes?\n\n- Because they made it to Septum, - Haderach sounded like it was common sense, but it must have meant that these cows ran across at least two other states uncaptured. Either that or they were brought in on purpose. Super crazy fast cows or a training set up. At this point both outcomes seemed equally possible. Quintus had hybrid technologies.","n":32},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"- Did they tell you what happened? - Kara sat on the stone fence looking into the forest. It would have been so easy to run away. It was just a ten foot drop and an easy climb up.\n\n- No, it was just an accident. Something blew up and the rescue ships got damaged, - Rein sat on the other side of the fence facing the town. It was very quiet, many families mourned at their homes and rest seemed just slightly dazed. Probably just hungry. Last shipment from Quattuor came last week and was poorly calculated. Still better than nothing and they eased up the hunting prohibitions.\n\n- What are you going to do? Did they work out the plan? - Government was quite efficient with the labor market. The lack of homeless people on the streets was quite remarkable. Not like the streets were by any means comfortable for living anyway. Benches didn’t allow anyone to sit on them longer than an hour. You could sit on them all day if not for the body heat and you would get in trouble if you used something as an insulator to extend your stay.\n\n- Well, they said I can stay in school, but I will still have to find a job to afford the medicine, - Rein sounded determined. Kara wondered what it would feel like to have a sister to look after, but she was the only child. Her problems were a bit less stressful, the government can’t separate something that is not there to begin with.\n\n- So what are you thinking then? Don’t tell me they offered you your fathers spot, - It wasn’t uncommon, the job market diversity for residents of Septum was quite scarce. Kara thought that she would grow up into some safe office job if she was lucky, but she would die of boredom if she had to be locked up in a building for eternity. She could always apply for a transfer, but that would require some high grades in a specialty other than Energy Development and local ones didn’t provide enough courses in anything else anyway. She would be going into the wrong industry with the wrong specialty in hopes that she will adapt quickly. And she would probably never see her parents again. Or Rein.\n\n- I can go to the coal mines, - boy didn’t sound concerned, but Kara felt a slight disappointment in his voice, - It is easy enough and the pay is quite good for the first time job.\n\n- You can’t be serious about this? - Kara felt a cold gust in her stomach, - They don’t even report mine accidents anymore. I didn’t even think states use coal for energy still. It’s a dead end industry.\n\n- It is my best option, - Rein sighed with annoyance. Kara felt her cheeks blushing, she couldn’t tell him what to do. That was selfish of her to assume that he would choose to stay just because she thought of something in her head. Kara never asked how much the medicine costs.\n\n- Sorry, I just wanted to say that I’m going to miss you, - For some reason she thought that they were going to be together forever, but that changed recently. She struggled to find the right words and nothing seemed fit. Anything that they used to talk about became irrelevant and everything they talked about now was just plain and sad. Latest news just made it more apparent.\n\n- You will find new friends and so will I, - Rein always sounded more adult than Kara. He was the one to come up with something to do and Kara just winged with anything. She just liked talking to him. Still, sometimes Kara did not believe how little he sometimes cared about what they did together. He always had something else to do.\n\n- I guess so, - Kara didn’t want to admit that she didn’t want to. For a second she thought about going to the mines with him, but her parents would never allow her to pick up such a dangerous profession. It seemed like it was their last goodbye.","n":33},{"chapter":"Training grounds","text":"- Must have been some crazy fast cows, - Kara slightly smiled as she and Haderach made their way downstairs into what looked like a common area. The rest of the team sat patiently at the table. She could barely believe that they were the same heroes that exited the coliseum with her. They all looked different, all but the hooded boy.\n\n- What the hell is this? - He was the first one to notice Fluffer Huggins walking down the stairs.","n":34},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"Fluffer Huggins was quite an energetic kitten once he got back to health. Always jumping around and chasing at every little ribbon Rein and Kara presented him with. He lived in the box on Karas side backyard that they shared with Reins family. It was a long responsibility talk for both of them, before they got permission to keep him there. Kara was excited to finally have something to look after. She thought Rein was excited too. After all they got a new friend to accompany their walk to school and back when Fluffer would grow longer feet. He was very smart for a cat.\n\nMaybe that’s why Kara was excited to present her flaming tom to the hooded boy that looked like Rein. It could finally settle the cards and straighten up the questions. Only Rein could have known that name.\n\n- It’s Fluffer Huggins! - Kara smiled vividly as the fiery fur of the giant cat spirit brightened the room. He must have been excited to see the hooded boy too. The chatter at the table stopped as four heroes focused their eyes on a potential threat. She couldn’t blame them.\n\n- Whatever this thing is, it's definitely not Fluffer Hugins, Kara, - Rein’s words suddenly hurt Kara, as he spoke with such confidence and disgust that she felt the urge to throw something at him. She didn’t understand how it boiled up so quickly. She knew that she just called a spirit with an old name from the memory, but part of her still believed that little Fluffers returned. If you can call it that. She just shoved away the thoughts of doubt.\n\n- Well, that’s its name and you don’t get a say in it, Rein, - Kara was surprised that with the explosive temper of her fiery spirit it didn’t attack anyone yet. She appreciated that, but it didn’t make much sense given the previous experience.\n\n- My name is Night Piercer, - Rein corrected Kara, but it was too late for the first introduction.\n\n- You can call yourself whatever you want. Whatever makes you feel better about yourself, Rein - Kara was annoyed, but it felt nice to be angry. It spread across her body with a fresh sensation, if it was the end of their old friendship she gladly accepted this closure. Except there was one problem. He was a teammate and she was stuck with him.\n\n- Well that’s a good start. You two know each other? - The man with surprisingly clear light blue skin tried to lighten the mood with his soft, almost feminine demeanor. Not the worst color of transformation in Kara's eyes, considering that the other two at the table were red and green. He looked like he retained most of his human features too.\n\nKara didn’t answer, neither did Night Piercer. She wanted him to respond, but he just relaxed in his chair and looked away.\n\n- Well, my name is Kara Toham and this is Fluffers, - The tom stepped forward, nudging his head under Kara’s arm and she suddenly felt how warm and fuzzy he felt. It didn’t burn at all, but everything else around him seemed to start covering in black burn marks, - I guess this could be a problem.\n\n- I could be indeed, - The blue man didn’t seem too worried, - I’m Floats, - he waved his hand nonchalantly.\n\n- We can head out now and get introductions on the way, before something catches on fire, - Red man stood up and Kara weirdly recognised him to be that same man who was fighting back to back with Rein in the coliseum. Only now he had red skin and demonic horns. He passed by Fluffer Huggins and gave him a friendly pat on the back and almost jumped when spirit lightly growled, - This kitty might have to live outside.\n\n- Sure, right after I learn how to train him properly, - Kara smiled as she hugged her spirit's neck with her arm to keep it from jumping, - I am still getting used to it all.\n\nThe rest of the table crew reluctantly followed with green goblin-like creature quickly rushing to take the lead, - Finally some action! - it was a she and Kara almost didn’t believe that it could have been the same beast like woman that almost killed her. She was now twice smaller and, funnily enough, had a fluffy raccoon like tail.\n\n- My name is Fezzik Alfonce and that is Tallie, - Red man pointed at green goblin lady happily rushing forward. Kara wasn’t really sure what was happening, but it’s not like she had anything else to do. It was an uncomfortable situation, but she bet there was a child somewhere dreaming about this life. Maybe it was her dream. What was the last thing she remembered? Did she fall asleep in the potato garden? That would have been nice.\n\n- So what is the plan again? - Kara was starting to feel a bit overwhelmed by the amount of information and also the lack of it. She usually didn’t care about the details, but teamwork wasn’t something she was used to. So far she just knew that she needed to watch out and be careful not to hit teammates.\n\n- We are going to investigate the village in the mountains. They said they have been hit by some sort of plague, - Fezzik was answering reluctantly given that the rest of the team seemed unwilling to talk. There seemed to be some tension and the rest of the way to the armory, no one dropped a single word.","n":35},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"The moose had destroyed a good fifth of the garden. Kara didn’t even need to stand up to know this. She layed on the ground for quite some time, feeling how her back pulsates from the pain from being struck by the wrong side of moose antlers. She was lucky they were still covered in velvet and not as sharp on the ends yet. Otherwise she would be laying on the ground with very different thoughts.\n\n- Yes, Teresa, you were right. I will make a fence, - Kara finally rolled over to stand up, realizing all this time she was laying on some plants, - Thanks for the catch guys, - She paused on her knees feeling guilty, but grateful. Their stems were ruined and Kara didn’t know if the support stick would save the situation. She would try for sure, but the prospects of revival were quite slim, - Mark, Lillian, Perry, I’m so sorry.\n\nShe lightly touched each separate plant that she severely injured and struggled to her feet. Back felt stiff, but Kara had no reason to wait for it to heal. There was no miracle way to magically get rid of the uncomfortable pain and a dead moose would soon attract predators. Kara was not ready for another fight and potatoes were too fragile of a support team.","n":36},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"Kara picked up a battle ax in the armory and couldn’t resist trying a swing. It went inches away from Fezzik's back and the man annoyingly turned around with some judgment in his face. He didn’t look surprised at all, but the gust of dangerous wind definitely wasn’t something he appreciated.\n\n- Kara, you gotta be careful there, - he didn’t seem that angry. Almost as if it was quite normal.\n\n- Sorry, I just wanted to try a swing, - Kara wasn’t trying to be sassy, but Tallie definitely enjoyed it like a joke. Kara caught her eyes smiling, but, as soon as their gazes met, the goblin just moved on and exited the room. Everyone else followed without a word, awkward silence seemed to be awkward only to Kara, - So who knows where we are going? Anyone been to this village before?\n\n- No, but she has the map and that’s that, - Rein definitely wasn’t opening the floor for conversation. Whatever happened during Kara’s three week absence, it didn’t bring the group together at all.\n\n- Hey Tallie, do you mind showing me the map? - Kara hurried up to the front, but, as soon as she leveled with the goblin, Tallie let out an almost animalistic growl that stopped Kara in her tracks. She never heard humans make such noise and it wasn’t like goblins are normal acquaintances in the forests where she lived, - What’s up with her?\n\n- You tell us, - Rein was visibly annoyed, - You were the one who ran out of the pit holding her hand. We thought you were friends, - Kara hated that sound of disappointment in his voice. Did they think that she was one of the original heroes with this beast woman? Fluffer Huggins stood still. For a second Kara thought that he wasn't breathing, but as soon as she thought about it the flaming cat let out a big yawn.\n\n- Yeah, you would love to believe that? - Kara was getting tired and angry, somehow every word Rein spoke put her on edge, - It was you in the pit, why didn’t you come to help out? Acting so cool now. Just say what you were thinking, Rein?\n\n- It’s Night Piercer, - Rein walked past her with a smug nonchalant expression, - Please call me that.\n\nKara didn’t understand anything. Whatever this bunch of people were, they didn’t seem like a team. Almost like there were no heroes among them at all. However there were at least four. Could it be that she and Tallie were the odd ones out?\n\n- Take it easy on him, he has a lot to deal with, - Fezzik lightly touched her shoulder, - People don’t volunteer for these tournaments for good reasons.\n\n- Did you? - Kara didn’t even know that you could volunteer to be a hero, but, if there was a chance, out of all people Rein would be first in line.\n\n- Me? Heh, someone had to keep an eye on him, - Fezzik didn’t look like a man who regrets his choices. In fact Kara didn’t even know what to think of him, he didn’t look like a rookie and yet it seemed like he didn’t quite fit on the battlefield. Quite tall, but it seemed like he was more of the back line tactician. She wondered if he was the captain.\n\n- You must be a good friend then, - Kara sighed.\n\nThey kept walking, she didn’t feel like talking anymore. Something was draining her energy. It was a weird new sensation, it almost felt like the part of her that felt depleted wasn’t even in her body. It was just a looming atmosphere of pressured air around her that gave away the feeling that something was off. Fluffer Huggins seemed to feel it too. His flames grew slightly weaker with every minute passing until he just dissipated back out of existence. Kara felt a strange relief and turned around to see the last flames go out leaving no trace. She guessed that it was her limit. It would be quite obnoxious to have Fluffers around at all times and he did seem to appear only when she was awake. He will return.","n":37},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"Kara hated winter. Not always, but today the forest was so painfully peaceful. She sat in her hut under five blankets because she couldn’t bother to light up the fire after a long walk from school. It was sunny outside, but it only irritated Kara as the rays were passing through the cracks in the door. She needed to fix those sooner, but she forgot until now. Maybe she will get something for it on the market tomorrow, but today she could only crunch her teeth as light mocked her dancing on the wet freezing floor.\n\nIt was a tease, nature was testing Kara’s patience. Potatoes were hibernating under the snow, warmed by the plastic blanket, and seeds were safely stored in the box in the corner. Kara had to wait for the spring to plant them. She could tell seeds stories, but they didn’t even sprout yet. She would definitely look crazy and that’s even by potato standards. She thought about it though, about all the things she would tell them. She would tell how she hunted, how her feet were constantly wet because of the snow, how her teacher totally stopped complaining about dirt. He did slip on the wet floor, but everyone had wet shoes from the snow. She would tell them how she couldn’t enjoy the sun without them.\n\nShe chuckled on a thought of how poetically she misses these stupid vegetables. Maybe in a few years she will be able to keep them in a greenhouse. She didn’t know if Lillian would see it, but maybe her seedlings will. Maybe then she would like the winter again. She had to change into her forest attire.","n":38},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"No one said anything when Fluffer Huggins disappeared, it seemed only natural. Kara felt as if a gust of energy returned to her. For the first time in a while she felt as if she was somehow whole again. She finally had the energy to look around and realize that they were walking on a dirt road. They were free, she could go anywhere and find a place where they would never find her again. The treeline called to her with a warm welcome, she could have been exploring it with Fluffer Huggins all this time!\n\nShe clenched her teeth as she saw that she was behind everyone. She had to focus, it was her first day with this team and they were as dysfunctional as a door handle without a door. They barely talked and who knows what kind of trouble Rein could get into. She wanted to stop at that thought, but she was already taking over Haderach and Floats.\n\n- Fluffer Huggins is taking a rest, - Kara smiled at halfling expecting a wise remark, but it seemed that he wasn’t as interested.\n\n- Good idea, - man sounded assuring, but she didn’t like his tone. It wasn’t her idea. She wasn’t sure how to bring Fluffers back and, by the looks of it, she couldn’t waste energy on rookie training during the mission.\n\n- How far is this village? - Kara dared to ask the goblin woman, but she didn’t seem to bother and just sped up her pace, - Does anyone else know? - She turned around taking a couple of steps walking backwards, but rest just shrugged their shoulders.\n\n- We don’t know, goblin just grabbed the map and by now you can imagine what happens if you try and take it from her, - Rein seemed to have this answer prepared and suddenly Kara didn’t feel as safe with her back turned to Tallie. She didn’t reply to him. Why would anyone ever give a map to a goblin? Why would a goblin grab the map anyway? Well, she was a woman, but who gets so excited over a map?\n\nThey walked until the sundown and at some point goblin went off the road and everyone just followed. Now they were walking through mountain plains with occasional trees. Kara never saw the world from such heights without climbing above the treeline. She actually started to enjoy the hike.\n\nWhen the team stopped in the open space, the tailed goblin stopped only for a second. Fezzik asked if it was a good spot and Rein confirmed. Tallie seemed to make a note of that, but she still continued walking.\n\n- Where are you going? - Kara made a couple steps after her, but Rein called her over.\n\n- Kara, let her go, - he sounded tired and confident. Kara almost believed that Tallie would come back. Maybe she was just checking the perimeter, but she could have just kept going. She did have a map.\n\n- I will just check where she is going, - Kara reassured him, but he still stood up in front of her.\n\n- Just stay here, it’s getting dark, - Rein sounded tired and annoyed.\n\n- I can take care of myself, Rein. You don’t have to worry about me, - Kara snapped and walked past him following after goblin. Her posture changed and Kara mimicked her careful steps. There were now only two of them against the wilderness. They entered the little forest and left behind the open field.\n\nThey walked for ten minutes, maybe less. In the distance Kara heard some rodent screeches and briefly looked in the direction. It seemed Tallie also noticed the hustle and decided to check it out. Kara thought she heard the raccoon chatter and slowly walked up to the sight. Tallie made it there first, as she recently charged into the bushes. Kara only saw the tail of a raccoon dive into the foliage. Strangely, Tallie did not follow. She was looking down picking up an injured black weasel. It looked like a bad fight for a poor thing. Kara did not interrupt as she watched Tallie check it up and clumsily pet the fur. It didn’t look healthy either, could have been some sort of plague.\n\nKara tried to reach out to pet the weasel too, but Tallie growled and rushed into the forest escaping Kara’s sight in seconds. It was time to go back.\n\nSun was fully down and stars covered the sky when Kara noticed the fire on the plains and escaped the forest. Rest of the team already set up the camp and Haderach seemed to be busy cooking dinner. Kara didn’t like walking in the dark and thought about how Fluffer Huggins would be a good torch to light up the way. Thought stuck with her for a second too long as the giant flaming tom torched up into existence by her side. He was warm. Fezzik already was glancing in her direction.\n\n- She ran south and I lost her in the forest, - Kara felt a bit defeated saying that.\n\n- Told you so, - Rein raised his eyebrow. Kara almost felt warmth touch her heart as she remembered last time she heard these words. Stupid hope, made her put her hand on Fluffer Huggins almost wishing to be burned. She squeezed the flames hard, feeling them physically as if it was regular fur. It hurt to admit that she had to talk to him.\n\n- Well, better than sitting still and letting it just happen, - Kara wanted to sound stronger, but got distracted by a weird consistency of the flaming fur. It was so silky soft, - At least we know the general direction now, - the team looked tired. It must have been not their first limbo with an irrational goblin. Kara wondered why that woman didn’t trust them so much, - I can take the first fire watch with Fluffer Huggins.\n\n- I’ll join you, honey, - Floats gestured at the spot by his side inviting Kara to sit by him. Fluffer Huggins stayed at the other side of the camp. He was preparing a safe spot to sit down by burning grass and compressing ashes to avoid accidental spread of fire. He seemed to read Kara’s mind and come up with solutions on his own. She sat by Floats and Haderach handed her dinner. It was a porridge with a nice sweet smell to it.\n\n- Sorry, that’s all they packed in our rations and today is Sweet Sunday. Hope you don’t mind, - Haderach seemed to like cooking. Kara wondered how well he could prepare some meat. She should have hunted while she was in the forest. Still, she didn’t mind some porridge. It reminded her of school.","n":39},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"- Kara, who in the world would think about hamsters generating electricity? It’s like a middle school level idea for a project, - Lilith was never the nicest girl in the classroom, but at least she didn’t mind doing projects with Kara. They made a quite nice team if you left out all the toxic comments she let out about anything Kara did. Sometimes it was almost fun to listen to her ridiculous chatter. She was always right, mainly because Kara never took her seriously. They got the job done and never talked outside of it.\n\n- Well, we can simulate the river damb mechanics if you really want to. However boring it sounds, - Kara didn’t mind either way. Damb project would take more time and research, but it would fetch them a better grade. Maybe she would even get on the honor wall for once. She didn’t have much else to do while the snow covered the ground.\n\n- Good then, I will book us a room in the library for tonight, - Lilith never asked if Kara was free.  One of the reasons they always ended up working together was because they always stayed in school after hours to complete their assignments. She never asked why Lilith did though. They completed the task and went home. Sometimes Kara would stay longer to finish other homework.\n\nGroup of boys chucked a scrap paper ball as they passed by the girls. Lilith rolled her eyes and the boys hurried out of the classroom chuckling.\n\n- I’ll meet you there after dinner, - Kara was back to finishing up the notes on the project plan. Her hamster argument lasted for maybe four rounds. Better than before, but still ended up in the stupid idea bucked. Kara noticed this trend a long time ago.","n":40},{"chapter":"Not Fluffer Huggins","text":"- So what did they get you for? - Floats spoke as soon as everyone was off to sleep. He seemed calm and unbothered. It seems like they have solved the hero riddle already.\n\n- Illegal cultivation of potatoes, - Kara sounded firm and almost charmed by the innocence of her sentence. She wondered how ridiculous it sounded compared to the rest of the team. Maybe they were just a bunch of accidental bystanders. Well, Rein and Fezzik volunteered and Tallie probably just fought someone on the street. That left Floats and Haderach, - What about you?\n\n- Oh, nothing special. Haderach just got into a dispute with officers and they grabbed me too for good measure, - Floats sounded innocent, but vague. Kara didn’t bother to ask further, she felt like she would sleep better at night if she didn’t question it, - Must have been a terrible raid, I’m sorry darling, - blue man sounded surprisingly empathetic.\n\n- Yeah they burned everything, I got to save just four, - Kara regretfully looked at her hip bag, - Well, now just three.\n\n- They must be special if you took them with you, - Floats must have been just being polite, but Kara was grateful for his understanding. It felt nice to feel a friendly touch a very once in a while. She wondered if she would be better off being friends with Floats and Haderach than with Rein and the rest of whatever this team was. She thought about the poor weasel and Tallie, who took it somewhere into the woods. Didn’t look like she wanted to hurt it. Kara didn’t understand much of it, but if the furry pal would survive the night maybe there was a way to talk to Tallie.\n\n- Yes, very special, - Kara looked at Fluffer Huggins that was calmly laying down in his burnt nest. He didn’t seem to move much when Kara wasn’t focusing on him, almost like he wasn’t alive when she wasn’t looking or keeping him in the back of her mind. Was he pretending to be alive just because she so desperately wanted him to be?","n":41},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"There are always two sides to the argument. Well at least two anyway. Whoever came up with a saying “one sided argument” must have been crazy or delusional. Kara was trying to figure out her priorities and she slowly felt how ridiculously indifferent she was to the fact that she randomly stuck potatoes at the top of the list. It made perfect sense in her mind, since she didn’t know much about her teammates. It didn’t take as much energy to protect three potatoes and Kara was ready to risk dying for them. It was a no brainer, Kara already killed five people to preserve these tubber plant roots. Price for a rare type of insanity that she decided to have for her sanity's sake.\n\nKara longingly watched the moon, suddenly understanding all wolves that ever howled at it. It was unbearably painful to know that this same moon was looking down at the gorge where the potato garden used to bloom. Maybe a little sprout survived. Maybe it would survive the winter. Maybe Kara will know for sure one day, she just had to survive to see it. And if not, she did have three potatoes in her bag. Two sides of the argument, Kara was fine in either case, but only if she was to preserve what she had. She would never trust sprout his own survival, too many things could go wrong.","n":42},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"When Kara found the dried up gorge she almost could feel her past catching on to her feet. She never had spent so much time alone. For the first time today she felt as if something was forcing her to run away. She finally understood why she left the orphanage instead of waiting for new parents. She felt her heartbeat chilling her entire body with exhaustion. She didn’t know where she was, all she knew was that if she went back she wouldn't make it back through the night.\n\nShe cursed her fear. She cursed the fact that she didn’t trust anything that she heard anymore. Kara was scared to trust someone to change her life, she liked it the way it was. She didn’t want to learn new rules. Changes hurt her for no reason at all and in the ways that she did not understand. It was like constantly fighting the impulses that used to make you happy. She wanted to be selfish, for once in her lifetime. If she wasn’t allowed to be, then no one should have been. And there were plenty of other selfish people, right? Aren’t they the reason we constantly face problems? Well, besides the natural disasters anyway, but who knows.\n\nKara looked down at the gorge, it almost felt like she was choosing her own trench for the First World War she was about to declare. Like a privileged kid that she was, living in the great era of equality and safety. Her troubles seemed so tiny and meaningless. She was alone and never felt so much content in her life. Nothing behind her depended on her survival. It was her own choice to stay alive. Whatever she will do from now on will be the consequences of her personal choice today. She could choose to disappear.","n":43},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"When it was time for bed Kara let Floats decide who to wake up for the next shift. She went straight to her sleeping bag, well to the one that Haderach or someone else grabbed for her. Maybe it was in her backpack all the way. It wasn’t like Kara checked or took it out herself. It was nice to realize that at least her teammates watched out for her. It was almost painful to take it for granted as she quietly slipped into a cozy blanket. Kara just thought about how ridiculously simple the idea of a sleeping bag was and yet she never thought about buying it. Five years in the woods struggling with all the blankets in attempts to make a semblance of a bed. It would have been much easier with a sleeping bag.\n\nKara fell asleep almost instantly feeling surprisingly calm. Probably the best night sleep she had in the past three weeks. She wasn’t even sure if they let her sleep in between sessions. She was just happy to know for sure that next time she will wake up to see the morning. It was nice to be free. Even if it felt like the coliseum fight felt like it was yesterday. She still welcomed freedom to choose to fall asleep. How weird it felt to think this way. She only skipped one night and yet somehow it turned into a three week blackout. Funny thought.\n\nKara woke up to the sound of clanking plates. Haderach was cooking breakfast, did someone appoint him as a cook? Kara thought that it would be a weird chore to appoint a hero to. It looked like he almost enjoyed it, the porridge was never intended to be sweet. He added sugar to make it bearable to eat. He was also the last one to be on the watch, for a dysfunctional team he somehow made Kara forget it was the case. Even if this illusion only existed in the early morning, it did feel serene.\n\n- Good morning, - Kara sat up in her sleeping bag feeling restless. Haderach was making food for everyone who was at the camp and Kara felt bad for Tallie since she skipped it. She didn’t even know why it bothered her so much that the team wasn’t together. She wanted to believe that everything was alright, but facts didn’t add up, - I take it Tallie doesn’t come back for the nights. How are we supposed to find her?\n\n- Night Piercer will send Barrow to find her when we move out, - Haderach didn’t seem bothered at all.\n\n- Barrow? - Kara felt uneasy. She was almost sure that it wasn’t one of the names of heroes and the idea of Rein in command of anyone seemed confusing anyway. He seemed the most childish out of everyone in this team, but, again, he wasn’t exactly on good terms with Kara. She wondered if it was because of Fluffer Huggins.\n\n- Yeah, his scouting owl, - Haderach passed over a plate without much of a thought. Kara expected him to say something else, but he just continued on with his little chores around the fire. She wanted to ask more about the powers, but from what she knew they were quite personal. Fluffer Huggins didn’t appear out of thin air when she woke up. The patterns of his behavior truly puzzled Kara, though the more time she spent with him the easier it was to predict what he was going to do. Surprisingly easier.\n\n- Alright, - she didn’t want to distract Haderach anymore, he seemed quite busy. Kara wanted to look around in the morning light.","n":44},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"The scenery was amazing. For a prehistoric movie the simulations of the background were on point. The mountains looked almost too real and all the people in the scene had some sort of purpose in the shots. Almost like each and everyone of them were directed what to do. Kara never understood how people could so calmly follow directions for so long. On their own too. How did they know all the right choices to make to follow set directions?\n\nKara watched diligently as the time passed. It was a long movie to watch in class, but it was in the school program. No kid had three hours after school to watch some old movie about Hobbits out of all things. So they showed it and randomly asked to write an essay about superpowers or something. There always had to be an essay, students couldn’t just enjoy the film. It ended on a weird cliffhanger, like they actually intended it to have a sequel.\n\n- I can’t believe they just made us do that! - Kara was annoyed by the weird irregularity in her schedule. The movie stretched into the activity time and now on top of that they had homework. The day was completely ruined.\n\n- Well, we do need it for the grade, everyone does it, - Rein always said the smart things about school. Kara would be completely lost without him.","n":45},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"It didn’t take much time for the rest of the team to wake up to the smell of breakfast. Everyone was quiet and did their own thing. Kara watched as Rein stood up and stretched a hand as if he was expecting a bird to land on it. It was weird, because Kara did not see any birds in the sky and she was pretty sure she would spot an owl if it was flying around. The silhouette appeared from a distance. There was no way a bird could see this command from this far. Kara wouldn’t even notice it if she didn’t know what she was looking for. It was white. Rein must have known how to command it telepathically. At least it seemed that way.\n\nKara caught herself staring and quickly looked away before anyone could notice that she isn’t that mad at Rein anymore. He definitely had no right to be mad at her. Unless he did, but she couldn’t pinpoint where it could have gone wrong. She did kill people, but so did he. It didn’t matter, they were not friends now. They were teammates and by the looks of things it was definitely two different states of the matter.\n\n- Goblin is about an hour away to the south, - Rein was surprisingly unsurprised. It was like he was saying a stationary comment that told everyone exactly everything and a personal touch of discontent with an uncooperative teammate. Kara was beginning to doubt the humanity of that creature.\n\nThey moved out almost as quickly as they decided to stay for the night. Packing sleeping bags took a bit longer than unpacking them. Kara almost felt proud that she woke up a bit earlier and packed, because there was no way she would have known what to do if she woke up last.\n\nThey followed the owl. Kara did recognise some of the way, but beside the fact that she didn’t trip over the roots there was not much else she could do with this information. It was notable though that she definitely had better time tracking in the forest than most of the team. Kara wondered if most of their missions were around these mountains or somewhere else.\n\nThey found Tallie on a tree waiting for them. There was a weasel in her hands and Kara saw Rein smirk at it with disgust. No wonder. It unsettled her for some reason. The weasel did look sickly, but who knew how severe it could have been. Didn’t look too contagious, so maybe that’s why Rein said nothing.","n":46},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"- Aren’t you afraid that it is sick? - little Kara finally spoke to break the awkward silence. The whole scene made her want to puke and she didn’t even look into the box to see the rest of the litter. She just knew that she was supposed to feel sorry for the kitten, but her mind tried really hard not to get attached to a potentially dead case.\n\n- Doesn’t look sick, just hungry, - Rein looked very confident in his judgment. Kara wasn’t looking at the cat. It could have been an accident - others look like they starved.","n":47},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"They walked until they hit the road again. Not much could be said about that walk, Kara was mostly surprised that Fluffer Huggins didn’t impulsively show up at some point. Whatever this training was, she definitely did quite well at it. There also could have been an option that he disappeared entirely, but Kara was more focused on the fact that she needed to learn to control him efficiently as soon as possible. In any way, it wasn’t like she particularly needed his assistance to walk.\n\nThey walked for maybe ten more minutes before they met a group of distressed people in red vests. Their horses looked like a pack of wolves had torn through them. Right in the middle of the road. Right in the middle of the day. Kara thought that it was quite peculiar that wolves didn’t touch humans.\n\n- Help, please we need to get to the village, - woman sounded hysterical, Kara was caught off guard. They didn’t seem sick, what was the reason for such distress?\n\n- Calm down and you can show us the way, - Fezzik tried to speak, but this crowd seemed to be mindlessly surrounding them just for the action of asking for help.\n\n- Please, you have to understand, - the other woman approached Kara trying to grab her hand. It felt unnatural and Kara just ducked out of the way and started to walk toward horses to see what happened. There was no reasoning with the hysterical crowd, experience told her to try to stay away.\n\n- I am so sorry, - it wasn’t the most straightforward phrase for the situation, but somehow it made perfect sense as Kara felt something hit her side. Woman already apologized for what she did, but Kara wasn’t sure if she forgave her before or after the stab. That’s why she instantly swung her ax in response.","n":48},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"Little Kara ran out of the house as soon as she heard the sounds of the cat fight. She heard them before, but never been so close to the door to react in time. She was always scared that it could have been Fluffer Huggins.","n":49},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"She missed almost on purpose. She didn’t understand anything, she didn’t expect anything. She thought she was alert. She did not expect she would have to kill again before the tournament. Who were these people? Why would they want to attack heroes? What was their plan?","n":50},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"She didn’t remember how she caught up to a tabby tom that was on Fluffer's tail. She just remembers grabbing it tighter than ever before in her life.","n":51},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"Second stab followed almost immediately. Kara barely felt it, still recovering after the shock of the first one.","n":52},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"In one angry swing the tabby cat flew into the wall with a painful thud and disappeared into the night. Little Kara almost felt it hit the wall with her own spine. It wasn’t something she was proud of doing. Poor cat could have been injured now and unable to hunt properly. Fluffers could easily survive cat fights. Kara could have killed a cat just by falling on it. Maybe that’s why she didn’t swing as hard. She could have put her back into it. She wanted to. Something stopped her and it didn’t come from her rational part of the mind.","n":53},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"Kara didn’t remember what happened between the second hit and Tallie swinging her hammer into the neck of this woman. It could have been seconds, could have been minutes. It was enough time for her to realize that she wants nothing to do with this village and whatever was the reason behind this attack.\n\nKara looked up to see the entire road covered in blood and corpses as heroes stood on top ever so slightly surprised. Floats stood with a ghostly man by his side. Kara for a second thought that it could have been Haderach, but there was something else that somehow made a better candidate on the road. It was absolutely hideous, but it definitely wore halflings clothes. Kara tried not to stare at it to be polite.\n\n- They are civilians, - Kara was looking at Tallie that probably saved her life again, but the goblin just started munching on the corpses. Kara did not stare at that ether. She just silently took a couple of steps away to give the green creature all the space and time it needed to return to the tame version that Kara had the privilege to experience a bit earlier. They were civilians.\n\nThen there was beeping. Kara barely had time to take cover at a gutter by the road. It was like all action scenes she has ever seen have instilled a pure fear of this sound into her psyki. Maybe she was just generally scared of a situation as a whole. She looked over on the road and understood that the it’s previous state was actually not that bad. All red vests have exploded and not those who were not as fortunate to be at the curb were hit and covered in blood. Rein seemed to shake a bit as he was trying to clean himself up. Who ever came up with this training practice wasn’t very subtle about his intent of training murderous survivalists.\n\n- What the actual, - Kara wanted to finish a sudden unnatural click made her jump to her feet, - No, no, no, I am done, - she guessed a direction back to the training polygon and started walking. It’s not like she had the chance to sign up to whatever was going on, but she definitely did not support it.\n\nThe ground in front of her shifted.","n":54},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"- Mom, where do cats go when they die? - little Kara felt kind of stupid asking adult such silly questions, but she was asking her mother.\n\n- Well, it really depends, sweety. Some people actually think that cats have nine lives, however it is almost impossible to know how many lives it already used, - Kara knew that her mom made up this story to calm her down. Maybe she read it somewhere in superstition collections. Kara wondered if it was something to do with the Feng Shui book that was so popular among moms.\n\n- So they don’t disappear like we do? - Kara wasn’t sure she used the right world. People disappeared and reappeared all the time. Sometimes they disappear for good, but it’s not like you could ever know for sure unless you see it with your own eyes. People didn’t talk about it much because it was painful.\n\n- Honey, you are thinking about ridiculous things, - Mother smiled and turned off the lights, - You are too young to be worried about it.","n":55},{"chapter":"Sick Weasel","text":"Whatever this thing was before didn’t matter, it’s skin was burned in a flare of Fluffer Huggins apparition. Flaming tom instantly backed away, but the creature swung at him visibly misplacing the chunk of burning mass leaving a deep empty cut. Kara almost felt the hit herself as she herself got out of the way of a swing.\n\n- For the love of all sprouts, - Kara didn’t have much time to look behind her, so she made sure that her teammates knew how angry she was that there was literally no heads up on situations they run into in training.\n\nFluffers spitted out a flaming ball and the burned creature dropped dead. Its body looked terribly distorted, and yet still somehow anthropomorphic. Kara did not want to think upon it any further. Whatever problem they thought they had in that village, it was by no means related to anything Kara felt competent of commenting. What was done was done, she just hoped that there wasn’t another way that she didn’t see. Well, there was always the other way.\n\nKara retreated back to her teammates only to discover a total chaos among which Tallie did a series hasted blows and chased the distorted humanoid into the forest disappearing behind the trees. The road seemed to have secured a peaceful state of some sort and heroes started looking around for clues. Kara hoped that was the reason behind all the disgusting ravaging. She tried to look around and surprisingly noticed a half dead black weasel crawling into the bushes. It looked even worse than Kara remembered. She wondered if it fell out of Tallie's grasp or did the goblin just drop it as soon as her attention shifted. In any case, the critter needed help.\n\nKara picked up the weasel, feeling that there was literally nothing she could have done for it. It seemed to have some shattered bones and bad scratches. On top of whatever illness it had previously. Kara was almost sure he would be gone in hours. Fluffer Huggins stepped a bit closer, but she rocked a bit away feeling that weasel grown tense at sudden change in temperature.\n\n- Sorry little bud, - Kara remembered the trick that Haderach showed her. She concentrated on her hands and the orange glow seemed to have moved some fur as the scratches stitched together and disappeared. She felt cold in hands, it seemed to have taken away more energy than before. Kara felt weakness in her whole body.\n\n- Kara, you can’t be serious? - Rein was straight up staring at her. He looked quite angry, a weird type of angry. Almost as if Kara did something insanely stupid.\n\n- Hey, he is still alive, - her reply was indifferent. She finally remembered about the two open wounds in her torso, which felt almost normal with the adrenaline rush that coursed through her body. She tried the same trick on her wounds and it seemed to work as a charm. It still felt a bit sore, but bleeding stopped entirely. She placed the weasel in the backpack and wore it on her chest to be able to keep it safe and comfortable, - I am done here.\n\n- Maybe we should at least check it out, - Fezzik did sound concerned as he took out some sort of the note and reread it.\n\n- Well, for all we know, - Rein plucked the piece of paper from red man’s hands and dropped it to the ground, - you don’t know who left this note. If they really wanted us to take care of it they would have given it with the map.\n\n- Maybe they really need help, - Fezzik wanted to pick up the paper, but Fluffer Huggins beat him to it, burning it to ashes with one step.\n\n- If you call exploding people by being in their proximity helping, sign me out of your little ventures, - Kara clenched her teeth. It’s not like she felt sorry for what happened. Maybe she did, but she hoped that her decisions were closer to common sense. She didn’t want to do any of it and the threat to her life shouldn’t have been motivation to do anything. Though she couldn’t help but think that it was quite a powerful excuse.","n":56},{"chapter":"The map","text":"Was there even the reason or the consequences for refusing to do something during the training season? Kara didn’t know, just like she didn’t know that she could be tracked deep into the forest and charged for the crime that she did not commit. If she was to face the consequences of her choice she would not mind confrontation to protect her case. Like Victorian said, if not then good riddance. Kara knew that her hopes to return to her peaceful potato gardening were not worth the human lives that she took. She already lived in debt that was forced upon her by the system. All because she somehow decided that her goal was worth living for. Kara wondered how many times she was going to have to remind herself that her life had a price behind it.\n\nKara didn’t wait for anyone to respond, she just continued walking in the direction they followed after they came on the road. She must have been confused. Kara didn’t want to think much about what happened and what was about to happen next. Suddenly the idea of exploring what lay at the end of this road seemed like the most interesting thing in the world. Hopefully there was a river. She wouldn’t mind Fluffers having a bit of fun there.\n\n- Let’s go Fluffers, I have to tell you so much, - Flaming tom seemed happy that Kara finally paid undivided attention to him. Kara was happy that she had him. Whatever he was, he was a friend. Even if he wasn't, she was too tired to suspect anything else.","n":57},{"chapter":"The map","text":"- Fluffers, did you know that you are the cutest cat in the entire city? - Little Kara was intensely petting the orange tom cat with all the love and passion that she could imagine. Fluffers was purring intensely and twisting around exposing his favorite spots.\n\n- Kara, aren’t you squeezing too hard? - Rein got startled by the sudden intensity of the situation.\n\n- It’s ok, I am mad at Mister Sawyer, not Fluffer Huggins, - Kara squeezed an ear and tom twitched a leg in a pleasured impulse, - I would never hurt this furball of pure happiness.","n":58},{"chapter":"The map","text":"- Can you believe them Fluffers? - Kara was gently petting a jet black weasel wondering how natural this color was. It almost looked healthy in the shade of the bag. Kara really wanted to believe that it was true, but its movement was so bleak that she unintentionally looked around for possible ideas where to bury the poor rodent, - I can’t even start understanding what's wrong with them! They barely talk!\n\nKara tried her best to keep her voice down, not to startle her little passenger. For a second she felt a pin needle in her heart as she glanced down on the Flaming figure next to her. It wasn’t listening, its ears were lifeless. He looked back at Kara and suddenly flicked its ears. It wasn’t a relief she was looking for. She almost felt as if she was the one who commanded it. She almost felt her ears flicker like a mirror.\n\n- You are not Fluffers are you? - Kara felt horrible saying the words, but it only made sense. Fluffer Huggins would not be reborn as a spirit. He was probably living his seventh life somewhere in Quattuor. He would never remember her, they barely had a year to remember each other, - Sorry, we can still be friends. Funny, I can’t even call you junior. That would look ridiculous, you are nine times bigger than him. I wonder if you will grow bigger. Maybe I can ride you?\n\nKara almost forgot about the massacre she left behind. She never held things in her head for too long. It was easier not to think about baby rabbits that might never see their parents again. Bet it all on hope that there are no baby rabbits, - You know, I think they are watching all the time. They asked which one was Vincent. Why would they care? Do they seriously think I am this crazy? We can’t trust anyone, - Kara felt a shiver in her back. She really wanted to trust Rein, but even that could have been just her losing her bearings. How did he know her name?\n\nIt didn’t feel right to think about staying on full guard all the time. Kara wasn’t scared, she was frustrated. She would be fine if she just had some time to calm down. Some time to understand what was going on and then she could sit down and ask everything she wanted. It was a rational decision, whatever happened in that village she didn’t want to know or see. She wasn’t competent to take any responsibility for what could have happened there. World existed without her before and it could continue just that.","n":59},{"chapter":"The map","text":"Kara never ran so hard after a squirrel. Well, it was a rabbit, but it felt almost as stupid a squirrel in the park. Rein never approved of that and now she felt like this experience was about to get her dinner. Who would have guessed? Skipping from side to side along the gorge, there was nowhere for the rabbit to go. Its fatal mistake was to try to climb up to safety. Kara pounced with full body like she always wanted. She was wearing her worst shirt and felt as free as a wind. She spent so much time in the forest the dirt didn’t bother her.\n\nRabbit felt scruffy to the touch. Almost dusty. It kicked a lot, Kara almost didn’t believe she caught it. She almost didn’t know what to do from here, but her hands held on with weird confidence. It was definitely stronger than a squirrel, maybe even stronger than a cat. Kara quickly grabbed it by the neck and squeezed tight. Next thing was the toughest.","n":60},{"chapter":"The map","text":"- Hey, do you have the weasel? - goblin shape appeared seemingly out of nowhere. Tallie must have run quite fast to catch up to Kara. She almost jumped at the surprise, but held her cool by shrugging it off in indifference.\n\n- I am not telling you unless you ask properly, - Kara was instantly mad. Tallie could slam her new hammer into her chest, she would probably care less. Though it was quite smart that Kara kept her front protected by a bag with a weasel. She couldn’t help but feel grateful for that much.\n\n- I already asked, - goblin didn’t seem aggressive, just concerned. Maybe she really cared about the black fur ball.\n\nKara felt a bit stupid. She had no reason to be mean to Tallie, beside the fact that she growled at her once or twice. She sighed and slowly showed the weasel to the goblin, - It looked really hurt. I tried to patch him up, but it might have caught something before.\n\nTallie visibly calmed down. Kara didn’t even know why she noticed that. Maybe she was still expecting a sudden attack.\n\n- Do you mind if I see the map? - Kara suddenly remembered that no one really had any idea where they were going. She was almost startled when after a low growl Tallie actually ducked her hand into her bag and took out the map. She opened it and all of a sudden Kara felt a bit uneasy. It was a large map of Septum. Kara had no idea that they never left their state. No one ever said that the central training ground coliseum of the hero tournament was in the most unstable area of the country. Well, no one ever said that heroes needed to be trained.\n\nOn the top of the map there was a note neatly written in red sharpie. It said to go towards the Riverside to get the next mission and to stay on the road. Kara examined the map to try and figure out where they could be. It seemed like they cut a good chunk of the way by cutting through mountains. Nothing about the village, it wasn’t even on the map.\n\nTallie folded the map and hid it back in her backpack, - Now can I have my weasel back? - Kara almost forgot about the critter in her bag. It looked so cozy in his little shelter.\n\n- Tallie, you can’t just throw him on the road if the fight breaks out. I will give it back when you prove that you can really take care of it properly, - Kara was suddenly very brave, she must have forgotten that this same little goblin woman just hammered a couple of crazy people to their death. Kara struggled to hit them even once. She didn’t even know who was better in this situation. They all still died in explosions. Well, explosions definitely finished them off. The memory made Kara shiver.\n\nTallie grunted at Kara, but the weasel stayed in the bag. The rest of the team caught up to them after a couple of minutes. They didn’t seem to hurry, but they must have been surprised that the goblin didn’t try to run away. At least Kara believed that she did something quite remarkable. Yet she said nothing when boys got close enough. She pretended to be preoccupied with Fluffer Huggins.","n":61},{"chapter":"The map","text":"- I don’t know, I do think it is quite crazy, - Kara spoke to herself looking at the potato plant that she replanted in the gorge. She felt quite stupid, but its not like trees could really judge her, - So what now? Do I give you a name or something?\n\nPotato plant didn’t budge. Kara almost tricked herself into waiting for a response. She thought about a fitting name for a hot minute. Then she felt stupid about announcing it out loud. It wasn’t like the potato plant had the capability to remark on it and it wasn’t like she had anyone else she would be talking to. She just wanted to talk to it. Maybe one day it would save her life having it nearby. Kara’s stomach turned.\n\n- Yeah, I don’t think I am ready to eat you, so don’t worry. We can be friends. People go keep flower gardens right? - Thoughts felt different when said out loud. They felt alive, she had to take pauses for breath and listen to the voice. They almost felt like they didn't belong to her at all. It was like she was listening to someone else.\n\n- No, I don’t have a name for you, - Kara could name him John, but the name was too simple for a first potato in her garden, - I will make a list and we can choose together.","n":62},{"chapter":"The map","text":"They walked by the road after the massacre. Counterintuitive, but there were no other clear shortcuts and, since Tallie wasn’t running ahead, no one really had other options. Kara just followed directions on the map by memory, which she wouldn’t trust completely but, so far, there were no road forks.\n\nMeanwhile Kara fed the weasel, apparently opening the entire world of animal handling to her green friend. Tallie got so excited when the weasel took food himself that Kara even caught herself smiling. She felt Rein piercing her with his glare from behind. It scared her. The weasel was sick.\n\n- Can we see the map now? - Rein called from behind and Kara felt a cold breeze. She stopped and turned to him. Tallie stopped with her facing some sort of dilemma in her head. It didn’t take her too long to take out the map and show it to everyone else. There were one or two annoyed sighs. Fezzik just shook his head. Kara was wondering if that was a better highlight of the day than the weasel care lessons. It wasn’t.\n\nThat night they stopped together. Rein picked out a spot and Kara stayed up for a bit longer making sure that Tallie wouldn’t try to steal the weasel during the night. Surprisingly the goblin didn’t seem to mind at all.\n\nShe couldn’t fall asleep and almost couldn’t believe that she did it so easily last night. She didn’t expect that thoughts about the weasel made her question her morality again. Why didn’t she just walk on? Did she seriously just save the weasel to get on the good side of her insane teammate? She held him hostage and yet he was better off with her. She would leave him in the forest without a second thought. She would even leave it if she saw it on the side of the road. The only reason she picked it up was because Tallie cared about it. It was a wild weasel and she prolonged its life by keeping it captive. She will be lucky if it develops Stockholms syndrome. Otherwise it would be hard to pretend that she means well for the fur ball. It would be fun to have a friend weasel. Pet, animal friends were pets.","n":63},{"chapter":"The map","text":"- Have you seen Fluffer Huggins? - Little Kara was looking under the wooden planks. She wasn’t worried, but she always checked there first. Kara glanced over at Rein, but he already closed the door behind him. Kara knew that she was supposed to be more ready for the bad news.","n":64},{"chapter":"The map","text":"Kara almost had a heart attack when she felt something touch the bag through her sleep. She instinctively hugged the bag with all intensity she could allow. She was so startled by the rapier pointed at her that she almost forgot to jump away. Why would someone want to kill the weasel? Kara almost screamed when she saw Rein.\n\n- What do you think you are doing? - Kara whispered to avoid waking up others.\n\n- We both know that it is better this way, - Rein didn’t hesitate. Neither did Kara.\n\nRein hit the bag barely avoiding hitting Kara and somehow dodging Fluffer Huggins pouncing to existence in an attempt to stop him. He must have been awake for quite some time, because he even enhanced his attack with some magic to make sure he finished the job. With a low thunderous thump the bag and the weasel flew into the treeline.\n\nKara never thought that she would ever be this scared to witness something that she predicted to be theoretically possible. Tallie hit Rein with a hammer around the same time Kara made the joke in her head. She will kill him now. It took Kara a moment to absorb the shock of the past twenty ish seconds of her being awake. She barely caught Rein as he was falling down from the blow. Haderach chanted something in a ghostly whisper and Tallie unnaturally screamed in fear as she ran off into the distance.\n\n- You just had to wake up the goblin, - Rein was muttering, barely composing himself for a conversation. Kara wondered how badly the lack of oxygen in mines could have damaged his cognitive thinking. How was it her fault?\n\n- You idiot, - Kara channeled her energy, but whatever she did didn’t look like quite enough. Orange glow seemed to need quite a bit of stamina and she couldn’t quite concentrate being half awake. There was a lot of blood, he must have had a punctured lung. Kara fixed her look on Tallie and stood up in front of Rein picking up her ax. She noticed bells ringing in her ears.\n\n- It’s the middle of the night, can everyone just calm down? - Fezek didn’t look happy. Kara wondered if this situation had happened before. How much of it was really her fault? Kara couldn’t help, but think that all of it. She didn’t expect Rein to try and kill the weasel, maybe she would if she was his friend. Why was she protecting him? She had more reasons to protect the weasel. Kara was mad, but she wouldn’t kill anybody over it. Tallie apparently would. Rein did. Somehow it all made sense considering that this situation was now their reality. Kara hated being in the middle of it, but it was the right thing to do. It gave her at least some ground to stand on. Better, but it didn’t mean she liked it.\n\n- You tell … - Kara was interrupted by a loud electric snap. She almost swinged at the figure that popped out of the darkness in front of her. She only stopped to admire the blue lights that echoed the shape of a human. She remembered the feeling.","n":65},{"chapter":"The map","text":"Kara has never seen flower buds before. Flowers either came in a bouquet or were such an unimportant part of the background that she never noticed. She liked to believe it was her first time. Like a love at first sight, like the fields of lavender that blooms once a year. The future fantasy of what was meant to come. This potato would have bloomed without her. Kara just chose where it was going to happen. She was quite proud that she did.","n":66},{"chapter":"The map","text":"Kara dropped the ax and jumped when it fell by her legs. She wasn’t sure why her arms gave up on her for a second. She felt scared, but quickly jumped to hold down Fluffer Huggins from firing at Taric. Her heart pounded in her ears as a flaming tom roared with a sudden burst of flames. It was a weird instinct reaction, but Kara felt like she always wanted to do that.\n\n- Still trying to kill us? - Victorian almost looked amused when he glanced at Fluffers.\n\n- Still expecting a different reaction? - Kara struggled with a flaming spirit trying to get his head out of the grapple, - Stay still won’t you?!\n\nFluffer Huggins stopped fighting and Kara felt the wave of disappointment course her body. It gave up so easily that Kara almost felt guilty giving this order. Taric spoke to Rein, Kara hoped that he was telling him off for killing the weasel. She didn’t listen.\n\n- What were you thinking of sending her in with us?! - Kara screamed at Taric, - It was obvious she was crazy!\n\nWords felt heavy in her mouth, she almost forced all of them. Tallie did react exactly how Kara would if anyone in the team would attempt to destroy potatoes in her hip bag. Insane and completely understandable. Maybe that’s what Fluffers hated so much about Taric. He forced unlikely friendships. Kara felt rage flood her mind as she pieced the puzzle pieces together.\n\n- So you are watching us? - Fezzik grabbed Taric’s attention just in time as Kara was about to scream something else. Or do. She almost panicked as her hand slowly slid down to count potatoes in the bag. Three, that’s right. Percival didn’t make it out of the pit. She wondered if she had time to mourn him. He died like Kara wanted him to live. Fighting without fear. Funny how far it had gotten him.\n\n- Don’t you think we have better things to care about than a freaking weasel? - Rein sounded furious. Kara almost instinctively raised her hand to slap Rein on the back of his head. That was no way to speak about an innocent animal that he just murdered. She must have swung quite hard.\n\n- Kara, there is no need for that, - Taric raised his hand and her whole body jolted in a halt. Fluffer Huggins sprung up with an angry roar, but that was the last thing he did before dissipating into thin air. Kara didn't see it happen, but the feeling was too familiar.\n\n- So did you guys fight like this too? - Fezzik didn’t sound happy at all. Kara didn’t expect that he would be the one losing his composure in this situation. She guessed that he was worried about Rein. She didn’t know why, but it was the only conclusion that made sense.\n\n- I bet they ate each other if these problems are so common, - Kara just wanted to sound spiteful, but she couldn’t hold a light hysterical chuckle. That’s right, Taric and Victorian were heroes that survived the tournament. Two out of six, the realization was cold and unforgiving. Out of fifty four heroes, a maximum of six can survive. Nine teams, all fighting for their lives. Even if you are alone you have a choice to win and survive or let the other team live to save others.\n\n- Good question, what happened to the rest of your team? - Fezzik caught on to Kara’s thought. She felt even colder. No one watched the hero tournaments, it was something for children to worry about. Colorful scenes, bright lights, superpowers. These were by no means useful to those who faced the reality of their lives. Normal people rarely saw the nearly guaranteed death as a career pathway and it wasn’t like they were even guaranteed a spot. Rein volunteered and still ended up in the pit. No research could have prepared him for that, nobody talked about it. No one knew about it. Heroes didn’t live among normal people for a very good reason, Kara knew first hand.\n\n- Well, do you see them? - Taric sounded jaded. Kara was almost thrown off by how easily words flew out of his mouth, - Well, there you go. They are probably dead, - Taric didn’t give much time for the thought to sink in, - And if you are going to keep fighting with each other you all will end up just like them.\n\nKara suddenly understood why she picked up the damned weasel. She wasn’t trying to be friends with Tallie. She was just trying to survive, it only made sense. Her stomach turned at a thought. She chose to prolong the suffering of a poor wild animal just because she wanted to survive. Never in her life she thought that she would feel guilty in front of a dead weasel.\n\nVictorian talked to Tallie and she calmed down. She started heading to the bushes where the weasel flew off into, Kara followed her. It was her bag, even if she was scared of what she was going to find in it. Kara was glad Taric beat her to it. Her heart skipped a beat when he took out a dark lifeless silhouette out of it. It was hard not to think about it.\n\nKara never felt so hopeful when bright white light shone in the palms of Taric. She thought that it was brighter than the sun itself. It was barely enough to light up Taric’s face. She fell down to her knees and hid her face in her palms to hide her face. She fought hard to not look too happy. It didn’t make sense, she wasn’t attached to the weasel at all, but it was nice to know that it was alive. One less thing to regret and one more to worry about. It was a questionable balance.","n":67},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"Are we responsible for those who we have tamed? Forever is a long time, but it sounds pretty fair. Someone said these words and it caught on. Now Kara was sitting down cursing the feelings that mixed as she remembered how big was the responsibility that she took upon her shoulders. Maybe she should have let Rein kill the damn thing. Maybe she would do it herself if she was stronger.\n\n- Here you go, Tallie, - Taric handed the weasel to the goblin as she rushed towards him, - Now you have no reason to kill your teammates, so calm down, - he sounded soft, much softer than when he spoke to the rest of the team. At least Kara thought that she noticed that. She didn’t blame Tallie, she was just a bit scared when the goblin suddenly attacked Rein. She would choose Reins life over weasels, Tallie was just on the other side of the scale. Kara wondered at what point she got in the middle of this. Was it when she chose to save the weasel or when she decided to use it as a leverage for a map? Why didn’t she give it back to Tallie in exchange?","n":68},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"- You know what, I am just going to call you Optimus Fotch, - Kara almost laughed at how silly the name sounded, but it wasn’t like anyone would ever hear it. She was pretty sure that if someone would ever find out that she is speaking to one specific potato plant in the forest the name would at least break some ice, - Optimus because I need some positivity in life and Fotch because Prime would sound too pretentious for a potato, - Kara raised an eyebrow at her own explanation, - Yeah, sorry I had to be real with you there, buddy.\n\nShe swinged her ax back on her shoulder. She spent seven hours in the library researching good methods of survival in the woods today and completely forgot to make a list of names. Well, not completely. She just thought that she could do it later, but the awkward silence was killing her mind as she was chopping the tree for firewood and building material.\n\n- I will go back to work, but if you think of something feel free to shout it out, ok, - Kara sincerely enjoyed the sarcasm in her voice. Optimus Fotch seemed to be flawless at his job.","n":69},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"It took a minute for Kara to pick herself up. She just witnessed a full death defying resurrection of a weasel and most she could think about is that why on earth she even cares about the stupid rodent. She didn’t even care that death no longer was certain in her world. Maybe she was crazy.\n\n- Hey, - Kara approached Tallie and reached out to pet the weasel that was looking more alive than ever, which wasn’t saying a lot. It still appeared quite weak, but he moved with a bit more confidence, - I guess this sprout deserves a name, - Kara tried to smile, but the sentence felt heavy on her chest. It took Tallie a couple of seconds, but she was ready before Kara got the chance to join in. She was grateful for that.\n\n- Charcoal, - goblins voice was stern and yes pleased. There was no going back and Kara knew it way too well. Now Charcoal could die any second too and the poor thing had no say in the situation whatsoever. And they could not keep it in a zipped hip bag.\n\n- That’s a great name, Tallie, - Kara pulled another smile. Maybe she should have let Fluffer just be Huggins all those years ago. It could have saved her from some of the pain.","n":70},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"- You know what, why not? - Rein was getting a bit angry, - We can go and look for Fluffers, but don’t be surprised if we don’t find him, - he stood up and dusted his pans, more of a habit. Their playtime trousers were the opposite definition of clean. It didn’t help that their parents were spending an unusual amount of time at work this time of the year. Kara always wondered why.\n\n- Well, it is definitely more fun than your stupid game, - little Kara puffed as she stood up. She almost never beat Rein in the games he made up and when she did it felt severely exhausting. It was never worth it anyway and today she figured out the best way of getting out of it. She was almost proud. Almost.\n\n- Well, someone is a sore loser, - Rein saw right through her little gig, but it was her best defeat so far today. She felt like he had his fair share of fun. Maybe they will find something better to do on the streets. Kara wondered why she had to be so worried about Huggins right now. Rein wasn’t at all.","n":71},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"Kara spent the rest of the night with Tallie that retreated back into the forest now that the weasel was back in her possession. She picked up her bag, but the rest of the camping material had to stay in the main camp as Tallie did not care to come back and Kara was afraid to lose her again. Boys could deal with Rein themselves. Kara took a night on the bare ground to get out of even a chance of being a bigger part of that. He was Fezziks problem now.\n\nShe woke up sore, but satisfied. Tallie woke Kara up when she jumped down from the tree. Almost intentionally. Kara was grateful nevertheless, it would have been painful to wake up with her gone in the woods. It would have defeated the purpose of her escape from Reins mindgame. It wasn’t good at all.\n\n- Do you know how to carry Charcoal correctly? - Kara barely woke up, but already was frustrated that Tallie wasn’t paying proper attention to her pet. She was so sleepy that she almost forgot to be surprised at the fact that the goblin didn’t growl and simply nodded and proceeded to comfort the rodent in her bag.","n":72},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"Kara was mesmerized by the white flowers. It was part of a simple habit that helped. Well, it could have been. Kara didn’t question the urge to stare deep into the white to discover every almost invisible vein on the petals. She pretended to see the water move inside of it. She almost felt like she was moving it herself. Just so that she would have an excuse to stay in this moment for a bit longer. At some point she felt tired and closed her eyes.\n\nShe didn’t think too hard about it. The ground felt so soft, she wondered if she could ever resist this blissful feeling. It was one of the warmer days, a little nap wasn’t too bad of an idea. Her clothes were already dirty. Nothing would change in twenty minutes. Not in the woods, very unlikely. And if it did, she might have already died, so why worry about it. Luckily animals still were somewhat wary of humans. And it wasn’t like Kara was the most helpless one around either. Good thing that school did a good job brainwashing children into this belief. Good thing that humans did the same thing historically to animals. Kara might have never made it this far if this wasn’t the case. Privilege of being human.","n":73},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"Group reunited, closing eyes on their morale, and proceeded their way as normal. Almost by normal team standards. Tallie was sharing the map and happily feeding Charcoal small snacks every now and then. Rein was staying a safe distance back. He still looked quite angry, but at least he was not about to act up on it anymore. For now at least. Kara was happy to have this break. She would take whatever moment of peace she could get as the team began to feel much more crowded as they started talking and looking at each other. Fezzik told some of the interesting things that he did before he met Rein. Mainly how he knew Reins and Kara’s fathers. Pure professional friendship, no sentiments for each other and pure manliness. Floats shared a couple jokes. He might have been serious sometimes, but his never changing tone seemed to make everything he said so flamboyant. It didn’t help that one of his aspirations was to find a magic bean that grows into a giant statue of him.\n\nHaderach seemed to disappear at some point as he was constantly on the other side of Floats. And he was a halfling.","n":74},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"Why would little Kara care if Huggins would even run away. It wasn’t like she was the one who took him out of that box. Now Kara only wanted to put him into another so that he wouldn’t run away again. It was understandable why he would run away. He was an adult tom cat with plenty of energy and strong will to survive. Kara blocked all other thoughts. Soft kitty, warm kitty. Little ball of fur.\n\nIt didn’t matter at all. Whatever that furry ball was thinking when he ran away little Kara had the box ready. She had enough. Happy kitty, sleepy kitty. She hummed the rest nervously, it was pretty dark outside - Pur, pur, pur.","n":75},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"- Yeah, I would offer Rein help myself, but you know these horrific roads and message systems, - Fezzik was genuinely telling the truth, but why did it sound like he apologized, - To be honest when your dad said that Rein might have to find a job I didn’t even know that his dad was gone, - Kara never knew that her father helped Rein to go to mines. She thought that he was against that idea. Kara almost wanted to believe her dad was the only one who helped Rein to go to these horrible mines. All so that Fezzik could have had his retribution. Man literally followed Rein into the Heroes Tournament. All because he felt guilty for that one time he didn’t receive the message in time to react accordingly to the poor boy's situation. Maybe Kara was just grateful that someone was standing up for Rein when she didn’t want to.\n\n- Dam, no wonder you guys don’t talk, - Kara felt like something was watching her from behind, - You know a heads up could have been nice on the whole monitoring situation, - What Fezzik shared instantly sparked the memory in her mind. He did talk like her and Reins fathers. Formal, appropriate with a sprinkle of softness. She could almost swear she heard this name before now. He was here to protect Rein, she could respect that. She had no idea who it was though. Rein probably didn’t either. She felt safe by his side, even if he wasn’t going to grab a bullet for her. He would for Rein. She wanted to believe that and she knew she could. Adults don’t lie to children. They just never say the whole truth and Fezzik acted like an adult. To be honest Kara never understood the concepts of benefits from lies. Other than that they made pretty nice jokes. And adults sure loved their jokes.\n\n- Yep, - Fezzik was abrupt, he must have forgotten about the invisible eye. Kara was wondering if she was responsible for something extremely unpleasant in the near future. If police would hear him talk about bad roads he could have easily gotten into trouble. If they had a bad day for example.\n\n- Sorry, - Kara lowered her voice and continued the way. None of them looked distressed, it was like they had some innate command to keep their best behavior. And it wasn’t magic, more like an ignorant normality of everything that was happening. They were just walking all day and slept at night. Night shifts were producing most conversations, sometimes based on the fact that Rein should not be even unaccompanied within the proximity of the weasel. It didn’t make sense, but Tallie would have made it one way or another. It was a fair trade off. Also Kara never thought that the roads in between cities in Septum were so quiet. They never saw more than two people going from town to town. Sometimes they saw the flying convois of ships, but there was really no way to know if they even had pilots. It was fun to watch thought and Kara would follow their path whenever she would spot them on the horizon. She probably looked like a know nothing forest girl. Oh wait… That’s exactly what she was.\n\nScratch that, she looked at the ships because she liked looking at the ships and she will get bored when she will get bored. Redundant, but sometimes Kara had to remind herself that she had to preserve her sanity until she would even get the chance to return to the gorge in the forest. Was she even ever truly in that disgusting place? She wished she could ask some questions about the invisible eye, but she didn’t even know where to look.\n\nThere was nothing else to do. Kara looked at the ships because there was nothing else to do, but imagine how many people each convoy held. How many people were involved in online piloting. If those were even people. Amen.","n":76},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"- Bander will snatch Teresa if you don’t grow harder Vincent, - Kara whispered gently to Vincent, wishing that he would truly hear her plea. The thought was on the brink of insanity, she was talking to herself again. And again. And again. And again. Why didn’t she come up more often to the boys in school? They were always more fun than the girls. Kara was always a bit jealous of the nonchalant attitude of her classmates to each other. They gossiped, spread lies, spread truth, spread everything that was not supposed to be spread without any concern. Kara could destroy all of them with all the things that she heard just by sitting at the girls table. She wondered what it would be like to have to genuinely have a choice, not the last option.\n\n- Nice joke, right? Who am I kidding? - Kara facepalmed so hard it hit her nose cartilage, - You guys don’t read books, you guys don’t watch TV, you don’t even know who of you related to whom. You are so boring sometimes! - Kara tried to sound soft, but she needed some action in her lungs.\n\n- And I am no better, - She defeated herself, - Who on earth runs away into the forest to talk to potatoes? They don’t even belong there. Congratulations, Kara, - she didn’t say out loud that the reward that she just gave her sane bit of mind was the Darwin's Award. That would render all her efforts ultimately useless. There was really something special about the potatoes that she could tell apart. It was something that didn’t belong to anyone, but was the product of her own choices. Her repetitive choices to chase the same choice. Just because it promised to always be there for her if she was there to make it. She blindly learned to love this feeling as if she was born to do that exact thing all her life. That perspective never scared her before and probably never will. Quite romantic, isn’t it? Why did she write that essay? It cost her the grade and it wasn’t even funny. It was sad. But, she was one happy preschool Kara.\n\n- Sorry Bander, but Teresa is already with Vincent. I decided, - Kara no longer wanted to bargain destiny. It’s not like either three of them had any choice in how she will pair them up. One had to go or Kara would run out of names she could remember. She already forgot the acronym behind Optimus Fotch. Maybe not fully, but it was unlikely for her to remember the pattern in which names succeeded each other. She forgot her own code and today was the day when she drew the line of spilling her own emotions on poor potatoes. She will get a job and she will turn back to society for help. Even without access to any keys. She needed a new way of storing what she had and currently that was the ax. Everything else she didn’t technically own, it was illegal to have proof on any of it. Not the little hut that she built with unauthorized logs that she legally chopped down. Not the potatoes that grew wildly on the wild ground. She technically didn’t even need to own them. She just wanted to have them all to herself. Sounds pretty greedy without context.","n":77},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"- Have you ever thought why people break the ceiling to talk to the god, but a fourth wall if they want to let other people into their lives, - Floats was making one of those weird jokes that only sounded like jokes. The ones with the upbeat ending. Man definitely did not know how uncomfortable he made Kara, for whom both of the options sounded like a very cold winter. She would hate it even more if others were the ones doing the breaking. Kara would definitely join the fun if somebody else told her that the building needs demolition anyway. Heck, she would even join if the man was just going insane and asked her to do it at his home. Of course the craziness in that would lie only if he purposefully lied to Kara. She would definitely want someone to help her burn her little house if she was this fed up with potatoes. She wouldn’t even mind burning that fire alive if she was ever that convinced that she was crazy. That’s why it was much easier in the forest. Easier not to hurt anyone if the only person there to hurt is you. From there you can choose if it's cowardice or pride. If it’s cowardice you go and change it, if it’s pride admit and live with it. Cowards do tend to survive a lot better than narcissists. Second ones just prefer to die in blissful ignorance.\n\n- Did you break a ceiling when you jumped really high one time in life or something? - Rein spoke for the first time today, so everyone listened, - Can you stop with these jokes, they are not even funny?\n\nKara chuckled, Floats did look like he would do something like that. She didn’t even know why, it must have been that story about magical beans. Hard to take someone seriously when he talks so seriously about nonsense and jokes out of que. And yet it wasn’t far off of things that were looping inside her head. It was a fine edge.\n\nThey were sitting at the tavern two days earlier than expected. Probably beaten some records with viewers, or got hatred for not saving the god forsaken village. On top of stupid jokes by Floats, Kara barely had the patience to fight the audience. Haderach had already left the table before they even got to the first round of simple soda and Rein didn’t even walk into the tavern. He just sat outside with Fluffer Huggins and Kara had zeroest of the clues why she would even get triggered by the stupid joke made by an insane man. She already knew that flaming tom would set fire to an entire place and she had no idea how to just easily turn him off like Taric did. Why would Taric even have a way to control Fluffer Huggins? And for the love of all gods, why didn’t he tell her the trick if he was so smart?\n\n- So what’s your story, Floats? - Kara was done and asked the question, - What do you want out of this tournament?\n\n- I want wealth and all the shiny things that capital brings, - Kara almost dropped her head on the table with passion of powerful repetition. Good thing she was better than this much.\n\n- What do you want?\n\nSilence.\n\n- What do you like? For the mother of all mothers, say something, - Kara no longer had faith in this man.\n\n- I like oranges, - three words worked like a cold shower for both of them. Kara was shocked how precisely she understood Floats by his face expression after this phrase. She asked more questions to be polite and he silently let her. Orange oranges are not original. He was trying to remember.","n":78},{"chapter":"Your story","text":"The essay asked you to write about how you would describe yourself. Kara Toham finally remembered. It was so long ago. It must have been less than a hundred words or something. She did it as a joke, then it got dark. She felt the heat in her cheeks. Potatoes. She was the potato savior. Back then she thought it was so funny and original. The most original love confession to the most unoriginal vegetable. She wrote a whole story describing someone fictional, knowing gosh darn too well that she was none of these things. She wished for her last meal to be the best potato dish that has ever existed.","n":79},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"- You like oranges? - Kara raised both of her eyebrows in amazement, - Like orange oranges?\n\n- Yes, - Floats was surprised himself. It seemed to touch something that warmed his senses. Not something that Kara felt about the potatoes, but something terrifically vague, - They taste quite sweet, actually, - Floats was a bit cautious with his words, but still not that concerned. Kara was done. The alcohol in the soda must have started working. It really starts tasting like water after a while.","n":80},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"Fluffer Huggins was chasing the ribbon like it was his first time, every time. That’s what Kara was tricked to believe by the kitten every time he went for it. Well, basically, it always took a lot of effort to get him interested. However, Kara enjoyed it. Even if the little thing would sometimes never even look her way.\n\n- Kara, stop! You are going to trip on something! - Rein was extremely frustrated, he would never go into a backyard dumpster for a game of chase. Kara wondered why he was this scared to get one or two scratches here and there. Yes, there were some bicycle parts and sharp plastics, but none of them could cut deep enough to be scared for life. Maybe scarred, but sometimes scars do something good for attention. That cat on the road would definitely have some scars if it had survived.\n\n- Oh, please Rein, you fell once, - Kara leaped over the tire and picked a clear space to land. She landed safely, but her legs felt wobbly for a second and she stopped letting Fluffers catch the ribbon. The game has ended. His claw got stuck on the fabric and little tom didn’t show any interest to let go. He even looked a bit confused by the situation.","n":81},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"It wasn’t that hard to find the main building. It was the only other place in town guarded heavily by the police beside the gates. Even more surprising was that no one really cared about Fluffer Huggins. Adults kept their distance and children just followed with their heads as if flaming tom was a regular stray. The walls around this town were much taller and it itself was much smaller than Kara was used to. She wondered if locals were allowed to leave to get higher education.\n\nShe broke into cold sweat for a second realizing that she already skipped almost a month of the application season. She would never get the chance to apply for the Quattor transfer now. She didn’t even know if heroes could apply for the transfer. Sure thing she could visit Quattor, but own a plantation there as a hero from Septum? It doesn't even sound right. Kara didn’t even know why it upset her so much. Considering the fact that she was lucky to be alive it felt a bit wrong to sulk about something that was improbable to begin with. It still hurts that she didn’t even get a chance. It could have been super fun to live in Quattor.","n":82},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"- They really make it hard to figure out how to get out of Septum legally, - Kara was plowing away in her little garden, - I mean, I could look for a job there, but they will require experience proof and I can’t really say that I am a farmer, - she swinged once more and rubbed of some sweat off of her forehead, - I am pretty sure this college is really the easiest route, but I don’t know if I could get in. Even if I ask all my classmates to tank agronomy, it won’t really guarantee me a spot. No one really did it before, well maybe they did, but they haven't stayed in Septum to tell the story or share tips.\n\n- I know, right? Crazy! Why would you stay in Septum if your whole goal was to leave in the first place? - Kara chuckled at her small ironic situation. She would never look back at the place that she left, but she didn’t really have much to leave. She barely knew anyone here, almost no one knew her, - I mean, if someone really wants to change something in their life so drastically, it is almost sensible that you let them figure it out by themselves, - Kara felt quite content with this thought. It was precisely what she was doing and she thought that he was doing quite alright on that path.\n\n- No, I actually don’t know if they would let me take you guys with me. I guess I will have to figure out a way to smuggle you out with me, unless you want to stay. I am pretty sure you would be fine here without me, - Kara smiled. Potatoes never made her worry about anything. She was fine with or without them, she just had to believe that they were safe in the forest where Kara left them. Sometimes she believed that this is how true love feels. Kara never felt truly exhausted from working in the garden. Only happily tired and when she was, the potatoes were there to provide a cool shade while she was resting in the trenches. She knew their smell by heart and their names by leaves. She would never be able to sleep under lavender. It must have been too strong and obnoxious when it bloomed.","n":83},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"Kara couldn’t quite figure out what was the purpose of this building in this town. It looked more like a mansion than anything else, but it was ridiculously big for one family to live in. Kara wondered why one would even build something like that. It reminded her of the orphanage. She almost hoped to see children inside, but the horror of the situation made her shiver. She hoped there were no children in this mansion.\n\nThe police let them in without any questions. They just silently watched them go inside. It was so quiet Kara almost believed that the doors could be locked. They did arrive early.","n":84},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"- Who is there? - Kara was cautious to open the door. Her parents would never forget or lose their keys. It was pretty late in the evening for visitors, specially at the front door.\n\n- Kara, open the door, - she did not recognise the voice at all, but the man knew her name. He also wasn’t alone. They could break the door if they wanted to. It would give Kara some time to run, but where to? She didn’t really know where her parent’s office was, she only been there once, - We need to talk.\n\n- Alright, - Kara took a deep breath and fought her urge to hide. She opened the door and almost jumped when she saw the uniform. She never saw the police this close. They didn’t barge in straight away, but their intent gazes almost forced her to step out of the way as they stepped inside. They looked around for a minute and turned back to Kara. She still stood by the door a little shocked at the visit. Children should trust the police, everyone should. Kara though that running away was dumb, but that was exactly what she wanted to do.\n\n- Kara, you have to come with us. Your parents are not coming home, - the same man spoke again and Kara shivered a bit. She knew that the moment she opened the door. She just hoped that she didn’t. She could have acted more appropriately then, maybe a bit more shocked, maybe she would even lose her balance. Maybe then she would cry. However now it all was spoiled by a stupid hinch of previous knowledge.\n\n- What happened? - Kara sounded coldly curious, she hoped that it was the part of her that believed that situation wasn’t as grave as it looked. She wasn’t surprised when her questions weren't answered. She didn’t even pick up any of her things as she followed the men out of the door, strictly following the instructions. It was a harsh rule, but the one that people somehow knew innately. Trust the police or risk dying if they are in a bad mood. It wasn’t like Kara had anything she wanted to keep in this house either. None of these possessions seemed quite as important as the fact that her life was now forever changed. Maybe she was just too busy trying to figure out why she wasn't crying. There was something that she forgot in there, she couldn’t remember why it was so unimportant that she left it. So she did.","n":85},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"Inside the woman with olive skin greeted them as if she was waiting for them all evening. She for sure knew that they were at the tavern. For some reason Kara was surprised to see her, almost pleasantly. With so much brutality happening around, that woman was gracefully unphased by the whole situation and smiled ever so slightly. Toham prayed to her potato gods that she wasn’t aware of all the murderer that has happened. Maybe everyone just got resurrected like the weasel. Kara was too scared to ask.\n\n- Well, you are here early, - the woman with the olive skin sounded different without microphones and up close. More human somehow. Kara stepped toward her, almost mesmerized that the same white dress she saw on the day of the criminal feast was now so ridiculously close to her. Floats beat her to it.\n\n- Oh my, oh my. This is the most exquisite fabric! Where do I get it? - he sounded extra annoying and Kara rolled her eyes. She hated to admit defeat, Floats appeared to be much more fit for this kind of things.\n\n- In time, my dear, in time, - woman smiled ever so gently. Kara tried really hard to remember her name, but she was never good at those. She was a never changing face for their state for as long as Kara could remember, but the last five years in the forest must have flushed that memory away for good. She will remember when she hears it.\n\nWoman greeted them and said something about their training, Kara did not listen. She was tired and woozy and at some point miss olive skin must have noticed her staring off into some red velvet chair. It looked quite intriguing.\n\n- Glad to finally see you again, Kara, - olive woman spoke as if she knew Kara for quite a long time. Kara physically felt the irritation in the ears as she heard her own name. She was getting tired of people knowing her name for no clear reason. This trick was getting increasingly old and the woman was extremely lucky Kara knew how to stop Fluffer Huggins by now.\n\n- Are heroes allowed to keep potato gardens? - Kara will never know why out of all the questions in the world she decided to ask this one. Such a deep and sincere one that she must have sounded completely crazy. But, to be honest, there was simply nothing else that interested her in that specific conversation.\n\n- What? - Miss Olive sounded confused for a second. She for sure thought Kara was quite far gone, - Honey, you can get all the gardens you want if you win the tournament, - Kara didn’t even feel a tingle from that answer. The goal was achieved and the obvious answer used. Next time Kara will have to come up with a new one.\n\n- Good to know, - Kara resumed watching the chair.","n":86},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"There was nothing funny about it. The mouse was lying dead with a crushed skull right on the porch. Fluffers left it there right after he heard Kara wake up. He must have. It looked too fresh. Kara looked away as a first instinct and it took all her courage to look down again and see what she was seeing. It even became interesting after some point. She could see where the skull was crushed and even noticed the fur was still a bit wet around the area. It would have all dried up if it was there all night. Kara wondered if that’s how detectives work when cracking a case.\n\n- Mom, Fluffers killed a mouse again.","n":87},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"When Kara finally got to go to bed she wasn’t really looking forward to staying alone in the room. Though she got quite used to not talking to people in their presence, it was heart tearing not being able to speak to potatoes in her bag. She didn’t want anyone to know about them, the more they knew the more they suffered. How did Victorian know there was Vinsent, but didn’t know which one he was. How didn’t he know that they all could be Vincent? Whatever it was, Kara was not going to give away anything else. She couldn’t speak to potatoes, even if it was exactly what they wanted. Kara wasn’t about to risk it all for a petty style that she developed to talk to herself.\n\nShe talked to them silently, but it got boring too quickly. It usually did when Vincent was getting all sassy about being a scapegoat. Kara felt deeply guilty for her mistake and the only saving grace was in the fact that Vincent was just a dormant potato root. He wasn’t a human like the five probably dead people that did or did not make it this far. Kara even joked in her head that she knew for sure that those people were dead. Unlike the weasel, she for sure could not deny it in her head. Weasel could have died, the five people did. One woman and four men. Not like their gender mattered at all. Well, maybe a little. Kara didn’t have time to see the ratio of men to women in the pit. Not like it was the greatest of her concerns, but there were no women in the group that chased her first. It was 8 men. Three of them had to die to make room for her, the rest died because they followed the ax. Woman died with the help of Percival. At the price of Percival too. Five people and one potato. Kara didn’t remember why she wanted that woman dead more. Was it because she was protecting Rein or because she was mad at Percivals demise? It was a clear shot. Then there was the last man. He didn’t even see Kara swinging her ax. If Kara knew ahead of time she would let Tallie just finish the job, but instead Kara blindly rushed for the action. Why did she do that? Tallie could have killed her. She was very close.\n\n- I am so sorry Percival, I will miss you. A lot, - Kara was staring at the ceiling feeling immense shivers all around the body. The trade didn’t seem fair at all. She lost more than she gained and what she gained wasn’t even clear in its definition. A chance for three potatoes and herself. Well, three potatoes didn’t have a chance without her anyway and she currently had no other value but those three potatoes. So a chance for three potatoes and Rein. That’s right, Percival died to save Rein. Weasel survived to save Rein. Kara did not like making this connection, but it had to be done. Three, however, is still more than one. Even if that one is a human. Kara could not control his safety with her choices and she was just barely able to do that for potatoes. Her options relied heavily on her ability to react quickly and choose fast, which is hard to do when the question is life and death. When will Kara stop fooling herself and admit that she did this all for her own selfish survival? Hopefully before it’s too late.","n":88},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"- Rein, why didn’t you come to school today? - Kara was worried. Rein didn’t come out in time and when Kara knocked on his door no one answered.\n\n- I took my sister to hospital, she got worse, - Rein wasn't reassuring. Kara hated her question now, she should have known. She should have shut up.\n\n- It’s bad? - Kara did not know what else to say. The question had an obvious answer and an easy one. No one goes to hospital if it’s not bad. Not early in the morning. Unless she hit a corner of the table while stabbing her toe on the cupboard.\n\nRein didn’t answer. Kara didn’t ask again.","n":89},{"chapter":"Still here?","text":"Kara did have a dream that night. It was a nice dream. Percival was alive and well with Lillean, Perry and Mark. She told them everything that happened and they listened like they always did. Kara knew that Persival would forgive her and Persival knew that Kara would die if he didn’t. Saying that, Kara was lucky to wake up that morning. If the dream was bad she would not want to remember it for too long. She was glad she did, though.\n\nShe was fully dressed when someone knocked on her door. When she opened the door there was no one at it, but the rest of the heroes were heading back to the common room. It wasn’t too early in the morning. The red velvet chair was still in his place, now glittering in the rays of morning sun. Kara hoped that she could see Miss Olive's annoyed look as she would see Kara getting distracted on the same object again. She couldn’t look at the chair and into amber eyes at the same time and not break the thin ice of interpersonal space. It would happen if she didn’t look to check and she could decide how real it was afterwards.\n\n- I hope you guys rested well, today is going to be a tough day. We got something special prepared for each of you, - Miss Olive was quite excited. She must have had fun preparing for these training sessions, - We are going to split you into groups. Kara you will follow me, rest wait for Taric.\n\nKara shivered, feeling that her teasing games for sure must have had their effect. Quite a negative one too. Miss Olive must have noticed Kara in the pit, how much did she see? Well, everything, probably. Kara didn’t like that it wasn’t so obvious what Miss Olive was thinking. She wasn’t just following orders, she was part of the decisions. She was in control of their freedom. Maybe not her own, but Kara didn’t choose what she was going to see behind the door at the end of this corridor. Miss Olive did. Kara chuckled.\n\n- What is it, dear? - Miss Olive was almost waiting to ask that question and Kara was startled by that readiness.\n\n- I remembered a funny joke about hallways, - Kara spoke as if she was speaking to potatoes. It was hard to explain everything to clueless tubers, - Most of the time we return from them the same way we walked in.\n\n- Well, that could be said about any of the rooms, - it must have been quite hard to get Miss Olive unfazed. She did smile slightly though. Kara was wondering how polite it was.\n\n- Not rooms, - Kara skeptically shook her head, - but doorways maybe, - she shrugged her shoulders a bit. Nit picking at wording was the easiest way to win stupid arguments. Requires least amount of compromises. You don’t have to agree on principle to describe it in a senseless way. Potatoes don’t care either way, they would believe anything.\n\n- Right, - light chuckle of miss Olive somehow calmed Kara down for a bit. Maybe it wasn’t serious training afterall. Kara could ask a direct question, but did it really matter? Hallway wasn’t long enough for her to think about the strategy and false theories on insufficient information could prove to be uselessly biased anyway. Not like Kara expected to die at the other side of this door and impressing her trainers with exceptional results didn’t quite fit on her schedule. Could it have helped her to excel in her ability to survive? Maybe, but how interested was she in that? Was her potato dream worth fifty three lives that it now required as a bare minimum? Would she want to be the one that makes that sacrifice? Kara knew all the answers to these questions, she just didn’t want to admit that her answers didn’t quite fit the situation that she was in. Uselessly biased answers. Her simple dream shouldn’t have had this price to begin with. It didn’t make any sense whatsoever and yet it was her reality.\n\nThe door opened and Kara saw a weirdest looking room. It was like she entered an underground city river cross section. Three bridges to connect four corners. All illuminated by soft white lamps and built from big square stones and concrete. Kara was surprised how empty it was and how clean it looked, despite the moss growth by the water. It didn’t look like anything that would fit in the mansion or under it. It was too ridiculously old fashioned, but it did look very real and strangely cozy.\n\n- Alright, you stay here, - Miss Olive made a step and disappeared into thin air in dim light blue spark of light only to reappear from the similar fashion on the far end of the room, - Now, my dear, you need to come through him to get to me, - woman didn’t shout, but her voice was loud enough to just about go over the sound of the river. She pointed at a short man standing in front of the first bridge. Kara didn’t like the sound of her next task.","n":90},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"It was like a shiver, but Kara barely felt it. She expected a training, but something about this short man told her that he isn’t there to take it easy on her.\n\n- Hello there, - Kara was wondering whether there was a chance this was a riddle man. The chance was skewed ever so slightly towards unlikely, - Can I pass by you, please? - She could have asked for a riddle straight away, but she didn’t want to be mean.\n\n- Oh my, no one usually asks so politely, - short man seemed to be quite calm. Amused even, - I guess then you can pass.","n":91},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Kara slept under a fallen tree. It was quite a warm night and her limbs didn’t feel as bad as she expected. Well, she wasn’t quite betting on waking up, but the weather seemed to be pushing for another sunny day. Kara never felt so free. The bright sun shone right into her eyes and she almost mindlessly was staring right back at it ignoring the uncomforting burn. Her back felt stiff, but it still motivated Kara to raise up and shake off the pine needles from her hair.\n\nIt took her a solid minute to stand up. She didn’t particularly know what to do, she just knew that whatever she decides didn’t involve laying down. Kara had a plan, but it was quite concerningly tiresome and terribly vague. Still, it was better than trying to figure out the world that she left behind. Less chaotic.","n":92},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Kara was just about to pass by his shoulder when the short man spoke again, - Hey, in such a rush? Don’t you think it would be polite to ask me a name? - Kara almost swung her ax in fear, but a sudden thought somehow instantly startled her. The man appeared to be a halfling, just like Haderach. Was he also a hero once? Maybe there was a way to fail some sort of qualification to get out of the tournament.\n\n- Oh, sorry, I do forget to do that quite a lot, - Kara smiled and turned to face him, - What’s your name? - If this was a friendship test, she failed miserably and now the outcome was determined.\n\n- There we go. My name is Enur, - halfling gave her a friendly smile. Cold, calculated and unforgiving friendly smile, - And I can’t actually let you pass the bridge.","n":93},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Rein was looking somewhere deep in the ginger fur. It was sprinkled with brownish red speckles, - Looks like Fluffers got into another fight. This black old one apparently has quite a bit of feist left in him. Who would have known.\n\nIt was quite amazing, actually. Old Tomson, the son of Tom, suddenly felt challenged by the presence of young challenger Fluffer Huggins. Kara would be impressed, if something inside didn’t burn with a weird hate. Tomson crossed the line. Not like little Kara liked him a lot to begin with. He was loud and backbiting and now he hurt Fluffer Huggins, something that Kara didn’t know how to justify. It just seemed unnecessarily mean.","n":94},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"- Well then, we have quite a pickle, - Kara didn’t know what she was stalling for, - I guess I will try not to hurt you as much? - she wasn’t quite sure what else was there to say, - So how do we start it? - She felt increasingly uncomfortable from her own words. She didn’t really want to be the first one to swing, otherwise she would have already done so.\n\n- I’ll let you start, - Enur smiled politely before his face started deforming into what looked like a bear muzzle. Kara saw a lot of interesting things by now, but halfling's transformation was almost perfectly uncanny. She raised an eyebrow as she felt her heart skip a beat or two. She kept staring at the empty space as the now giant brown bear moved in front of her to block the bridge. It looked way bigger than Kara expected and she uncomfortably wondered if that's how big they were in the wild. She has only seen black ones before. It stood still and Kara felt a strange upbeat in her chest. He was waiting for her to move, so she swung at him.","n":95},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"She wished she had an ax with her. Though maybe not. Kara wasn’t sure if she wanted to have any excuse to initiate the situation. Wild wolf looked a bit bigger than her normal stray dog, she wasn’t sure if she could just intimidate it to go away. They looked straight at each other from the opposite sides of the gorge. Kara looked intently and was wondering if it was looking at her with hunger or just plain interest. It proved to be neither, as the wolf just simply went back into the forest. Kara wondered if that would be different in the middle of winter, but that was a worry for the future. For now she had to go back to the town and find some tools that could help in her small endeavor.","n":96},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"There is a reason why people don’t confront wild life one on one, despite being the apex predator of the planet. Giant bear barely flinched as the ax slid across its shoulder. The fur was thick and muscles even thicker. Kara scolded herself in her own head for being so recklessly confident. Why did she think that going against the bear, even with her new powers, was a great idea? She tried to step backwards, however, once initiated, the fight must go on.\n\nEnur the bear growled and bit into Kara’s shoulder almost dislocating it right on impact. Fluffer Huggins exploded into existence behind the bear as the smell of burnt fur filled up the air. Distraction just good enough to let Kara free out of the teeth of a not-so-halfling bear.\n\n- Maybe we reconsider? - Kara threw a quick glance to miss Olive, however she was just blissfully smiling in wait. Enur made a sharp twist and took a bite and a swing at Fluffers, who didn’t seem to have quite enough time to react. Flaming tom disappeared almost as quickly as he appeared and now Kara was stuck swinging her ax, which proved to be ineffective. Plus she didn’t want to hurt poor Enur any more than was absolutely necessary.\n\nCommon little one, if you don’t do something I will have to kill you. Enur’s voice calmly passed through Kara’s mind as the bear turned back to facing her.\n\n- Well, that’s not a good reason, now isn’t it? - Kara considered making a jump for a second, however a giant clawed paw quite inconveniently caught her leg digging dangerously too deep for comfort. Her leg twitched in a moment of weakness and Kara was lucky to duck out of the way of clacking jaws. It was a terrific feeling of desperate concentration when the fear of failure to notice an attack conflicted with the will to live and trust the natural flow. She wasn’t even close to knowing how long she could keep dodging, but the feeling of blood running down her leg and shoulder was counting down the timer with ridiculous urgency.","n":97},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"- Let's find him and break his claws! - Kara was quite ragious. She hated to see Fluffers get hurt. He was her and Reins' responsibility and the fluffiest cat on the streets. Scratches could ruin his impeccable looks. She now hated Tomson the old cat for attacking her poor kitten, - That way if they fight at least Fluffers wont get as hurt.\n\n- That might be a good idea, - Rein was pondering the genius behind the solution. It really wouldn’t hurt to remove claws from cats, so that they stop hurting each other. Kara wondered why people haven’t done it to all cats yet, - It shouldn’t be that hard, we just need to stay on the lookout then.\n\nKara stood up, still boiling inside she couldn’t even bring herself to pet Huggins. She didn’t want to risk touching the wounds.","n":98},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Kara saw a new charge of the head loading up behind the bear's neck. His fur still smelt a bit burned. Fluffers wasn’t there anymore, that’s one more life gone if he had nine. Kara was done with this training. It was pointless and she was almost ready to just get done with it. She saw the bear muzzle open and white teeth almost shone in the light. They seemed much whiter than they were supposed to be.","n":99},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Rein and Kara looked quite everywhere for Tomson. He wasn't the most sociable of cats and it was rare for him to approach humans close enough to beg for food and when he did he never took no for an answer. He walked the streets like a snob, ignoring all attempts to gain his friendship. He wasn’t pretty either, just a regular ragtag of the street, with some bald spots even.\n\n- You think Tomson knows that we are looking for him because of Fluffer Huggins? - Kara was growing impatient. It wasn't an unnatural disappearance, but the urgency to find him somehow made everything a bit more personal. Kara thought that a victorious cat wouldn’t be hiding and instead would walk proudly around.\n\n- He is a cat, Kara, - Rein sighed, - he isn’t that smart. He will turn up and we just need to keep looking, - he didn’t sound too enthusiastic about the idea anymore and Kara nodded, as they headed back home. Kara didn’t really know what was the difference between cat smart and person smart. Tomson seemed like a very smart cat, but somehow being a cat made him somehow incapable of persisting on certain strategies. Maybe Tomson didn’t even know that Kara is supposed to be smarter.","n":100},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"The feeling was more of an uncomfortable chill in the back. Kara’s eyes light up and she could almost feel her vision turn feral. She saw two things in front of her - a bear and Miss Olive in that beautiful fabric. It glistened.\n\n- She said get to her? - Kara tightened her grip on the ax for a split second. She could feel every nerve in her tail bone as if it was now sixty times longer. Room seemed brighter and much slower, it was almost too easy. Kara rocked back on instinct, weirdly trusting her tailbone to catch her as she dropped the tip of the ax into a crack in the stone. She jumped up and briefly stepped on the pummel sticking on her chest level. It felt as if the tail behind her gave extremely light feet, as if it was helping to push from the ground. Bear head clashed on the handle and Kara softly rolled forwards over bears back to the other side. World rolled around for what seemed to be an eternity and Kara almost forgot to catch her footing, leave alone the notice of a recreation of a fluffy tail that now was awkwardly rolling with her.\n\nShe landed perfectly out of balance to start booking it straight to miss Olive. Her body didn’t seem to be any heavier than it used to, but Kara definitely felt the weight of the tail trailing behind her as she leaned forward to compensate for the switch in center of mass.","n":101},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Tomson the son of Tom, the nickname that Kara’s mother always used to tell the great tales of his atrocious character. All cats in this town were heads over heels for him and that despite his brute way of treating his ladies in public. He would pick fights with anyone who would dare to look at him for too long, that among cats of course. Humans just kept their pets indoors and ranted about how they would always come back beaten up by Tomson.\n\nHe was quite a legend, that's why when Kara and Rain finally caught him he did not give up without one of the most vicious fights of their life. Kara was almost startled when Tomson scratched her hand to bloody lines. She grabbed him by the front paws and Rein held the hind ones. Something felt terribly wrong about the whole situation. Tomson was wiggling so viciously that Kara was scared he was about to break his own bones to get out of their grip. She and Rein only wanted to trim his claws. She did it twice to Fluffers before he learned to keep them in during play time, but Huggings was much calmer. It seemed like Tomson was fighting for his life.","n":102},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Gust of wind seemed to change the position of her tail. Kara reacted instantly, switching the tail around to torque herself into a better position to see the attack. If Enur didn’t want to grasp the tail it meant he was aiming for something more vital. That or he simply wasn’t able to see the tail. Which was equally confusing, Kara thought that they were friendly to each other. However, again, Kara didn’t know the specifics of the transformation. Maybe Enur lacked precision in that form and didn’t want to risk a failure on the wiggly tail.\n\nIn any matter, Kara turned around just in time to correct with a soft step on Mister Enurs nose and a mischievous kick as she once again rocked onto her tail to catch her footing. Kara was ready for a jolt of pain in her back, as if she was going to break the fictional tail that she might have had. Then she would have landed on her back with a foot on the nose of the bear. Not the worst position in a situation given.\n\nHowever, she rolled right over her tail and quickly her legs were ready for the next dash. She gave an extra spin on the bear's nose and pushed off with a satisfying kangaroo kick.","n":103},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Tomson seemed like he was charging up to do something stupid. He jerked out with a terrible yawl and hiss and Kara let go of front paws to get out of the trajectory of a bite.\n\n- Rein! - Kara tried to warn him, but he was quick to react himself and give Tomson his paws back for the landing. It wasn’t the most graceful of the landings that old tom had ever performed, however his take off was so quick that it totally made up for the glory of his escape, - You think he is scared enough?\n\n- For a couple days for sure, - Rein was rubbing his scratches, - He usually leaves the area if someone nags at him, - Kara wondered if these scratches would stay as scars. She saw people with cat scratches well into their eighties and old people are too clumsy to be trying to catch Tomson.\n\n- Sorry, that idea probably was dumb to begin with, - Kara sounded defeated, the mission was failed and Tomson remained a threat for months to come. At least now they knew how to hold him back until Fluffers grew out his own strong paws.","n":104},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"Kara landed softly feeling extra spring in her legs and rushed to miss Olive. Her legs were still burning with nerves of being so close to a giant bear's jaw. It was something like a buildup of nerve pulses from restrained nerve channels. Like tight muscles artificially held the signals before they could remind Kara of the fear she was supposed to feel. The leg might as well have been broken, Kara would still not bother about it and keep running. She jumped into a hug in a last ditch effort to escape this situation. If it didn’t work, at least she was getting a tiny rest after a shock. If the bear was to attack her now he was risking breaking the rules of the training and after that it would turn into a very different story. For Kara, for sure.\n\n- Oh my, this is my favorite part of this season! - Miss Olive was smiling with such a nonchalant smile that Kara felt chills in her backbone. Tail disappeared and Kara could just barely feel her legs. Miss Olive was hugging back and the fabric felt ridiculously soft. Kara suddenly noticed red smudged spots on it.\n\n- Oh, sorry, - She sprung up on her feet and smiled uncomfortably as she struggled to catch her balance, - I didn’t mean to ruin your outfit, - Kara forced herself to sound sweet through the sudden urge to growl. Partially on herself for doing something so inconveniently excessive. Why did she want to hug Miss Crazy Smile and her pompous appearance? It did feel quite soft, maybe she should have lingered for another moment.\n\n- Alright then, we can move on now, you will even catch other training shoots, - Miss Olive didn’t seem phased at all. Kara shivered at the option. Was she about to sit down and watch her teammates potentially die? Would she stop from helping them just like Enur stopped his attack? Would she be scared of the consequences of breaking the conditions or would it count as trust in the methods? Bear was already turning back into a halfling that was smiling quite profoundly.\n\n- Sorry little one, I was told that you need quite a push to get you going, no hard feelings, - Enur patted on Kara’s shoulder and she, somehow, didn’t mind it. They parted ways as he retired back into the river room and Miss Olive dragged Kara into a new corridor. She didn’t even have time to ask who Enur was and where he was from. Maybe Septum had more heroes in reserves, maybe it’s a support exchange program. Maybe Quintus was just sending their crazy ones to get rid of competition of their own. Not like it wouldn’t be out of character for them - they always had a tooth against Septum's fuel policies. Maybe they even were the ones to blow up the oil rig. In any way, Enur still seemed quite nice. Humorous even.\n\n- Is that the way you train us now? - Kara now was quite upset that miss Olive approves of such animosities in training, - No wonder you have such a ridiculous rate of wins, - Kara looked down at her wounds and they looked quite terrible. Bear bites seemed to puncture the skin seemingly solid inches into the flesh, but there was way less blood than Kara would have expected. She did grow a tail in the room but what was it really a tail? Enur is either a super trained shifter that knows how to arrange his bites around vital blood vessels or Kara somehow lucked out. What was really happening and how much of it was truly real? What could even be the technology behind these illusions? So many questions, too bad Kara wasn’t talking to miss Olive for at least five more minutes.\n\n- Now wasn’t it fun, dear? You did so well, so much progress and that in one day! - Miss Olive started chattering some ridiculous gibberish of importance, but Kara was only half listening. Nothing about potatoes and where the garden is going to be. Even that might have been more sensible of a conversation.\n\nThey walked out through another corridor. Similar and yet slightly different, Kara was wondering why it never joined the one they used to get in. They climbed the stairs and Miss Olive opened the door to a lavishly decorated living room with an open balcony letting Kara in.\n\n- You can rest here, I’m going to go back and see how the rest are doing, - Miss Olive smiled and retreated back to the corridor, closing the door. Kara didn’t hear any locks turning, but she had no intention to check. She still felt a bit weak, but the sole fact that she was still standing was perplexing to her enough to see it through. It was almost like the feeling of dull disjointed pain after she fought off the moose. Almost. She could barely move after fighting a moose and right now she felt like injuries just barely caused her discomfort.","n":105},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"What would she even do with a wolf? Fighting a beast that aims to kill you with a slight understanding of the necessity of self preservation is a bit more straightforward than trying to read the mood that people are in. However, what would be the best strategy to coexist? Kara didn’t want anything really entering her garden and wolves were technically on her side of the spectrum here. Unless they caught some dog habits to eat like boars while living with humans, but, again, Septum citizens never had gardens to teach them to dig out vegetables. Kara didn’t really want to fight wolves, afterall there were always bears they could team up against. Probably a stupid plan, but what Kara really had to lose?\n\n- Having your eye on this ax? - middle aged merchant seemed to be a tiny bit concerned. Kara indeed didn’t look her best after a night in the woods, but nothing too unusual for the area.\n\n- Only an eye, sir, - Kara sounded cold, she could feel it through her smile. She wondered what that feeling was. There was a thing she wanted to pick up from her old home, but it was locked when she came by. Maybe for the best.","n":106},{"chapter":"Fight or Flight","text":"The silence was quite heavy for a couple of moments. Kara didn’t even hear birds chirping outside and her tense ears could almost hear the cushy sofas soaking every bit of sound around. It almost made her growl at them in frustration, however the strange tingle of being watched stopped her. She walked up to the balcony, hoping to catch a glance of the trees, but all she could see was a rocky pavement, walls and a strange sand pit. She wondered how far she would be able to run before they caught her again. The orphanage didn’t have walls around it.","n":107},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"All stories reached their midpoints around middles. Even if it felt like a prolonged ending or a slow beginning. Book never fails to have an exact midpoint, after all of them had two sides to a page and pages had to roll over the bounding. Four sides total, making the midpoint the empty space that binds all pages together. Well, not really empty, in fact most diverse in substance and matter, but no words to describe how empty it is.\n\nKara felt lost, there was nothing for her to cling onto in this lavish room. She didn’t take potatoes with her to the training. That would be absolutely reckless and dangerous for poor tubers. It’s not like it would make for any change, since she resolved not to talk to them in any proximity of… Cameras? Gut feeling forced her down on the couch as she rushed to calm down the growing feeling of panic. She shouldn’t speak to potatoes at all, it wasn’t something that people do. Why was it such a problem in the first place? Her heart was racing. It must have been the pain shock wearing out. Right about time, Kara was beginning to feel a bit too ambitiously immortal.\n\n- I’m bored, whoever is listening, please do something, - Kara was ever so slightly annoyed at the fact of being monitored. But what they actually heard didn’t matter if it didn’t matter, so by process of elimination she could say whatever was meaningless to her. If they would kill her it wouldn’t be for a demanding attitude, they were too good at ignoring that.\n\nAs on command, by pure chance or not, a second set of doors opened and Taric let Rein and Fezzik in. Kara jolted to an upright position as if she mistook a stick for a snake. Room filled with a very mixed energy. Kara was exhausted and tense, Fezzik looked quite annoyed and Rein… Seemingly unbothered. Kara hated it. With every inch of her body. It felt so normal and calm, that she got stuck in an argument with her own head. She missed their presence, but not like she missed potatoes.\n\n- Kara, are you ok? - Fezzik was looking straight at the bite marks. She hated this attention, so she pulled on a smile.\n\n- It is, but a scratch, - Kara sounded quite sincerely chipper. She had to be, otherwise conversation would turn into a rant and weird exchange of pleasantries that would resolve in the exact same spot, - I see you guys did quite well.\n\nFezzik hesitated to answer. It was a brief pause of a mind grinding on self reflection to decide on the answer. In fact brief enough of Kara to grow quite intrigued by the details.\n\n- Yeah, - mastermind of an answer. Self depleting and stunning.","n":108},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"When Kara saw her first bee it was more of a miracle than anything else. Bright yellow colors and furry bellies made her stop in her tracks as she was passing by a dandelion overgrowth. She came closer and got down on the ground to get a closer look. Pedestrian bystanders gave her usual glances, but she mostly imagined them rolling their eyes. She never turned around to check on them, it was just given.\n\n- What are you looking at? - The officer sneaked up on Kara and she froze. They rarely spoke to citizens with good intentions.\n\n- Dandelions, sir, - Kara forced an answer, but didn’t look up. She saw officers every day, bees could disappear tomorrow.\n\n- Code seven five four zero at Elm and Lights street intersection, - Officer spoke into his radio and walked away. Kara cursed, sprung on her legs and booked it, forgetting all about the bee that she had discovered. Codes never meant a good thing, if there was something that was not supposed to be there Kara wasn’t going to risk getting caught in the crossfire. Curiosity is fun and stuff, but not when the outcome could be terminal. Not over some bees.","n":109},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"- Are you sure you are fine? - Fezzik stretched out his arm to heal, but Kara rocked away and did it herself. She still felt like she needed practice in these things and receiving help wasn’t something that would improve her own abilities. Afterall, they were in training.\n\n- Yes, - Kara concentrated like Haderach showed and her wounds slowly started to disappear. Such an easy solution to her troubles and yet she waited till the last second. Next time she will be quicker. It was different this time. She felt like the energy wasn’t leaving her body, but actually changing within. She wondered if she even needed to touch her own wounds to direct this transformation of energy. Sounds like meta gaming. Why was she even trying to do anything that she was asked for? Is it just because so far it was the matter of life and death? Sounds a lot like pushing universes into a funneling threshold.\n\n- And you sound like yours was a bit more lenient, - Kara would love to look angrily towards the camera, however instead she sighed and shrugged falling back on the sofa relaxing her back. Pain disappeared almost immediately, maybe it all wasn’t that bad and she was only supposed to die in the end. Surprisingly, but for some reason she felt like it was almost obvious that she wasn’t going to die.\n\n- Well you see, they are trying to capitalize on our strengths at this point, - Fezzik tried to explain, but the disinterested look on Kara's face made him cut it short, - Though they really need to watch out how far they go, our district isn’t known for it’s best training methods. Hey you, idiots, don’t you think it’s a bit too much? - he looked up with an inquiring shrug. He might have been actually insane or too good at bad acting.\n\nIt was common. Speaking to the unknown and yet very familiar audience was something that helped to vent sometimes. Exact reason why Kara rarely spoke to her potatoes out loud. She could barely look at them at this point. They just reminded her of the terrible fact that they still exist in her reality in fragile and very corporeal form. They and the sprouts, heaven, let there be at least one.","n":110},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"- Do you really think that there was only one God at some point? - Kara looked up to the sky counting clouds. There weren’t many. Remembering history facts was a fun way to pass time. It was like a whole world that actually happened over and over again in different settings and genres. And yet people still needed to create something in their heads to propel the time into the future. What was Kara creating? Nothing, because there were 8 clouds in the sky. Seven if you don’t count the one speck. Three if you count in clusters. None of them looked spectacular.\n\n- Don’t be silly, if it ever was then it is still. If he never was then there always were none, - Classic response often repeated, revised and reestablished. Rein always went for the right answer, without wasting time on stupidity. Kara felt her cheeks go red in embarrassment. She knew that answer and still questioned its viability. How come there couldn’t be two completely separate gods? She quickly weighed the options and her equation quickly collapsed. There was no way to check something that was created purely through human reference in an attempt to deny the inability to understand something fully.\n\n- Damn, sometimes you are just so incredibly boring, - Kara blew up her cheeks to cool them down from embarrassment, - Still though, quite a mysterious question. What it is like to take an extra step and assume more?\n\n- Because that’s how you split its essence to make it easier for others to see it like you do, - Rein didn’t wait to answer. It felt like a stupid trivia show now. She never liked those because they always made people feel so silly and ignorant. There are things in the world that happened and things that cannot be changed no matter how hard you put your will to it. History happened, no matter how people described it.\n\n- Why do you always know so much? - Kara blew into the sky attempting to move the little spect towards its cluster buddies.\n\n- What are you doing? - Rein must have raised a brow.\n\n- Magic, - said Kara calmly, pointing at the little cloud joining the bigger one. It wasn’t magic.","n":111},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"Everything happened, strangely, slowly. One by one the rest of the team poured into the room. Tallie looked exceptionally happy, Floats floating in ave of decorations and Haderach just acted normal. It was becoming quite uncomfortably crowded. It even felt wrong to be sitting down. Maybe Kara could go back to her room. Take potatoes. And maybe run. It wasn’t possible, but entertaining that thought was keeping life quite interesting. How far would she go? How many would she have to take down? It would make no sense, but she would be free and alive for the spring. Then she would plant potatoes and build everything up again. She would never have to see Rein again. He wouldn’t die in the tournament and live like the hero he was. Daydreams.\n\n- Well at least someone else is having as much fun as me, - Kara smiled at Tallie and waved half ironically with her ax, - What did you do? - She twisted over on the sofa and focused attention on a short fluffy tailed goblin girl. It was weird to think that she was twice her size about a couple of weeks ago.\n\n- Oh yeah, they brought me some fine brawler, - Tallie sounded chipper as she swung around her hammer in the air. She would not say anything else. It was kind of a tradition to keep the conversations short, this team had way too different ideas on fun stories. Floats kept talking about his appreciation for pretty things and desire to turn into a statue, Tallie probably liked the more gruesome bits of her battles, Fezzik talked gibberish about engines and etcetera. No one really cared to hear stories about the potatoes and Kara really had nothing else. The room soon returned to a common silence.","n":112},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"If there ever was a time when there was nothing to really say, it was that day. It was clear and sunny and yet grim and dark. It was easier when the news had just arrived. Emotions boiled inside and rushed out in a flood like milk from the steaming pot draining every inch of the duplex house. Now it was just quiet.\n\nKara sat home watching the daylight go out as she realized how empty her house really was. None of her books or possessions mattered, it seemed she never liked them to begin with. And yet she was sitting among them, solely because there was her place to be. She couldn’t pick herself up to go somewhere without Rein. It would be meaningless, the setting would not change no matter where she went. Mother said that it was going to blow over soon, like a cold. Kara knew she was right, they taught it loud and clear at school. Emotions are only natural responses to certain situations and everyone feels them the same, even if it feels different in the moment. Afterall they all were ninety nine point nine percent the same creatures. Even if that point one percent meant something it was largely outweighed by the silent and yet overwhelming majority.\n\nKara stood up and opened a window to discover zero wind coming from outside. There was no change in the temperature either. Only a slight change in the freshness of air and even that was barely noticeable. It felt suffocating and extremely wrong. Kara wished for a storm. Strong one. Strong enough to shatter windows and bring the freezing rain inside. Wasteful, but an entertaining thought. Window would need a repair, Kara could finally make these funny clear duct tape sails that some of the houses had covering their windows. It would probably stand like this till autumn and by then, hopefully, there would be a shipment of new glass. That could have been a nice new hope to have.","n":113},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"When Victorean slipped into the room maybe five minutes had passed. He smiled graciously.\n\n- Well, I hope you liked this type of training more. It is still beyond me why you skipped on saving the village. It would have been good compassion credit for the audience, - He sounded detached and only slightly displeased, - You know how much preparations you had wasted there?\n\n- Yeah, like people in termination wests make for good advocates for very real naturally occurring disasters, - Kara remembered how mad she was about that situation. Who really killed these people? Would it even matter in the end if they saved them if they were to be disposed of right after? At least heroes had the promise of a better life after the tournament.\n\nVictorian stood silent for a short moment. It was uncanny how little he cared.\n\n- Listen, we have been through this many times. Our job is to prepare you for the tournament and this is a good situational practice with good moral benefits to boost your popularity. We can’t let people go around saying that it was a set up. It doesn’t make a good hero story, - Victorian sounded so detached that Kara couldn’t help, but feel pity. It has been a long time since Septum won any tournaments. It would make sense why they were so desperate.\n\n- Don’t you think that making it so obvious would raise some questions? You never told us about this mission, so how could we have known that it wouldn’t get us into trouble? - Fezzik interrupted suddenly with growing irritation, - You have to be more transparent with things that you want us to do if you want us to do them right. What is this charade?\n\n- Alright then, - Victorian sighed, - How about this: We have two field missions for you. You can choose which one you want to do first.\n\nA choice. Kara didn’t know how often they had them before, but the rest of the team looked relieved and quite surprised. Well, the rest of the team that really cared about what was happening. Tallie and Floats looked quite unbothered.\n\n- Spill them out, Vik, - Fezzik sounded quite intrigued.\n\n- First one is simple, you go back to the mountain range and help the mining village with their infestation, - Victorian seemed to be unbothered by previous concerns of the group, - Second is a protection mission where you have to guard a new crop that was developed by Tarics uncle and have been pestered by local thieves. It is truly a marvelous invention, one leaf of this thing can feed an ox for a day. Very potent, - Interesting bit of information that made Kara wonder why the government would rather make efforts to better feed livestock than its own people.\n\n- Second one, - The choice seemed obvious to Kara. Prolonging the first mission would at least prolong the lives of the poor villagers. Maybe they could figure out a way to escape their situation before they arrive and destroy everything.\n\n- What if these miners really need our help? - Rein spoke out and Kara felt a sting in her chest. There were real people out there and yet she chose to tend to farms, before helping them, - We know these mines, - he looked at Fezzik, who seemed to understand the situation better from Kara’s point of view.\n\n- Hey, listen, you have seen what they do to the people out there. We might need to know a bit more information about how these trainings are done before we deal with human, - Fezzik hesitated for a second, - hostages, - it was quite hard to discern what exactly was to be used against them next. Group had more trust around Vik and Taric than they did with Miss Olive, but a nervous stutter was already in place. Heroes thought twice before they spoke.\n\n- But there are men dying in the mines right now. They have families, there are our friends, - Rein seemed to be set on diving right into it. Everything seemed to be uncannily centered around him.\n\n- Listen, if it is a set up I don’t want to be anywhere close to it. I don’t approve of their methods and maybe some time off will give time for changes, - Kara hated to sound this cold, but by no means she felt ready to be directly responsible for any more unnecessary stupid deaths.\n\nRein didn’t seem happy about this decision, but the uncertainty of the situation left him no arguments to defend. Room sank into a familiar quietness awaiting the opinions from the rest of the group.\n\n- I agree, I would much rather stay away from self exploding civilians for as long as possible, - Haderaches voice sounded soft and composed as always. He really didn’t fit in the entire frame of things. Him and Floats were friends, but Kara didn’t know anything else beyond that fact. They barely talked to each other. One wanted statues of himself to be erected in every state and the other was seemingly a simple barkeeper.\n\n- Alright then, I will tell Taric to contact his uncle in Quattuor. Rest up and you will move out tomorrow morning, - It was never in the habit of Victorean to stay in the room any longer than needed. Kara remembered that seemingly out of nowhere and yet sure as a bright day. This would have been extremely annoying to realize if Kara had more time. But she didn’t because she could not bother. She got to go to Quattuor, maybe she can make friends there and move to their town. If heroes are allowed to move. Maybe she could run away. At this point it seemed enough that she would get to visit it before the tournament. Who would care about anything else?\n\nIt was hard to smile even though Kara really wanted to. All thoughts seemed to be pulled out of the emergency box and really just clouded her mind. Kara wanted to be irritated, but she couldn’t think of anything to cling on to. She just looked like she always did: disinterested, fakely tired and slightly angry. Even she thought that whatever character she was playing was being a bit bland. Good, at least she wasn’t playing into anyones hands. Probably the most destructive thing she could do for herself. Maybe she should reconsider that strategy.","n":114},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"Kara didn’t remember falling asleep, but when she woke up the sun was already behind the horizon. Cold wind started slowly flowing down from the mountains gently ruffling summer leaves. It was a soft sound, maybe last of its kind before forest starts suiting up for autumn. Then the sounds will turn crisper every day, until they would be substituted for the crackling of the snow. Kara knew this slow changing symphony of seasons. Sometimes they took a slower pace, sometimes winters cut their spectacles short. But no season had more emotions than fall. Something about urgent hustle to change and prepare for the winter made the world dull and yet bright colors of nature spill on to the trees setting them ablaze only to strip them naked for the morrow.\n\nIf Kara was to apply to a transfer she would have to leave everything behind. Logically it seemed quite doable, she really had nothing to lose. This garden was just a small hobby that kept her mind busy, these potatoes were just plants. Maybe she should gather them up and give them away to neighbors as a parting gift. Maybe she should leave them here to be consumed by nature. Either way she would probably never see them again and for some reason her stomach felt uneasy at this thought.","n":115},{"chapter":"New Program","text":"Knocking at the door in the middle of the night was completely unexpected. Especially after an endless formal dinner. Miss Olive walked through every single rule of courtesy and fork handling. It took literal hours, Kara had to pick up the lap napkin from the floor about ten times. Every time Miss Olive was sure to notice the second fabric touched the ground. Rest was pretty self explanatory.\n\n- Who is there? - Kara sprung up like a trained meerkat. She hesitantly stepped on the floor and headed towards the door, weirdly still in her nightgown. It still felt weird to wear one and Kara had no idea when it became so normal. She cracked the door open only to see Taric politely waiting a tail distance away, - Did you knock?\n\n- Hey, we need to talk. Care for a walk? - Taric sounded quite formal. He was fully ready for a long stroll.\n\n- I guess better than just sleeping, no weird rooms though, - Kara put on her shoes and walked out. She wasn’t scared to get cold, the only concern was leaving potatoes in the room. What a coin toss. She might never return to that room, but she might attract too much attention to them if she shows too much attachment.\n\n- Don’t worry, it’s just a walk, - Taric gestured towards the hall leading to the outside door. Kara remembered her stupid joke to miss Olive. Building with multiple exits and weird structure. Back home buildings only had one exit. It felt too redundant to have more and yet liberating. Selfishly liberating, like having a better choice that didn’t involve breaking windows.\n\n- Right.","n":116},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"Fire. Useful, dangerous and incredibly boring. Not because it lacks utility or power, but because it took so many forms in so many places that it lost its originality. It doesn’t need to follow rules that other elements fall into to look natural. Like a ghost with a colorful suit that takes shape as an incorporeal guardian of its wielder.\n\nFluffer Huggins jumped into existence the moment Kara stepped outside, lighting the grass around him on fire. He looked exactly the way he looked the first time she saw him. Not a scratch. He growled quietly at Taric and his pelt burned so high that for a second or two Kara was wondering if he was going to take a shot against her will.\n\n- Still on bad terms? - Taric looked unbothered. Kara still had no idea why Fluffers hated him. It was among not many things that seemed to happen on their own to Fluffer.\n\n- Yeah, but I bet you deserve it quite a bit, - Kara ignored the burning sensation in her chest as she tried to keep flaming tom at bay without cold orders.\n\n- You know that you have full control over it, right? - Taric sounded quite tired.\n\n- Yeah, but why would I want it? - Kara crossed her arms on her chest feeling a bit cold, - Wouldn’t it make me more responsible for the destruction that he causes if I fully control him?\n\n- Kara, I am serious, - Taric started to sound slightly concerned, - Don’t lie to yourself, it won’t take you anywhere.\n\nFluffers growled and stepped forward burning even brighter. Kara just continued to walk as nothing was happening. Flaming tom just followed. He even stopped growling as her attention shifted to the road. She did have full control over him. She was almost sure that it didn’t even have to take the shape of the cat.\n\n- And where do you think I am heading? - Kara chuckled as Fluffer Hugging caught up to her. Mostly to warm up her freezing limbs, - To lie to self presumes that I know the truth. What if this control is the lie that you made up to fit into the boundaries of the trust.\n\n- Listen, I wanted to talk to you about your request for transfer, - Taric sighed, without much interest in the teenage half baked philosophy. Kara felt her body jolt into fury, - You won’t be able to move there and you can’t stay there without an order.\n\n- Thanks, good to know, - she clenched her teeth and tried to reason with Fluffers not to burn anything. There really was no reason to be angry. It wasn’t like she had any chance for the spot as it was. None of her plans ever worked and she was used to the feeling of their ashes being carried away by the gust of the wind. There really was no place she could see herself fit in the orderly chaos of this strange world, - So what do heroes do then?\n\n- Well, really anything you want if you are smart about it, - Taric sounded worse than Miss Olive, - Just remember that you will not be the only one trying to do it.\n\n- Gotcha, - Kara sighed and continued to walk, - Can I take a day off then? - she was tired.\n\n- Sure, I will tell the others, but you will have to catch up with them through the night, - Taric shrugged and started walking back. His steps were heavy with his trekking boots.\n\n- Are there any places I could visit around this town? - Kara didn’t turn back to ask a question. Taric didn’t seem like a man who would care for courtesies.\n\n- As long as you stay on course, go wherever you want, - Taric closed the door and disappeared into the mansion.","n":117},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"- Hero is a diluted term with many qualifying criterias, - Teacher spoke with slight boredom in his voice. Latest generations of Septum didn’t really have good heroes to cheer for and most of the kids were much more excited to climb some social ladder within the state or move out. It was a bad omen to be a hero. Almost all of them died and those who survived were gray mice among the rest, - you can be brave, cunning, strong, agile, but does anyone know what sets a hero apart from others?\n\nClass dropped into a tense silence as the teacher asked an unexpected question. It happened often, little Kara still had no idea why he would ask for wrong answers before he spoke out the right one. Seemed like an unnecessary setup for a social trap.\n\n- Kara, want to take a shot? - the teacher looked straight at her and she rolled her eyes. Rein briefly whispered the answer, like he usually did. Real life savior, considering the fact that for some reason his answers seemed to be right ones. True hero of the day.\n\n- Their deeds? - Kara sounded uninspired and bored as if she had the answer all along. She didn’t even process the answer through her mind. Many heroes did imaginary things to inspire people and usually it wasn’t the actual change that they brought that was celebrated, but the flamboyant exaggerations that they came up with to describe their actions. Like Hercules and the dirty stables. Digging an entire river off of its course to wash through the imaginary building to wash it off squeaky clean. It probably took down that shed in a heartbeat too. No wonder the king refused to accept this labor.\n\n- Yes, - the lecture continued.","n":118},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"Kara waited a solid five minutes to return to her room and got back into bed without saying a word to three potatoes in a parcel right under it. It felt wrong to tell them about something that she wanted to do just for herself. Something that would feel like a normal day out in the city so that she would have something to tell them after she came back. Something that they would not be judging her for because she would probably make a lot of it up and leave out the embarrassing bits. It still wouldn’t be the same, so she didn’t bother mentioning it.\n\nShe woke up right before dawn, dressed up and left through the side door. Kara always found grassy backyards quite petty. Waste of space and ridiculously fragile for any sort of activity. She looked at the burned patches Fluffer Huggins left at night wondering when Miss Olive would request for newer patches to be replanted. Maybe it will be done by the evening.\n\nIt didn’t take much effort getting over the fence. Kara could have as easily taken the main gate, but the thought of conversation with officers made her feel quite uneasy. To think about it, Kara didn’t even have a straight plan of what she was doing. As her feet touched the ground on the other side she felt out of place. She was supposed to be excited to learn about this new place and how it worked, but it felt weird to explore on her own. She left potatoes inside, why on earth would she have done it? That’s right, it’s not planting season and she never took potatoes with her anywhere. They were illegal.\n\nIt wasn’t it. She must have wanted to do it with somebody. Taric must have done quite a number on her in the past three weeks for her to really invest into making new friends. They did burn her entire life in one day for no apparent reason. Why wouldn’t she want to burn them all? It would only be fair and most of the people would understand if they knew the whole story. Well, Tallie would definitely approve of it.\n\nKara started walking, rushing every step as she felt like she just needed to venture a bit further down the street before letting her flaming tom loose. Fire spinned in a fury and with a roar exploded Fluffer Huggins to existence on a pebble road. Good thing this town didn’t seem like an early bird type. She knew nothing about this place. It wasn’t exactly her city and people here seemed pretty used to heroes.\n\nIt definitely looked different. Most of the houses were built in a simple wooden frame. Extremely flammable and easy to rebuild. Early hours made it look like a nice lake resort where people would go fishing. Except there wasn’t any smell of lake. Kara lightly hugged Fluffer Huggins for reassurance, but had to let go before clothing would catch on fire. It felt soft, as always.","n":119},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"It was like hugging a heating pad, except a really fluffy and dusty one. It became a little tradition to meet Fluffer Huggins on the way from school. Funny how quickly young tom picked up certain habits and how much little Kara got attached to them. She felt like it was happening all her life when school really started again only two months ago.\n\n- Kara, stop. Can’t you see his paws are wet and dirty today? - Rein rolled his eyes knowing that his commentary would not produce any sensible response.\n\n- What gives? He already splooged on the shirt. Aren’t you happy to see him? - little Kara just hugged young tom tighter and let him down on the ground. Fluffer Huggins meowed in slight surprise, but landed confidently on his paws.\n\n- We see him every day, Kara, - Rein watched tentatively as mister Huggins followed them in determination, matching their speed with his four freshly grown longer paws. It was like he was never sick or hungry.\n\n- Yes, and every day he grows bigger and bigger. I already miss the little Fluffer kitten, - Kara smiled quite proudly as young tom took over and strutted right in front of them. Tail up and proud.\n\n- Well that’s what happens, kittens grow up, - Rein sighed. The new member of their gang was a pleasant distraction, however it seemed to annoy him that Fluffers wasn't quite considerate when it came to hygiene. Good thing that Quintus made sure there were no ticks or other biting or stinging bugs in Septum. Plenty of roaches for birds though.\n\n- Ah, right, that's where the big cats come from. Thanks for clarifying, - Kara smiled and lightly kicked ginger tail making Fluffers let out a surprised meow and chatter as an annoyed follow up, - Aren’t you one fluffy cat mister Huggins?\n\nHuggins responded with a lovely soft meow. Kara had at least ten years of his company if he would turn out as old Tomson. It was nice to realize that. Maybe he will get to live inside once Kara gets her own place.","n":120},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"Painfully soft. Mainly because the char from his clay like surface felt like dust. Flaming tom even nudged towards Kara and she could almost hear the rough purr. It was quite uncanny how this fire seemed to be ways weaker than anything Kara was used to. Her clothes barely turned brownish from this brief moment.\n\nShe looked for a library of some sort. This wasn’t her town, books here must have been different since capitol supported the separation of cultural literature beyond the most general school education. These people must have been living in a very different world. Maybe they didn’t even know about the capital, some villages opted out of being involved in politics. They said that when heroes came out of these places they had the most natural aptitude in understanding their powers, but least favored by the crowd. They just perished due to the most stupid mistakes that people with more understanding of the situation avoid as a given. Happens when you grow up in a limited system of abilities.\n\nIt took Kara about an hour to walk around this town, now a village in her eyes. It must have been more than ten times smaller than her hometown. Kara barely understood how they got so many resources if they barely had enough people for one office. Must have been part of a special program to make heroes a bit more comfortable without exposing them to large cities.\n\nAnd there was no library. At least no building looked like one. That depleted the pool of ideas in Kara's head. So she went to a tavern and asked for breakfast. Fluffers stayed outside.\n\n- Good morning, sure thing, - lady at the bar started a fire, - Didn’t quite expect you back so early, - she smiled as she placed a kettle on the stove, - Where are the rest?\n\nIt was weird how a familiar woman acted with Kara. Like she was a child who just needed a little bit of warmth from strangers. With a soft hint of pity and forced respect.\n\n- They are moving out today without me, I’ll wait till sun down, - Kara sat at the bar and threw a light glance to the window to make sure Fluffer Huggins was behaving. He scratched his ear and layed down.\n\n- Not a fan of the sun? That should be quite inconvenient, - lady broke two eggs into the frying pan with a slight distress in her motion, - I remember lad who fainted at the sight of blood. Don’t think he quite made it through the first half of the tournament.\n\n- It’s not that, I’m just tired of it all. I shouldn’t even be here, - Kara laid her head down on the table and lazily watched the lady cook her breakfast, - Why doesn’t Septum just raise heroes like Unus or Novem. It could have been so much easier.\n\n- Well, now you are just whining, - woman gave a light stear to egg whites to fluff them up, - If you wouldn’t want to end up here you could have just followed the rules like all others. Isn’t it more fair than being condemned from birth?\n\nShe might as well have been a robot. Kara had no idea whether she had to explain how ridiculous some of the rules were. Especially considering how little thought was actually given to trials.\n\n- Well, don’t you know everything, - Kara picked herself up so that bar lady could put her plate down, - So what do you do to get to live here? - it did seem like a nice and quiet village.\n\n- Well one way or another, mostly lifetime hire applications for exemplary citizens, - woman shrugged her shoulders. She did seem like a very orderly and responsible candidate, - It takes a lot of trust to keep a village that is busy only three months a year.\n\n- Sounds like quite a bit of fun, - Kara heard about these jobs, but never thought that they were so enticing. No wonder you had to have powerful connections to even be considered for the list. Who knows, maybe Kara would end up in one of these villages if only she stayed in the orphanage. If only she had trusted the system. Now it was a bit too late to reconsider.","n":121},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"- No Percival, I don’t think that it’s insane for you to be talking to me, - Kara rolled her eyes as she spread some of the rabbit fluff at the ground around the potato stems. It was supposed to help with certain slugs. Not like it was much of a problem, but it was a nice precaution she read out of a book, - To say the least, out of the two of us I would be the one guilty. Not like you have much say in it anyway, but if it really bothers you I can name you the most insane potato of them all.\n\nShe chuckled and stood up. She didn’t mind the perspective of staying at the gorge for the rest of her life. She already had everything she needed to become a complete hermit and once the school was over and the transfer rejected she really would have no reason to come back to the city ever again. It was quite unsettling to realize that she would spend the rest of her days speaking to the potatoes, but at least there was quite a bit of certainty in that. One day she would just be too weak to hunt and die from hunger or eaten by the wolf. Quite natural and organic. At least she would have had plenty of good days before that would happen.\n\n- Yeah, quite different outcomes to consider. It is going to be sad to leave all of you behind and try to move out, but at least it would be something new that I definitely would like, - Kara looked over her plantation with shameless pride. Her bootleg gardening skills looked nothing like textbook greenhouses, but all plants were healthy tall and lavishly green, - Hey, no need to be sarcastic. I might be the only one applying. They must fill the quota, so don’t be sassy or I might really consider it.\n\nEvening breeze freshened up the gorge. It felt nice to finish a day on a good quarrel, maybe the last of the serious quarrels she would ever have.\n\n- You just watch. In twenty years I will be the best farmer in Quattor with a multitude of people admiring my hyper productive harvests. It would be the crop that will feed all states and people would riot to get my creme de la creme, - Kara felt noxious even just saying this to her potatoes. Maybe it was for the best if her potatoes would stay in this gorge forever undiscovered. It was definitely something she would have to work on if she ever considered moving back into society. A little psychological disorder that sure would go away given enough time and practice.\n\n- Sorry, thanks for being so understanding. I know you know that I would turn into a very different person, but it shouldn’t matter if we never meet again right? - Persival didn’t answer, Kara couldn’t come up with any good lines.","n":122},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"It was an ok breakfast. Company could have been better, but it wasn’t the first time Kara had trouble keeping a conversation going. She could have asked the lady for her name, but if she still called miss Olive by a nickname why should anyone's name matter? It would have only led to an unnecessary introduction and Kara wasn’t about to discover that yet another human knew her name without her telling. Plus it must have been easier for the bar lady. For all she knew Kara would not return next year. Quite most likely.\n\n- Allright, do you have any advice before I go? - Kara finished her breakfast and stood up. Seemed like a reasonable question for the road.\n\n- It’s nice that you guys are trying to be friends, it’s harder to lose when there is something worth fighting for, - woman picked up the empty plate. She was right, it was harder to lose friends than strangers. What would Kara feel if she saw Rein die in the pit? Probably nothing much, he would have been just a face that looked familiar. It would be unsettling, yes, but would she blame herself as harshly as she did for what happened to Percival? And yet somehow now it felt like a fair, however painful, trade off. Because it only made sense. Human life is more valuable than the life of a potato. However, how fair was it to change the course of the tides to take up a spot on a limited salvation ship for your own friend instead of a stranger? At the price of a Percival.\n\n- Thanks, - Kara hesitantly looked down feeling something weighing on her chest, - So nothing new.\n\nShe walked out and called up Fluffers. They went one more round the town. There wasn’t much activity at all, most of these people seemed like they spent quite a bit of the time drinking. No wonder. With walls this high and strict gates these people were basically locked in to live their staged lives. In a village that could easily be burned as any mine could collapse or an oil rig could explode. No, Kara would never be happy here.","n":123},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"- Kara stop sneaking food in your pockets, - mother shook little Kara’s hand and she dropped the half torn sausage to the floor, - Don’t you understand that it leaves stains?\n\nLittle Kara just stood in silence blushing fiercely as she was caught quite red handed. It never passed her mind to care about the mess she was making.\n\n- Sorry, I forgot, - finally words formed in her head and then in the air as she spoke.\n\n- Listen, I don’t mind that you want to help Fluffers, but please think with your head next time, - mother tapped on little Kara’s head and she heard the knocks on her forehead.","n":124},{"chapter":"Wants and Don'ts","text":"It was midday when Kara returned to the fence of the mansion. She gently patted Fluffer Huggins.\n\n- Think you can take me over the fence yet? - she jokingly smiled and felt flaming tom ignite something within him. For a moment everything around got engulfed in flames. It felt warm and quite dark before lights came back up and Kara found herself standing with Fluffers on the other side. She looked back finding a scorched mark on the spot where she was just standing, - Well, not quite over, but I’ll count it.\n\nKara was quite a bit shocked. Fluffers did that before, but she would never think that she could jump with him.\n\n- Good to know you can do that, pal, - she gave flaming tom a nice head pat.","n":125},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"- Well that was quick, - Tarik appeared almost out of nowhere. Kara didn’t expect him to wait right at the door.\n\n- Didn’t really see anything interesting, - Kara walked past him letting Fluffer Huggins disappear. It wasn’t worth having another conversation about his behavior. Not like she could do anything about it. Maybe he would just outgrow this stage.\n\n- Any remaining questions? - man must have turned to see Kara walk down the hallway. His voice sounded quite clear.\n\n- A new map I assume, - she didn’t see any special vehicles outside, so the journey would have to be on foot.\n\n- Yep, make sure to use a front door next time, - Tarik started walking after her. She slowed down to let him through first.\n\n- Sure thing, I’m not an idiot, - Kara sighed. She was an idiot. Training grounds coliseum wasn’t in Septum, it must have just had a gateway replica of some sort. She wasn’t getting to Quattuor on foot. Or a horse. Unless, of course, the capital would feel comfortable disclosing where the other states actually were. Heroes would run all over the place.","n":126},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"It was a rock overhang. It looked quite terrifying as Kara looked downwards on a twenty meter or so drop underneath. She sat down hanging her legs in the air and feeling nervous waves follow upwards from her feet. It was a great place for a break. Fresh air, beautiful view of the forest and not too comfortable to fall asleep. Sun sets and rises must have looked phenomenal up here. Something to motivate her to go back and forth from day to day. Maybe she will always stop there on her way to a new home. Definitely a possibility if she continues in this direction.\n\nAnd so she did.","n":127},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"It took Kara less than five minutes to gather up her barely unpacked backpack. Not like she cared about anything in it anyway. Most of this stuff seemed too replaceable, useless or redundant to be there anyway. Who puts in a cutlery knife and a swiss knife into a backpack meant to be carried miles on your back? Maybe Kara was just annoyed that with so many things there it was not a safe place for her potato parcel.\n\n- Good morning, sunshine, - She dragged her precious potatoes from under the bed and hung them over her shoulder. She probably could just leave them here like Tallie left her sick weasel with Tarik for safe keeping, but at least Charcoal had a chance of gaining some sort of sentience and running away. Probably to the wilderness, but it still would do much better than poor potatoes. Maybe she should have left them, but Kara was in no mood for another separation dilemma, - Hope you roots are ready for another long walk.\n\nKnock on the door revealed Tarik standing right behind it with a map. His eyes lightly glanced over the potato parcel expressing light agitation, but man knew better than touch upon this situation. Fluffer Huggins might have been under Kara's full control, but that played heavily against Tarik in questions regarding these three vegetable roots.\n\n- Here, stay on the road and I think you will meet up with the rest of the team around here, - he pointed at a lakeside section of the road, - If you don’t get there by the morning then head straight to this village, - he traced his finger along side of the river and stopped at the dot named Mantichfield. Weird name, definitely not something you would find in Septum. Kara wondered what it meant or who it was named after.\n\n- Aye, aye, capitan, - Kara took the map and headed towards the exit, - Take good care of Charcoal or Tallie might actually kill you. Actually, if anything happens just tell her that he ran away. Might buy you some time while she looks around the forest.\n\nTarik could have at least chuckled. He knew that Kara would not turn around to see if he smiled. It’s not like she wanted any gratification, it was just annoying to be stuck in momentary anticipation of it. Maybe she should just stop trying to communicate, not like anything she said carried any value.\n\nKara opened the front door feeling the change of air outside. It was still fresh air, but much drier and way warmer. Outside looked exactly as she remembered. Even guards were staying in the same spots and looking in the same directions. She wondered if Quattour heroes were anywhere around and would their door be locked as long as Kara was holding it open. It would have been fun to see competition before they actually have to kill each other. Fun, but probably not nice. Kara didn’t really know if killing friends is worse than wishing them to be killed by someone else. Maybe they could trip and fall stupidly.\n\nThe town seemed to be the same too, but Kara could swear she never saw these people before. They just looked stronger and healthier and yet much simpler. Just like Kara imagined them to be. They spoke in a weird dialect. Much softer tone and way longer words, but occasionally recognisable enough to have a rough idea of the context. It was almost like she was walking in a dream. Except she doubted she would be able to imagine so many new word variations.","n":128},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"It became a tradition. Kara decided to come by the overhang everyday to spend some time away from everything and just sit observing the valley. She also vowed never to go there to keep the mystery. She didn’t want to know anything about it beyond what she saw. Maybe there was a border of Septum somewhere further beyond the horizon of trees, maybe if she continued going she would have reached the ocean. The possibilities were endless unless she actually explored.\n\nKara sat silently watching the sun set blanketing the forest into warmer orange light. Rare sight for the cold climate of Septum, so she soaked every detail she could in her memory. It must have been nice to live in warmer states with no fear of long and hungry winters.","n":129},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Once Kara got to the gates it was obvious that she wasn’t home. There were no mountains and the entire view was filled with farms and life. She looked up at the sun to see if it was different too. It seemed to be higher than usual. Quattour must have been closer to the equator. It made sense - plants need plenty of light to grow. What didn’t make sense was why they were so protective of their produce and got upset when someone else tried to tap in on the vegetable food production. Everything they produced was thoroughly sterilized before it was sent to other states. Not a single orange would have any seeds in it and even if you would get lucky you would have to pray that no one would discover it growing on your window.\n\nIt was a nice walk for the first two hours. Endless rows of farmlands had a certain organized charm. Kara soon recognized some of them to be corn, although most of it looked like wheat. It wasn’t like these fields were exactly labeled for tourists to know the difference. Maybe she could tell them all apart if she was born here or maybe these families stayed true to their land and never left the premises playing the game of lords and struggle of filling quotas. For a moment it was funny to imagine how Kara would take over Quattuor to cover all its lands with potato descendants of Teresa, Vincent and Bork. People would try to throw corn in retaliation, but elongated shape would make it harder to throw hence requiring more resources on training troops. Potatoes would definitely take over the corn and wheat doesn’t even have a hard core to be thrown. Everything else would just lose the battle of numbers. Completely hypothetical situation solemnly because a long time ago the government decided to keep true to the preservation of diversity. Kara was almost sure that the technology to create a super crop containing all needed nutrients already existed; only it would mean that Quattuor would have to deny its citizens the choice of crop and at that point lazy farmers would have no trouble filling their quota with crops stolen from the neighbor.\n\nIt always came around all the same. First communists hit it off with a strong idea completely forgetting that humans would never miss out on an opportunity to profit from difference. It was one of the stronger points of the current state affairs. By giving states monopoly in their field it left the state to compete with itself ruthlessly and by any means. And the government just fulfilled agreements to hold each other's processes exclusive. Kara didn’t learn that in school. It was just a meaningful explanation of how the cold world of mortal human politics worked. Septum never had a war with Quintus, Quitus just supported a certain sector of Septum on its rise to power.","n":130},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Everyone knows that others too have their egos. They just forget it sometimes. Kara wasn’t happy to see the office building completely gone. Not the actual building, but all of its inhabitants too. Major company ripped apart to the bare bone with all of its workers gone. Without anyone knowing what happened. People on the street walked by as if it was like this for millions of years.\n\nThere was no blood and no furniture or wallpapers. Kara heard about these things happening and it was only rational that it would happen after an oil rig explosion. Afterall there was a reason why Kara and Rein lived right next door to each other. The truth was stripped off naked. She could have as well moved states to stay safe, except she had no reason to. It was widely known to leave children alone. No one liked this kind of violence.","n":131},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Kara wanted to stop and play with Fluffer Huggins in the fields. It was quite torturous that two things that she trusted her life with would never combine into a happy trio. She just realized that if she was to grow a new potato farm she would have to stay there without Fluffers. He would have to watch from quite far. Ironically there was no way in this lifetime Kara would allow any sort of fires in her garden ever again.\n\nShe stopped at the little hillside in the shadow of a lonely fruiting tree. It was gorgeous, but it looked kind of lonely and out of place. Maybe it was a gift. A kind gesture or a peace offering. Maybe a desperate white flag. Why else would it have been left so far from the farm house. Somewhere where Kara could just easily grab its fruits and run. It wasn’t nice or legal, but there was no way on this planet the owner of this farm could have known the exact number of fruits on this tree to care. He would definitely never know the difference if Kara picked one from the top.\n\nIt took less than a moment. Kara felt the spring in her step and the next moment she jumped up high enough to grab the exact orange that she marked. It looked quite sour, and must have had a hard time competing with surrounding crops without any special treatment. Kara was almost tempted to grab another one, but she already felt ashamed for the first one. She gently touched the tree and tried to nurture it a bit.\n\n- Sorry, grabby hands and lack of thought seem to be my signatures, - Kara felt the bark rumble under her palm as the orange tree started gaining colour and fruits on it filled with the juice, - Hope that wasn’t illegal.","n":132},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"It was unbelievably stupid at first. Waking up every morning before dawn to walk thirty minutes to the overhang and running for two hours to be on time for the first class. Fun, but stupid. By no means it was a sustainable tradition. Mainly because every day the sun was rising later and later and Kara had to run faster and faster. By the end of September she had already abandoned this habit with a promise to return to it in the spring. It sure made her trips to school longer. There was simply no reason to run that fast anymore.\n\nNow Kara was sitting on freshly wet stone and looking at a gray horizon knowing that she would not see sunset through this much fog. It sucked to have gloomy weekends and yet Kara still came over. It was still beautiful. It reminded her of the first time she discovered it. Sun didn’t hoard all of the attention to itself as it usually did. There was much more room for breathing without anxious anticipation of rise or set.","n":133},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Kara hid the orange in a potato parcel. It could have been either bad or good for them. Kara kind of wanted to see the difference, but soon threw the orange into her backpack. Her potatoes might have been susceptible to new germs or viruses. Mostly intrusive thoughts, Kara didn’t want to stress about potatoes more than she already did.\n\nIt was even harder not to eat the orange. For some reason she really wanted to give it to Floats. The tree didn’t look like the heroes had ransacked it and the blue man was too well mannered to grab something by himself. She silently scolded herself for not grabbing the sweeter orange after she helped the tree, but then she would have the dilemma of eating the tastier one or saving it for Floats. She didn’t particularly want to eat the sour one if she knew there was a better one.\n\nIt felt quite weird not to do selfish things. Well, not as weird as doing something potentially illegal to make somebody a tiny bit happier. Happier than it would have made the owner of the tree, but maybe less happy than a child for whom it might have been a first orange to set a lifelong adoration of oranges. On the other hand, maybe it was better for the orange to be sour.","n":134},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"It’s been quite a while since she last went to the overhang, but today was special. Kara was thoroughly exhausted from the exams and it was the first snow. Freezing morning. The only reason she woke up today was the excitement to see the valley turn white for the first time. It was every bit worth the struggle. White confetti snow glistered in the early sun rays. It would have melted if Kara didn’t make it in time. She watched as the forest slowly turned back to green and yellow.","n":135},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Kara walked for quite a bit after the sunset, but decided to camp further away from the lake. Mainly because turning up in the middle of the night to a camp full of jumpy heroes wasn’t a particularly safe idea. Last time Tallie was startled in her sleep she almost killed Rein.\n\nKara climbed a tree for a nap. She wasn’t particularly scared of falling down in the middle of the night, but she did urge Tallie to make a safety rope knot so she had to do it herself. If the little goblin warrior woman was somewhere in the area Kara would much rather be found following all safety protocols to set a good example.","n":136},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Kara woke up in the middle of the night with a feeling of absolute terror. It was a nice dream that started in a soft sunshine and then from the treeline walked out a dark cloaked figure with a wide eyed, twisted hag face. It followed Kara from dream frame to dream frame coming closer and closer with each new one. Last one was the most terrifying. Hag touched her shoulder from behind and Kara could swear her heart had stopped the moment she turned around. She could barely remember what the dream was about, but the face of the old woman printed in her mind as she carefully listened to the howling of the wind outside.","n":137},{"chapter":"Back on track","text":"Kara woke up feeling a cold breeze pass through her bones. Her eyes shot open and she almost fell off a tree at the sight of a cloaked figure briefly sitting on her branch with two cloudy glowing eyes looking straight at her. Fluffer Huggins lit the tree on fire a moment later making the shadow flee back into the darkness.\n\n- Fluffer! Down! - Kara panicked for a second putting out the flames with what she only assumed was magic, - What was that?!\n\nIt really didn’t seem like the hag was after the potatoes or in need of any food that would be considered normal. For all Kara knew she was not to ever sleep alone in Quattuor again. Good thing the transfer plan didn’t come through. It would have sucked to go through so much trouble and get stuck in place which quite possibly hosts the creature from her nightmares. Especially if it found her literally on her first night there.\n\nMaybe it was a coincidence. Maybe Taric asked yet another friend to make sure that Kara doesn’t think about running away in Quattuor. To be completely honest, Kara would prefer that version to any other. She would even thank Tarik for it if he comes clean. Sick method, yes, but it better to be a method than something that had a separate sentience and motives. At least Kara knew what Taric wanted.\n\nShe quickly untied herself and jumped down. She basically ran towards the lake. It must have been minutes before the sunrise by the time she made it there to discover a morbid sight of skinny men lying around a half military camp in extremely uncomfortable positions as if they dropped on the spot. Her teammates appeared from behind one of the tents in two packed horse wagons in a quite desperate hurry.\n\n- Kara! - Fezzik reached out his hand and tugged Kara on the driver's seat with him, - We gotta get out of here before Victorean shows up with the cleaning crew.\n\n- What the actual? - Kara was thoroughly confused and terrified, - Did you guys somehow manage to release ancient evil or something while I was away? It was just one day! - Kara rubbed her shoulder feeling the consequences of a sudden jolt on her shoulder, - Why are you stealing wagons?\n\n- Well, - Fezzik looked back at the rest of the team and Tallie weirdly looked the most upset. Usually she would be the most excited about a good brawl, but this time it was quite different. Rein looked quite shocked and the rest just sat with stone faces, - It’s not like these men would need those anymore. Did you see anything?\n\n- Only the most terrifying nightmare fuel of all time! What was that creature? No offense, Haderach, but it looked even worse than you, - Kara was met with three pairs of confused looks. It appeared that the rest of the team didn’t quite know what happened either. No one responded, so Kara didn’t ask more questions. She was content with the fact that she wasn’t the one attracting all the bad luck to the group. The insanity of a decision to stay with them, on other hand, was overridden by the fact that she didn’t have a choice. At least she didn’t have to walk the rest of the way.\n\nIt was a weird consensus. They didn’t talk about things that happened, there was really no point to. Mostly because, no matter from which side they looked at it, it was still an unnatural cause of death. They lived in places where people just disappeared. Now they were seeing corpses. It should have been no difference because people didn’t come back after disappearing either. And yet somehow it felt different when it happened in the moment they had witnessed. Taric resurrected the weasel, so why was it so important for heroes to feel the gravity of the even heavier uncertainty. Kara hoped that it was a part of a well planned cycle. She didn’t check the pulse on the corpses. Taric probably made up some mysterious ghost to make sure that we keep on our toes while protecting the crops. After all, they were in a training program directed by someone with zero clue of how to set up a believable situation.\n\n- Oh, Floats, - Kara suddenly remembered something, - I got an orange for you.\n\n- Oh, thank you, dear, - he really tried to sound as nonchalant as always as he reached over for the orange. Kara felt like an utterly useless member of this team and mostly so by her own will, but she at least could be nice about it. She wasn’t really the one trying to win anything.\n\n- Yeah, kind of thought that you would not have noticed that tree, - Kara smiled, hoping it would have brightened the mood. It did mix the silence with some orange aroma and the sound of peeling.","n":138},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"There are certain things in life that you should not question if you already know the worst answer. Words that only sound smart, but can be interpreted in so many bad ways and applied to so many wrong situations that one might wonder why would anyone ever bother to write them down. Why question what happens after death if you already know the baseline to be eternal non sensory darkness?\n\nKara didn’t question such silly things usually. It probably would be a way to annoy Rein and his big brain at the time of absolute boredom, but now that their group was filled with adults it would probably be too embarrassing to be fun. It certainly wasn’t funny for anybody on this wagon trip.\n\nBy the time the heroes made it to the village, the mood had almost gone to normal. It wasn’t the first time they encountered something completely out of normality with many seemingly unnecessary casualties. Tallie briefly mentioned that one of them was a really good fighter and that they were kind enough to share camp with heroes. They were transporting some dangerous government prisoner. What a great coincidence.\n\nYet it was still unsettling. Was there a way to save these men? Maybe it was supposed to urge the group to take more initiative in these matters. Maybe they could stand watches at night to make sure no one helps the prisoner to escape.\n\nYet it wasn’t their mission. It wasn’t even their state. They were not supposed to do anything beyond the protocol otherwise they could get in trouble. Even them being in the proximity of this accident was a bad look. Kara didn’t really know what kind of immunity being a hero granted, but Fezzik rode the wagon like it was only reasonable. Or maybe they had two wagons when they left the mansion. However that would mean that they specifically decided not to leave Kara a horse. No wonder they missed that orange tree.\n\n- So do you think they would kill the horses too? - Kara decided to test the grounds. Ask the question with the worst known answer. Bottom line Fezzik would think that Kara assumed they were thieves. Nothing new in that department.\n\n- I don’t know, Victorian said to get out of there and gave a timer, - Fezzik spoke calmly, but Kara could hear a slight concern. It was nice to know that they stole the horses. Maybe it is quite possible that their lives were saved there. Heroes seemed to have made progress. So far they obtained a weasel and saved two horses. The latter, of course, being the progress part.","n":139},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"It was one of many things Kara didn’t like about the school. Movie nights with movies that just barely balanced on the edge of acceptably entertaining. It was a course on Senio state and the movie was supposed to show the perspective through which they trained their heroes. You would think that a state with the greatest number of victories would have the most heroes, but for a culture of individualism the team aspect of the tournament was a complete waste for them.\n\nMost of the time Senio heroes went into the tournament to show off their personal style and any extra surviving team members meant the need to share the winnings. The movie was supposed to encourage empathy and something about rising above the system. Some edgy morals and great costumes. Kara doubted that life was that unfair in Senio. Even Septum wasn’t as bad.\n\nExcept for the essay requirement, of course.","n":140},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"There seemed to be a commotion at the main square of the village. Some lady in a slightly burned leather jacket and roughed up look. She was standing on a wooden crate explaining some lustrous action and definitely working quite hard to please the crowd.\n\n- And then the manticore attacked us with its fire breath once more, but this time we were ready. I shot it right into the heart and it flew up into the air in agony before plummeting straight into the lake, - the lady was quite articulate and even stretched out her bow to demonstrate how she took aim at the beast's heart.\n\n- What is it now, fire breathing manticores? Can’t Quintus keep away from mutating any more of their hideous creatures? - Rein looked at the show lady with great pain. It was indeed ridiculous how much freedom the animal state allowed themselves with their field. It was even more ridiculous how little effort they put in to contain their experiments defending the position that animals are supposed to be free to stabilize new resilient genomes to fit better into their wild niches.\n\n- Well, this escalated quickly, - Kara sighed and jumped off the wagon. She quickly made it through the crowd and got to the boasting lady during her little antract. She smelled like a dumpster, - Hey, do you know if there are any more of these beasts in the area? We were sent to protect one of the farms from marauders, but it would be nice to know how to deal with local fauna, - Kara tried to lay out the situation, but the more she talked the more she felt like it was a bad idea.\n\n- Well that sounds like you got a late message. Program already sent us to deal with the troubles of this village, but I guess you guys can sit around if we need more hands on harvest, - lady sounded condescending, but nothing Kara would react too negatively to, - My name is Cindall and this is Brian and Jeff. We are heroes of Quintus, so there is nothing to worry about little one, - she patted Kara on her head and headed to her teammates.\n\n- Hey there, hey, - Fezzik finally caught on to Kara in the crowd and seemed to have questions of his own, - Any advice or good tips on, - He covered his nose in a startled reaction, - on how to fight these local manticores? Dam, what is that smell?\n\nCindall chuckled and so did Brian. Jeff seemed to be a bit slow.\n\n- Oh yeah, let me write it down for you. You know these beasts, - lady smiled and briefly tapped on her nose, - sensitive sniffers, - she wrote down some sort of a recipe and signed with a name and a heart, - Make sure to save this one, it will become quite valuable after we win the tournament, - she gave the paper to Fezzik and walked off flipping her long dark ponytail to the back.\n\n- Yeah, sure, - Fezzik muttered under his breath and Kara chuckled.\n\n- I think she likes you, - Kara nudged her demon teammate with her elbow and turned back to the wagons, - Make sure you two don’t get too attached.\n\nIt was a mean comment, but his tournament wasn’t particularly designed to fit the Romeo and Juliet happy ending scenarios. Kara was right, it wasn’t nice to meet somebody who by default was meant to kill or be killed. It was fun though.","n":141},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"It was given that Kara would return to that place. It called for her like a beacon of light in a gray unfamiliar forest. The only other misfit. She knew that this attachment was something that she knew as a coping mechanism. Like a man on an Island and his coconut. Girl walked till the evening and planned to walk back through the night. She came back straight away. It was only sensible, if people were to start searching for her eventually some would go into the forest and find the potato. And it would be gone.\n\nKara just wanted something to mark the place that she chose. There was nothing else to do and she had way too much energy and anxiety building up to sleep anyway. It was nothing special, but really the only thing she could do. She doubted that she would ever go that far again if there wasn’t something to come back for. Kara wanted to build up a garden just to observe.","n":142},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"- So what is this? - Rein looked quite disgusted by the lingering smell of recently departed Cindall. He looked at the note in Fezziks hands and grimaced with even deeper disgust, - What in heaven is goblins knot? - He gave Tallie a side eye.\n\n- It’s my boogers, you idiot, - the raspy nature of Tallie's voice made Kara chuckle.\n\n- Well, that takes care of that, I guess, - Fezzik looked through the list and instructions one more time, - Yeah, I’m not familiar with these plants. We might need to ask around for help.\n\n- Muckroot, that sounds kind of familiar, - Kara chimed in mostly to join the chaos of a discussion, - I think those grow around dry river banks.\n\n- Maybe we can just get these in the store? - Fezzik sighed and looked around for any store signs, but must have caught the eye of some halfling that instantly started strutting towards the heroes of Septum.\n\n- Good lord, you guys are finally here, - this halfling was much livelier than Haderach, but at the same time Kara could not shake the feeling that this wasn’t something so positive. His voice already suggested that he wasn’t about making friends, - Local gremlins are really getting out of hand, no offense, - he gave Tallie a side eye, but she just shrugged in response, - I’m Ben, Embers's uncle. I talked to the local tavern. They should have rooms ready for you.\n\n- So what’s up with these Quintus heroes? - Fezzik cut straight to the point. Not that they expected it to be a problem, but it was still a questionable situation. Heroes weren’t particularly known for holding back during training. Teams colliding together before the tournament seemed like a completely reckless decision on the organizers' parts. Well, for the main bit, Tallie would kill over a weasel. Septum heroes go all over the place on their mood alignment. It felt familiarly incriminating by this point.\n\n- Well, long story short, they are doing a pretty shitty job as it is, - Ben sighed with a chuckle, - They are trying to keep wild manticores away, but I think they just want to hide the fact that it’s a new one. No one saw damn things, people just disappeared. And all while nothing gets done about damn gremlins.\n\nIt was unsettling how freely uncle Ben talked about these things in front of them. Not about the whole thing, but just as if it was an absolutely normal, just rare, pest problem. Maybe Tallie would be too busy with other things anyway. They would just have to avoid working in the same sectors. Separate the working grounds and make sure that the paths do not cross. Kara was beginning to be worried. Fluffer Huggins was a bit of a curve ball himself. More accidental in property, but still quite potentially harmful. If suddenly manticores would come over to them they should be ready to repel them on their own too. Kara would assume that Quintus' heroes would not interrupt them while they are getting used to the regimen. They seemed confident enough.\n\n- So, if not a secret, do you know where we can get this? - Fezzik pulled Kara out of the train of thought by asking a question interrupting the ongoing random gibberish that Ben was talking about. Kara was largely grateful for a break. Demon extended a hand with a recipe and uncle read the recipe. For a moment there was silence, as much of it as a town square would allow.\n\n- Ah yes, there is a herbalist store right down this street, - Ben swung his hand in the direction of one of the streets and raised one of his eyebrows, - Don’t know if they have blossoms this time of year, but you may try. You know what this thing does, right?\n\n- The smell? Yeah, it’s pretty nasty, - Fezzik nodded, but for some reason Kara had a weird feeling about it. What if manticores liked that smell?","n":143},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"Kara first got slightly excited for the sight. It looked like a pretty picture from the textbook, but then came the realization of the size. It was bigger than any dog Kara had remembered. It looked the other way right now smelling around some tree, so she just tried to sneak up a little closer to have a better look. It wasn’t looking for her, she never climbed the other side to leave any scent around that treeline.","n":144},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"A trip to the shop revealed that blossoms, against Ben's prediction, were quite luckily in stock. That, of course, didn't mean that the store didn’t just run out of muckroots. Luckily a young lady at the counter told them that they can easily get some down the dried up river and be careful not to go to the other side of the bank. Something about goblin territories. And she would be interested in buying any extra heroes could gather.\n\nSo it was decided to split up. Kara wanted to do the gathering right away and after some bickering that she was fine to go alone, Fezzik convinced her to take Tallie and Rein with her. Rein was surprisingly quite perfectly fine with her idea. Tallie didn’t really care where to go, thought her hands were very jittery with her hammer.\n\n- So Tallie, do you know these goblins? - Rein tried a bit of small talk. Though somehow his voice made it sound quite sarcastical. It was obvious she didn’t know them. They were goblins in Quattuor and she just turned goblin four weeks ago.\n\n- I don’t know. Who knows, maybe, - Tallie sighed and nonchalantly continued on her way, - It doesn’t hurt checking it out.\n\nIt was quite uncanny to hear that response. Why would Tallie know any other goblins on this planet? She was from Septum. Now Kara wondered if maybe Tallie transferred from Quattuor to Septum and that required the opposite transformation of looks. All these questions made Kara’s head hurt.\n\n- Rein, stop assuming things about Tallie, - Kara snapped seemingly out of nowhere, but she was still pretty tense after the weasel incident.\n\n- Can you chill, Kara? I am just trying to make conversation. We don’t want to go in there not knowing how Tallie feels about them, - Rein sounded quite sensible, but Kara still felt like his words meant something else.\n\n- Listen, I don’t care. If they fight we fight back, - Tallie chimed in and walked continued in silence. She was right in some way. It wasn’t like they initiated any attacks on things outside their own team.\n\nWhen they finally came across the river, it was obvious that something was happening on the other side. Kara didn’t care, she just slid down to the river and started gathering the muckroot. Rein stayed on the watch and who knows where Tallie went. She could take care of herself. Meanwhile Kara was trying to remember the last time she dug some roots to sell on the market. It felt nice. If it smelled of moss and pines around she would even feel at home.","n":145},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"- Unus, Culo, Tribus, Quattuor, Quintus, Senio, Septum, Octingetti and Novem, - little Kara tried to sound enthusiastic, but it was the stupidest question out of the bunch. Teacher wasn’t even trying to challenge her by this point, - Why does Octingetti have such a silly name?\n\n- Well I bet there are kids in Octingetti saying the same thing about Septum, - Teacher sounded annoyed and moved on to the next question. Little Kara imagined little kids thinking that Septum is silly. They must have been some silly kids if they made fun of something that sounded so cool.","n":146},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"Kara would probably pack the roots and go back to the village, no problem. She would even ignore the wild cries that Tallie was roaring as she was probably swinging her hammer. Maybe she would leave her there to have fun until the sunset. The plan has changed when some mad goblin decided to take his aim at her. He missed by an inch and that was about enough for Fluffer Huggins to apparate from the thin air right next to the attacker burning him quite severely just milliseconds before it exploded to smithereens leaving nothing but floating ashes.\n\n- Shoots and leaves, Rein, - Kara shot a concerned look at her friend trying to forget what she had just witnessed.\n\n- You burned him first, - he just shrugged, clearly not so happy himself.\n\n- I’m going to go get Tallie, - Kara straightened up and climbed to the other side of the dry river bank. She emerged right around the area where the poor gremlin just stood. Fluffer Huggins was busy dodging some arrows and not so dodging others. It was getting quite annoying, but, surprisingly, gremlins didn’t care about running away - Tallie?! Common, let's go back!\n\nThere was no response, but once Kara saw the situation she quite understood why. Tallie was charging at a goblin who weirdly enough didn’t have any sign of the fluffy tail, but maybe only female ones did. What was even more understandable is that somehow Cindall was a little further down the road shooting arrows left and right into quite hostile goblins.\n\n- Hey there, need any help? - Kara was just being polite. She would much rather not be involved in whatever was happening, - Tallie, are you done?\n\n- I am doing just fine, - Cindall looked like she was wounded, but nothing that Kara would call serious. At least for heroes.\n\n- I just need to kill the biggest one and I’ll become their chief! - Tallie sounded beyond excited.\n\n- For sprouts sake, Tallie. I got the muckroot, they won’t let you stay to be a chief of some goblin gang, - Kara felt slightly uncomfortable with the whole goblin chief logic. For all she knew it could have been true.\n\nTallie growled and turned around. Goblins in their turn switched to retreat. Then something jumped out of the bushes and ran towards Cindall. Surprisingly, the smelly lady didn’t shoot. It was a giant racoon with a halfling rider. Looked as ridiculous as it sounded. Quite cute if you throw the ridiculousness out of the window.","n":147},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"It wasn’t too hard to come up with a plan for a build. Just cut a bunch of trees, lay out the foundation and assemble the rest from there. It was much harder to actually cut down trees. Much harder than movies made it seem. Apparently real life was a bit more dull and challenging than the imaginary world on the screen.\n\nIt took Kara almost an hour to cut down her first tree and it wasn’t even that thick. And forget about dragging it to the marked out location. The tree has also appeared to be a bit too heavy and drag and anchoring of the branches didn’t help one bit. Now she was just laying down on the ground cursing the entirety of her stupid plan. Everything hurts. Her hands already burned with blisters and that's after she used her t-shirt as a cushion.\n\n- I swear to god, Optimus, you better be worth it! - Kara shouted loud and clear and definitely put all of the blame on the potato nesting somewhere down in the gorge.","n":148},{"chapter":"Good friends","text":"- So you guys didn’t want to take the other route? - Kara felt a bit awkward walking back to the town with two Quintus heroes. The halfling on the raccoon turned out to be Zilli, a real charm and a half if it was the opposite day.\n\n- There is only one route to the village, girl, - Zilli just scored one more negative point in the piggy bank. At least she didn’t seem to know Kara’s name out of the box, - you guys really shouldn’t be waddling around like this, you only get in our way.\n\nKara would answer something, but it would not be worth it. The more they talked, the more personal this conflict would get and Kara really didn’t want to think about vendettas and grudges yet. It was their first day on a real mission, Kara didn’t need violent intrusive thoughts clouding her excitement.\n\n- Oh drop it, Zilli. We have no reason to fight here, - Cindall was a bit too chill about the whole situation. It almost felt normal to talk to her. Maybe it wasn’t that bad to be friends for as long as it could last. Afterall at least half of the heroes in this village had a quite literal timer on their lives. They could as well invest into spending the remaining two months in a relatively good mood.\n\nThe silence almost felt normal by the time the group had reached the tavern. So normal that when they saw Fezzik and Haderach playing a card game with Jeff and Bryan at the busy common room no one spoke a word of the bickering that happened on the way back. Apparently Haderach was quite good at card games and Jeff and Brian were just good sports. Kara almost felt ashamed of thinking them to be straight enemies. Maybe they will have a good time cooperating and maybe they won’t have to kill each other in the tournament.\n\n- So I guess we will party tonight? - Kara smiled and triumphantly waved the muckroots in the air. No one was as excited as she was, but Cindall seemed to like the idea.","n":149},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Parties. Reckless time to spend in relative safety of common ground rule of the cease fire for the benefit of the party. No one really wants to ruin the mood before the drinks roll in. Late at night it all stops to matter, drunken ruckus has always been an acceptable excuse ground for apologies. As long as you don’t say more that you could fight for.\n\nIt struck Kara with a quiet and alien state when she walked into the room full of yet to be drunken men. If she would ever imagine going to the party it would probably feel about the same. Maybe if she ever cared to go out with her classmates and end up somewhere in the ragged bar. It would probably start this year as they all gradually would turn of age appropriate for drinking and setting lifetime friendships that would last in memory till the day she died. Bland and mundane memory pool to cling on to and yet so natural for so many.\n\n- Hey, John! Poor a round of drinks for my Septum friends! - Cindall was clearly in a great mood, - Rest up, this one is on me, - She smiled and headed towards the table heating up with a card game, - Looks like someone is having fun, boys.\n\nKara wanted to follow, but Tallie took a head start eager to check out the other team's goblin. Grax was quite a charming man if you would trust Cindalls words literally. Kara didn’t want to play a wing man to Tallie’s routine. She wasn’t particularly good with people and goblins were completely out of her expertise. She decided to sit with Floats instead who happily enjoyed the solitude of the table that probably was chosen before cards rolled in.\n\n- Want to drink with me? - Kara didn’t really know how to start the conversation. She felt completely out of place and with the mud all over her clothes probably severely underdressed for the occasion. Good thing that nobody in the room smelled particularly good. Besides Floats, of course. The smell of citrus still lingered in the air around him.\n\n- Not particularly in this crowd, my dear, - Floats was polite as always. He did float above his surroundings most of the time bringing some peace and order in the overstanding turbulence of their situations. Even if he didn’t say much.\n\n- At least don’t leave me hanging, - Kara sat down with a tired thud. Not very ladylike, but it was the last thought on her mind. It’s been four weeks, almost a month. For them. It’s been a week for her, her nerves were on the edge and she couldn’t really blame anyone. She made sure that all of the choices she made were her own. Random enough and powerfully ridiculous, they all were the same in the light of the day. Mortal or not, it was nice to know that there was a timer on this particular shit show. For once she just rolled with it just to spite the odds.\n\nThe drinks came in in a heartbeat. Kara raised her cup and Floats politely cheered up with his own. He drank a half, Kara downed it with determination. Second time in her life she was about to get drunk and beyond that there was still the first time for everything else.","n":150},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Red, - Rein started the game. It was quite a fun one because Kara had a chance of winning.\n\n- Orange.\n\n- Yellow.\n\n- Green.\n\n- Blue, - Rein made a mistake, like he always did.\n\n- You meant cyan, - Kara smiled slightly.\n\n- No, it’s blue then indigo, - Rein whined knowing where Kara was going.\n\n- It’s ridiculous, then you would switch out the violet and end up with only six colors, - Kara knew that Rein thought that she was right.\n\n- Fine, Cyan, - Rein went on with the game.","n":151},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Kara didn’t know what was so upsetting about seeing Rein walk over to a bar rather than sit with her. It was wildly infuriating. What was even more infuriating is that he went there after that taller than average halfling girl named Zilli. It was infuriating that Kara even cared about it slightest bit, - Look at him, he can’t even start talking to me but so absolutely fine talking to her, - Kara only said that because only Floats was around to hear it. He just smiled politely without pressing the issue. Kara wasn’t even sure if he understood what she meant.\n\n- Well, she does have a raccoon, - Floats chipperly chuckled and shared his drink with Kara to toast up to.\n\n- Yes, and quite a giant one too! I mean she literally rode the thing! - Kara already forgot about Rein.","n":152},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Blue, - Kara smiled happily.\n\n- Indigo.\n\n- Seven.\n\n- Six.\n\n- Five, - Kara started thinking about next moves. It got intriguing.","n":153},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Kara looked back at Rein, a mistake, but a quite dear one. He was having fun. It was nice to see him smile from a distance. It created just enough space in between to make her almost irrelevant to the situation. Tallie growled in excitement as Brian raised his hands with excitement calling the men in the tavern to bet on some strength contest. Fezzik was looking a bit engaged in keeping track of the bids that Brian was collecting. Seemed like they learned quite a bit about each other during a card game.\n\nKara picked up two glasses and walked over to the contest table. It was quite a task to squeeze through the crowd. This beer seemed to be a bit stronger than Kara expected. Maybe she was just panicking in the crowd. Last time she was in one they were walking down the coliseum entrance. It could have been anything at that point.\n\n- Tallie, Fezzik, drinks have arrived, - Kara was putting the glasses on the table.\n\n- Oh no thanks, I already had my fill for today, - Fezzik smiled and waved in a lazy manner. He looked quite reasonable. Tallie on other hand growled excitedly and clinged the mugs and downed hers and so Kara drank a half of the second. It was only polite.","n":154},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Four, - Rein started thinking about his next move.\n\n- Three.\n\n- Two.\n\n- One, - Kara was excited for the next step.","n":155},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"It was nothing that Kara has ever seen. Grox muttered some words under his breath and started growing in muscles. Fezzik chuckled.\n\n- So this is how you want to play then? - he bowed down to Tallie’s ear and whispered something that seemed to upset her quite a bit. Kara has seen it happen before, it never meant anything good.\n\nAnd so Grox and Tallie clashed their hands together and planted their elbows on to the table with a thud.\n\n- On your marks, - Brian was counting down the fingers, - Go!","n":156},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Zero, - Rein added a step.\n\n- Negatives.\n\n- Positives.\n\n- Sun.\n\n- Moon.","n":157},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Tallie was caught off guard in the first round. Men cheered and Brian gave out the winnings.\n\n- Alright, another one and this time I will bet, - Fezzik placed down his bid on the table and Brian happily raised his arms announcing another round. Bids flew in again. Tallie was gleaming with excitement.\n\nAnd so Tallie went all out. It was a tough match, but mostly it was Grox trying to hang by the inch. Kara didn’t know that it was possible to be fighting this close to the table. Goblin just didn’t give up. Kara wondered if it was because he was a man Then it would make the odds even out a bit. Ego games.\n\nFezzik won his bet. Now he was looking for Rein. Kara nodded in the direction and Fezzik took his way there. Tallie cheered and bought a round for everyone in the bar with her winnings. It was only polite.","n":158},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Night.\n\n- Day.\n\n- School.\n\n- Home.","n":159},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Well, I’m going to call it a night, - Tallie downed her last drink and jumped off the chair. She threw Grox a weird look and Kara wondered what it meant. Seemed that Grox was as confused as she was. Tallie was already gone by the time Kara turned around. And so Kara returned to their table only to discover that Floats had also left the scene for the sweet embrace of the pillow.\n\nKara sat down and took a gulp out of the last mug still full on the table, however she immediately spat it out. Someone was using it as an ashtray. Multiple heads turned over and Kara saw a man with a cigarette in his hand. It didn’t take her long to gather up the courage.\n\n- Who in seven hells taught you manners, - she furiously rushed over to him, poking him with all her might in the chest. Maybe a bit too harshly, but it wasn’t like Kara knew anything about it in her drunken state.\n\n- I’m sorry, ok, really sorry, - man was taken by surprise as a tavern sank into silence.\n\n- You groundly better be, - Kara poked him two more times and the man retreated, apologizing quite heavily on his way out. She felt a bit bad for him. He did wear an eyepatch and they were quite a way away from the sea for him to be any sort of pirate. Maybe he was a visitor from Culo. Their people traveled quite a bit and quite freely to be anywhere they wanted.\n\n- Kara, you might have had enough, how about you go upstairs? - Fezzik was quick to appear from the crowd catching her by the arm.\n\n- Fine, but did you see how absolutely disgusting he was? - it was almost a miracle that Kara didn’t incinerate the poor man on the spot. A week ago he would probably be burned alive. That thought warmed her heart for some reason. Lucky man indeed he was.","n":160},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Bed.\n\n- Chair.\n\n- Cupboard.\n\n- Table.\n\n- Furniture.\n\n- Cutlery.\n\n- Kitchen.\n\n- Bathroom.","n":161},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Kara woke up to a knock on the door. It startled her and an attempt to turn towards it resulted in a surprisingly soft fall to the ground. She didn’t quite remember going upstairs and getting into the bed. Her head was pounding and the six steps she made to get to the door felt like a ride on a ship. Wavy and painful.\n\n- Who is there? - her voice was still quite sleepy and Kara could swear she could hear a couple of notes that she never took in a healthy state. She opened the door only to discover Tallie standing behind it with a wide grin.\n\n- My room has a giant bathtub, - raspy goblin voice seemed quite appropriate for the situation. Tallie gave Kara a big hug and lifted her up in the air. Girl never actually gave much thought to how strong the little goblin actually was until this moment. It felt quite unwise to resist, as Kara actually didn’t mind taking a ride to a bathtub.\n\n- Sure…","n":162},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Shower.\n\n- Bath.\n\n- Towel.\n\n- Curtains.\n\n- Theater.","n":163},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"Kara would never think of Tallie being a caring teammate, however all of her prejudice seemed to flow away as the goblin woman just carried her down the hallway into a giant room with an already hot wooden bath ready in one of the corners. Tallie helped her to undress with surprising confidence before helping her to climb into the bath without saying a word.\n\nEverything that was happening around stopped making sense right around this point. Kara sinked down in the water and Tallie took out a loofah from somewhere on the shelf beyond the view of her eyes. It was quite relaxing, but the entire experience mostly reminded Kara of a fever dream. An extremely bizarre and realistic one at that.\n\n- Tallie, you surprise me everyday…","n":164},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- We should build him some sort of a shelter. He can’t be out without a roof in the rain, he will get cold, - little Kara was looking for something useful in the backyard. There were always a lot of random scraps, so she was sorting through some metal sheets that were left over after their parents put up a fence, - These are too big, do you think we can bend them?\n\n- Kara, he’s a cat. They are designed to survive outside. He can find his own shelter, - Rein already has regretted a decision to adopt a kitten.\n\n- Yes, but I want him to stay closer to us so we can look after him, - Kara pulled on one of the sheets to get it out from under the pile of junk, - Take the other end.\n\n- He is a wild cat, you can’t force him to choose a house that you made, - Rein continued his argument, but joined the effort.\n\n- Well, I bet he will consider it if we make it really nice and cozy, - Kara tried to pull on the metal, but barely had any weight to budge it.\n\n- Here, - Rein placed a couple of bricks under the sheet of fence and reached out a hand to Kara, - It will bend if we jump.","n":165},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"It felt quite weird drying up clothing with not so explained magic, but whatever she did worked. Kara wondered if she just wasted some of her power potential to adapt to some mundane situation, but at this point of the day she didn’t care much. Her hair was already braided in a surprisingly tidy and comfortable Tallie style.\n\n- Thanks, I guess I needed that, - Kara clumsily thanked her, now presumably friend, goblin. It was an extreme way of becoming friends, however Kara was just happy with the progress. In a brief and wild debate in her head Kara even realized that Tallie was a quite nice company when she wasn’t trying to murder her teammates.\n\nThey headed downstairs to meet up with the rest of the team. Boys were already up for a while and had already finished brewing the supposed manticore repellent. The activity that certainly did not do well for their smell. Floats was fine.\n\n- You girls had fun, - Rein looked at the matching braids in pure judgment that gave Kara a weird satisfaction.\n\n- Jealous of our fresh braids? - Kara raised an eyebrow at a bunch of hay sticking out of Reins hair.\n\n- Well, some of us were responsible enough to wake up early and do the job, - logical check mate if they were actually competing for the title of the most useful team member, however Kara didn’t remember signing up for any of it. Unlike Rein. It still felt a pretty bit bad to make him do all the work.\n\n- Good job, - Kara didn’t know what else to say.\n\n- Thanks, - bitter, but still better than another sensible counterpoint. Rein knew better than trying to bicker with Kara after she agreed to a ceasefire.\n\n- So are we going to the fields now? - Tallie sounded excited for some action.\n\n- Yeah, we got directions from Ben earlier today, - Fezzik stood up from the table and grabbed some wrapped food, - We already packed your lunch.\n\n- Damn, is it lunch already? - Kara was quite surprised that her teammates let her sleep in so late. They were either super irresponsible or some really understanding friends. Kara preferred to believe in the latter. Maybe it wasn’t so bad having friends that could think for themselves.","n":166},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- So Kara, where do you live? You sure don’t smell right for downtown, - Lilith always was straight with her questions. It was still better than other kids that just came up with silly names and insults.\n\n- Why should that matter to anyone, - Kara continued reading a book. It wasn't a particularly interesting one, but the title was complicated enough to create a necessity to concentrate on the text.\n\n- Well, friends should know these things about each other, - Lilith wasn’t about to give up so easily.\n\n- Dirt shack, happy? - Kara probably sounded rude, but it was the answer that usually cut the deal.\n\n- I’m serious, you know you don’t have to play along with the bullies, - It was nice that Lilith tried to play friends, but Kara didn’t really need anyone discovering her extremely stupid and probably illegal hobby. She knew better than that. It wouldn’t end well for Lilith to know.\n\n- I’m not playing along and as long as they are happy with their games and keep me out of them I am perfectly fine with that, - Kara didn’t lie. She was perfectly fine with other kids doing their stupid kid things. None of them would actually try and pick a fight with her. First, she was a girl. Second, she was top in physical education class by quite a bit.\n\n- Don’t you get lonely? - Lilith pressed on.\n\n- Listen, I have friends. You don’t have to babysit me, - Kara decided to stop answering stupid questions. So she came up with a lie.","n":167},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- So you are saying that one leaf of this crop can feed an entire cow for a day? Isn’t it kind of ridiculous and implausible? - Kara didn’t quite understand how uncle Ben was able to achieve such progress. Although it would only make sense that Quattuor would rather invest into working out a better feeding program for the creatures that couldn’t comment on the quality of taste and satisfaction of their meals. If cow owners wanted to be humane they would just feed them the same vegetables they ate. It would probably also mean that the nutritional values would be greatly unbalanced in most of the cases. Nevertheless, uncle Ben was certainly a genius.\n\n- Yeah, I’m kind of excited to see it too, - Fezzik surprisingly shared Kara’s excitement.\n\n- Do you think it works the same for people? - Haderach joined the conversation out of the blue bringing some calm and experienced energy to the mix, - I heard these things make good cigars, but I never heard anyone eating it.\n\n- Well, I guess we can try and get a taste, - Kara smiled knowing all too well that she won’t be participating in that. Taste of tobacco wasn’t something that she felt particularly excited for anymore.","n":168},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- Office.\n\n- Papers.\n\n- Digitals.\n\n- Pixels.\n\n- Strokes.\n\n- Painting.\n\n- Photo.\n\n- Past.\n\n- Future.\n\n- Present. I win.","n":169},{"chapter":"Chit Chats","text":"- So who will play as a bait if the beast appears? - Rein gave Tallie a side eye, but Kara returned him an eloquent look of disapproval.\n\n- I guess whoever is the closest to the cauldron when it happens, - Kara smiled and it seemed to have settled the argument. No one really wanted to volunteer. Kara was surprised that guys convinced Floats to carry it. He never complained.\n\nIt was obvious that something was wrong when the group reached the field. Mainly because someone was already there talking in hushed voices. Septum heroes slowed down and Floats carefully put down the cauldron to be ready for an attack. It didn’t sound like goblins though. Well one of the voices did, but by that time it was quite clear what was happening.\n\n- Hey there, what’s going on? - Fezzik seemed to be relieved to see new friends, but his face changed quite a bit when he saw a loaded cart. It looked like someone was doing some unsanctioned harvesting, - Care to explain what's going on?\n\n- Hey, sweetheart, nothing much, just packing some crops for Ben, - Cindall sounded as confident as ever. Kara almost believed her.\n\n- Yeah, then do you mind waiting for him just a bit to make sure he is aware? I remember that he was planning the harvest for the next week, - Fezziks face grew angrier by the minute. Kara just walked over to the cart to check out the miraculous crop everyone was talking about. Heroes could have just been stupid and mixed up the dates. In any ways it wasn’t her concern. She hopped on the cart to inspect the harvest. The leaves were a surprising amber of veins spreading on the lavish dark green. It looked like kale.\n\n- Hey, hey, hey, listen, we are good friends right? Just let us go and we will never meet again, - Cindall dropped the act suddenly speaking in a surprised tone, - We both know that this tournament is bulls crap. We just want to sell this and escape to the uncharted seas, - She made a brief pause and Kara could swear she heard a flick of a lighter, - Listen, honey, we don’t have to fight over this, you just have to close your eyes and say that manticore burned it all up. We have already set everything up for it.\n\n- But this crop is already scheduled to be shipped off to Quintus, why would you want to steal from your own state? - Fezzik was having none of it, - There are people that rely on this shipment.\n\n- Didn’t you preserve any sort of decency? Do you even know what happens when there is a break in the delivery chain? - Rein sounded quite annoyed. Kara didn’t quite see the problem as the experimental crop was only being introduced and it would have been reckless to shut all other lines trusting in unrealistic claims, - How about you leave this cart here and we forget about this conversation.\n\n- There is no reason to fight over this, - Cindall suddenly realized the gravity of the situation at hand, - Well it was worth a try to reason with you guys, you seemed like a smart bunch.\n\nKara looked up and instantly grew tense. She looked away for the moment and that was about enough for Septum heroes to jump to action. It was quite a sight: Tallie was growing in size, visibly enraged; Rein was holding a rapier at the neck of Cindall, Kara didn’t know why he didn’t use his dagger; Fezzik was holding up his magic wand, well, it was his screwdriver. Kara instantly picked up a pitch fork from the cart and raised it ready for anything stupid that was to follow.\n\n- Rein, calm down, there is no need to kill anybody, - Kara knew he wouldn’t listen. And it seemed Quintus' heroes made up their mind already.","n":170},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"It is tough to live without stepping on some tails, leave alone succeed. The difference between friends and business partners is that at the end of the day you both try to work to benefit each other rather than just yourself. Afterall there are always alternatives in the market if you know where to look. It’s much easier to come to an established cratch than to build and fill your own.","n":171},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"It was revolutionary. People started to eat cats. That solved the problem with Tomson, he must have fled as soon as he noticed the change. Like a rat from the ship. Kara wished that Fluffers would be as smart, but everybody knew he wasn’t a stray. He would never let anybody, but Kara and Rein, anywhere close to him. Huggins wouldn’t even let their parents come too close.\n\nKara didn’t know what to think. She heard about these things before, but she thought that these kinds of things were tales from the olden times and far away places. Kara never thought that it would actually hit the city recommended list. It was officially allowed to eat stray cats.  Something about efficient population control.\n\nEverybody knew he wasn’t a stray.","n":172},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Kara never felt like this before. Heroes could kill each other in training, either that or Tarik was somewhere around to stop it. Why didn’t he appear yet? Did they not see what was about to happen?\n\n- No one move! - It was worth having one last chance for negotiations. Jeff just walked over to and threw a haystack on the cart. He didn’t seem to mind the situation at all. He was in quite a hurry. Kara just couldn’t bring herself to throw a sharp object at him, it just didn’t feel right.\n\n- Hey you, do you hear us? - Rein didn’t like that one bit, - Don’t you dare to put any more stacks into this cart!\n\nKara caught a slight movement from the side. Zilli was preparing to take an aim at Rein. Kara remembered throwing a pitch fork at Zilli before something blacked out her vision. It felt like a hit on the head.","n":173},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"This land wasn’t the greatest land for raising potatoes. It was dry and crispy and barely could hold any more moisture. Kara wasn’t even sure that she should risk trying to plant her precious pair of potatoes at this time of a year. She couldn’t believe she only had two of them left. It wasn’t worth the victory. Kara didn’t remember the last time she even spoke to them. The tournament seemed to be a ripped veil of memories. Ripped quite to shreds. Kara only remembered maybe five bullet points out of the entire experience. She didn’t even have time to remember the name of her last teammate.","n":174},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Kara was absolutely terrified when she saw that she had missed the target. Zilli has already taken a shot and Cindall got out of grapple without as much as a scratch. Rein had a cough fit, Kara knew that sound. An arrow in his side didn’t help it either. Zilli took two more shoots. Kara couldn't imagine in what world it was acceptable to just shoot three arrows at anybody. Quintus' heroes were not playing around and Tarik was nowhere to be seen.\n\n- You touch her one more time and I end you, - Zilli was being quite confident in her statements.\n\nFloats rushed to Rein to try and stop the unnecessary violence, but there was no stopping after shots had been fired. Kara slapped her own face to hide how disappointed she was. Septum heroes at their prime. No one knew what was going on.\n\nBy the time Kara opened her view to whatever was happening in front of her the shots had been fired and Tallie was already swinging her giant hammer at Zilli. Haderach looked absolutely unnerving in his monstrous form getting out of his hiding spot and already smoking with readied fire.\n\n- Hey, Tallie, Floats, maybe you can keep your friends down? - Grox spoke with surprising confidence, - We are good friends right?\n\nKara didn’t know what he was trying to achieve. It was hard to control this goblin as it was, leave alone straight reasoning. It still felt weird for some reason. Maybe Tallie would prefer to side with her kin if they were open to friendship. Hero world was still quite new to her.\n\nRein was rushing to take off the wheels of the cart as Quintus' heroes rushed to load, giving absolutely no mind to Kara standing in the back. It was quite unnerving that they dared to disrespect her presence in such a way.\n\n- Burn them up, - Kara commanded Fluffer Huggins to emerge and the world got engulfed in flames.","n":175},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"- You know there was a point where I thought we were friends, - Kara smiled ever so slightly. It was a great joke. Flaming tom was standing over her head, to block out the sunlight. Motionless, Kara could have made him a giant square, but she didn’t. She was a strong believer in his undeniable charm around the people. She couldn’t take that away from him. It was really all he had left of him. People remembered him with Kara and somehow this has made her life somewhat lighter. She didn’t mind talking about Fluffer Huggins if that meant that more controversial questions stayed in the back of the queue.","n":176},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"- Kara, you idiot, you are going to burn the crops! - Rein shot something as a follow up and the cart exploded with ice putting out the fire. The remaining sight didn’t look pretty. Jeff and Preet, the sixth Quintus hero, layed quite charred and frozen in the cart and Cindall was hastily hitting the reins to start making the escape. Grox was trying to help resuscitate Jeff and Zilli angrily roared in frontal attack towards Rein.\n\n- Hey, - Brian's voice suddenly sounded in Kara's head. It didn’t feel natural at all, - Maybe you want to help us escape safely?\n\nThe voice sounded quite clear in all this mess.\n\nIt only made sense, poor heroes were just trying to escape the wicked government games and Fezzik and Rein just stood in their way because they were protecting it. If they already have decided to stay in the games why Kara should care if she can rebel and end their unrealistic conformist ways. She could still choose to run.\n\nKara shook her head. It felt like following a stupidest train of thought. Rein had a sister he has to take care of, Kara wasn’t about to chase a stupid bait to freedom just to screw him up. Quintus' heroes were playing quite dirty, though Kara had no idea how or what they did.\n\nThe air was getting heated as the sound of screeching missiles were hitting the front of the cart. Kara barely noticed two arrows shooting through the air dissipating Fluffer Huggins into floating ashes. Tallie was for some reason mad at Rein again.","n":177},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Toham stood on a pile of debris. It was never a pretty sight any time she visited towns. They would never send her in anywhere where there was a chance for negotiations. She just needed to stand her ground and let the people see her while they scrambled whatever was left to salvage. It was obvious they were at war, otherwise why would they need surviving witnesses. Kara was just sent there in hopes that an angry mob would find the courage to attack. Then everyone would see Toham defend what she stood on.","n":178},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Kara couldn’t concentrate on anything in particular. She just tried to shove the thoughts to the back of her mind, but this was exactly what Tarik was trying to avoid. There was no clear way of controlling fire. It couldn’t stop people, change their minds or stay contained. It could kill the slow ones. Gruesome and animalistic approach. Kara never wanted it; she had no idea how to work around these limitations. Out of place, out of qualifications. Kara was just lucky she had a slight will to survive for three potatoes in her parcel.\n\n- Stand down, - Cindall angrily threw the now useless reins and readied a shot into Rein. It seemed that everyone chose to focus on him and he somehow was still standing. It didn’t look like Quintus was trying to follow suit in the scale of damage. Even Tallie was trying to help Floats stop Rein. Everyone else was just terrified of whatever Haderach turned into, so nobody looked that way. Kara would not believe her eyes if this wasn’t the general flow of events for Septum heroes. Too busy fighting themselves to do anything right. By now Kara settled on just adding up destruction hoping it would achieve something counted as progress.\n\nGood timing on that too.\n\nThe wind suddenly brought new roars coming from the sky with flaps of the wings.","n":179},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"When Kara finally had a chance to settle she went all out. She wasn’t about to cheapen out on anything. She requested to seclude an entire forest around her gorge and built a fence to prevent human souls from trespassing. No one was using that space anyway and she now had the right to claim it. There she could finally settle and stay out of whatever games other states' heroes were trying to play with each other. They got their show from her. It seemed like a fair exchange for a little bit of freedom.","n":180},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"These flying things weren’t just your regular manticores. Yes, general traits looked about right, but things had goat and snake heads sticking to the side of lion's mane. Kara had no idea what difference it made as a pair of these creatures wreaked havoc on the plantation breathing fire left and right. It just added weird goat bleats to the general stupidity of the situation.\n\nQuintus' heroes looked thoroughly terrified and seemed to switch their attention toward the beasts. Arrows started flying in a single direction. Kara had lost track of any logic. She thought if anything Quintus' heroes would be trying to preserve the escaped creature, however they were trying to steal something from Quintus. Maybe this new chimera breed could smell out rats and follow their tracks. Why else would they need the goat head if not to be detecting certain things. It was obvious what the snake head was used for.\n\nKara jumped off the cart, out of two, well three if you count her own team, threats in the field of view the chimeras looked like the most dangerous one. Attention shifted and Quintus made it quite sure to make the best out of the interruption. Clearing the way for the cart and getting their teammates back on their feet. It was hard to decide whether Kara was happy or not about the fact that Jeff survived the ice and fire. Mostly because he instantly shape shifted into a horse trying to set up an escape of his teammates. Maybe it was for the better, Kara had chimera to kill and teammates to protect. She didn’t really care for much else until she heard a distinct series of thuds as Floats for some reason knocked out Fezzik seemingly unprovoked.\n\n- I will murder that goblin, - Kara tried to gather up some courage. Chimeras were a bit more than anything that she fought before. It would be nice to have a short term goal in mind to motivate survival and fuel the anger. Fluffer Huggins appeared once more and Kara felt a solid strain in her connection to him. It seemed he still didn’t fully recover or maybe he was also scared of fighting the chimera. Somehow that was much more terrifying than just a manticore.\n\nFlaming tom exploded in Chimeras face and tore at it with his fiery claw as he exploded once more to jump away from the beast. He seemed to be growling quite bravely. Kara tried believing that Fluffers could take a cake of chimera on his own. She really wanted to believe that, but it was hard to pilot fire and concentrate on holding the form together. It seemed that the moment anything touched him Kara was too scared to keep him around. She could see where the arrows hit him last time. He didn’t mind those himself it seemed.\n\nChimera screeched, reared back and fired away. Kara watched in confusion as fire blew through the flaming fur as a gust of wind. It made no sense, why would the creature try to burn him. The lion head seemed to have snapped at the snake to stop the stupidity. Tallie charged in and with a powerful swing pushing the chimera back.\n\nKara turned back to Fluffer Huggins just in time to disapparate him before the second chimera snapped his teeth around him. Somehow the goat bleating sounded much more sinister now. The fields behind it were starting to spread fire into the sky clouding up the sun. For a second Kara wondered if Tallie would attack her if given the opportunity, but it felt horrible letting goblin fight two of these things alone. She suddenly felt worried about her green friend, afterall it wasn’t like Kara really knew who Tallie really was. She didn’t have a reason to wish for her death.\n\nKara was happy to finally switch to something less morally straining than killing heroes. Maybe if she was smarter she would find a way to smear the cart with a repellent, but why would she hope that Quitus heroes told them to make something that attracts things instead of repelling? If she was smarter she would probably figure out what it actually did a long time ago and had way less questions right now. Maybe she could have prevented the entire misunderstanding. This could have been so much simpler without manticores. Quintus heroes would escape and Septum heroes would have been beaten. Nothing would have changed, not in the world, not in their lives. Now they have to risk being mauled to death in case of failure. And in the midst of all that, Kara didn’t know if she was supposed to stop Quintus heroes at all costs or just let them go given that they would probably leave Septum heroes to die. Without a cart they all had to fight. With a cart they would flee and Kara wasn’t even sure if Fezzik was conscious. Someone had to stop chimeras, if Rein was smart he would have just asked for a ceasefire in order to defend against manticores. But it was all part of their plan all along, chimeras were about to burn everything here to begin with.\n\nMaybe it was good that Kara had to be the one swinging the ax at an obvious threat and leave the rest of the thinking to the others. She would, of course, prefer them helping her and Tallie, but only Cindall and Zelli were busy firing away at these creatures. Boys seemed to be more interested in talking things out or whatever they were doing.\n\nKara saw Tallie hit and swung true from the other side. She felt her blood rushing through her body as the ax touched the back of the beast. It didn’t feel right, but she couldn’t really choose. She would do the same to a wolf that dared to bite at her. Hungry wolves don't fight fair either. Kara did smell the burnt field in the background, it made the situation even more ridiculous. If she and wolves were to ever fight they sure would much prefer running from the fire not fighting her. Snake head went for a bite, but Kara dodged out with a tail. It was quite corporeal this time, she could clearly feel and swing it around.\n\n- Zelli, I’ll give you ten dollars if you help me get him off of Jeff, - Preet seemed to sound quite lively. Kara would be happy for him if he had his priorities straight. Zilli seemed to be quite easily swayed.\n\nIt actually didn’t take too much effort to put down the first chimera. Between Tallie and Kara basically overwhelmed the beast with heavy blows in such a unison that Kara wondered if that was how Floats felt sending Fezzik on a date with the ground. It happened so fast that Kara barely had time to breathe before her ax delivered a sudden killing blow. It was quite uncanny how still the creature got in a matter of a second.\n\n- Phew, well that’s one, - Kara threw a brief look at Tallie as both of them stood over the, suddenly still, giant feline shape. Tailed goblin looked like she was too busy with a second beast at her flank.\n\nA loud thundering clap clasped the attention as the now moving cart was hit by some force wave. Fezzik probably finally came to his senses and wasn’t about to let Quintus' heroes escape. Kara wondered if he even knew that they were currently getting attacked by manticore based chimeras. Because if he didn’t he might have been surprised by what was coming next. Kara could only watch as a chimera let out a heavy roar and bright fire covered the cart. Tallie instantly ran towards it. Kara took a second to see if anyone really needed help. She couldn’t see Fezzik or Rein anywhere so she was beginning to worry that they might have been around the cart. She ran around the fire trying to make out anything as the chimera started digging through the crops looking for something in the cargo. At its feet layed the better half of Quintus heroes, quite severely charred once more. Tallie was making a beeline towards a tree line. Kara decided to stop this idiocy and fulfill her previous promise. Grox had to stop whatever magic he used to turn Tallie and Floats against their own team. Tallie could actually kill them.\n\nKara swinged right next to the goblin that was helping Zilli up to get his attention, - Take down your stupid spell, she’s going to kill them!\n\nZilli didn’t like that and shot Kara in the shoulder, just barely scratching it, and jumped on her raccoon before booking it out of the view. Grox wanted to do the same, but Kara swung again in front of his nose, preventing him from going too far. He fell down saying something that he can’t really end the spell. Kara didn’t remember the exact words as Grox collapsed from a blast of energy shooting him in the chest. She could almost feel the hit herself.\n\n- Don’t waste your time next time, Kara, - Haderach clapped Kara on her back and moved on to the same direction as Tallie. Floats seemed to be in his senses and finally battling it out with chimera, so Kara ran over to help. A moment later Tallie rushed over from the treeline and planted her hammer in the skull of the chimera. There was something in its jaws. There were eggshells.","n":181},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Toham didn’t really regret many mistakes in her life. It wasn’t the fact that she didn’t trust Quintus' heroes. It was just that it always seemed to end up in a whole ton of mess every time there was anything to do with them.\n\n- Just let them be, Cassius, - she walked past him wiping her mouth from blood. It wasn’t worth it to fight. It would solve nothing.\n\n- Wasn’t planning to interrupt, really, - she hated how confident he was in these situations.\n\n- Now, why would you? - Kara threw the dark orange charm over her shoulder to Victorian, - Next time Eve loses it I’ll take her head off first. This isn’t a car key.","n":182},{"chapter":"Lack of Communication","text":"Three of Quintus' heroes were dead. There was nothing anyone could do. Septum heroes themselves looked like they could have seen better times. Kara was surprisingly fine, if you don’t count a scratch from Zilli’s arrow. If you would ask her she would probably respond with a solid she did what she could, but she sure didn’t look like it. Who knows how many would be dead for sure if Tallie didn’t come out of the spell and didn’t finish chimera of before it could flee to hatch out three more of it’s kind to terrorize these lands. Septum heroes did count up the shells and wondered why would Quintus heroes hide the eggs in their cart.\n\nThey also put out the fire spreading across the fields. An incoming rain helped with that quite a bit. Kara couldn’t even look in the direction of corpses, she just sort of blocked them out everytime looking for something else to focus on. Rein and Haderach took charge of dealing with the bodies. Maybe she should have spilled the repellent on the cart, maybe then chimeras wouldn’t attack as fiercely. She knew it was a lie, those manticores knew exactly what they came for. It was a breeding pair.\n\n- Hey, want to taste this? - Tallie stretched out a piece of chimera meat to Kara. Something about eating the kill to honor its death. Kara didn’t have the will capacity left to refuse. She absentmindedly tried swallowing rancid raw meat, but it wasn’t easy at all.\n\n- Sorry, Tallie, my stomach is a bit too weak for these traditions.","n":183},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"- Man, I’m really sorry, - Floats wasn’t being himself after everything was over. Regular sweet voice has dropped in pitch and felt surprisingly quite sincere that way - I don’t know what came over me.\n\n- Yeah, man, don’t worry about it, - Fezzik was inspecting one of his broken mechanical toys, - Dam, I hope I can fix this.\n\nKara sat by a rock without a single clue on what to do next. The outcome seemed like a complete disaster and they barely did anything to deal with gremlins that Ben was complaining about. Now who knows what kind of trial they were about to face. Logically thinking Kara figured that it could have been better to leave Quintus with less time to train new heroes, but was it really worth three lives to achieve? Kara didn’t kill them, but she still felt like somehow it was her fault. She could have let Grox go, but he refused to let go of the spell. Refused or couldn’t. If Kara knew the straight answer to this maybe she would know how to feel.\n\nIt didn’t take long for Ben to come rushing towards the smoking fields. He was absolutely devastated and Kara could almost understand his pain. Years of work burned in flames with not much to salvage, but more than enough to instill hope. Mainly because he wasn’t about to go to prison for it and go through the entire tournament before getting any chance to start over. His endeavor was supported by interested friends in Quintus. Friends that almost got backstabbed by their own heroes. Or maybe that was their plan to rip off the poor farmer all along. It’s hard to figure out who was behind who when you have to flat out solve the problem.\n\n- They did what? - Ben was so shocked he wasn’t about to believe Septum heroes either. Man was probably out of his mind from stress. Why would they want to steal his crop or lie about two chimeras and two clearly burned corpses? And the mess that was left of the horses. And a goblin. Kara had no idea now to explain why he had to die. She hoped that Haderach could explain that for her, but halfling was nowhere to be seen.\n\n- Listen, Quintus' heroes were just trying to steal this to move it through the black market or something, - Fezzik was already smoking a cigarette in a nervous fit, - Did you know that your crop is a superb tobacco?\n\n- Sorry, Ben, Fezzik got hit in the head quite hard, - Kara was just tired.\n\n- Why are you smoking my crop?! This is ridiculous! - Ben cried in desperation, - I will report you to the capitol and you will pay for your vandalism!\n\nIt was kind of uncanny. As if on the que, the lightning struck in the distance and the sound of the thunder blended in the heavy humming of the engine flying towards the fields. Through the mud out of the forest came guards instantly pointing guns at everyone in the clearing.\n\n- We were sent to pick up Septum heroes for interrogation on the matter of federal offense! - That didn’t sound right. They were not the ones trying to escape and if they could see everything at all times why wouldn’t they have interrupted earlier? They were more than capable of instant travel to any location of interest. Maybe they meant to resurrect these heroes a bit later for added dramatic effect.","n":184},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"Maybe it was her being stubborn. Maybe she stopped caring a long time ago and just propelled forward because it was something that she knew would be her safest place. In the rotation of general chaos under which the world seemed to work, doing anything at all seemed like something productive. Something to keep yourself visibly occupied so that the order built up around you is strong enough to create the perfect illusion of it.\n\nShe didn’t need a potato garden of that size. No one would ever need that many potatoes that no one was allowed to eat. She didn’t pluck them out either, carefully multiplying them and guarding them against herbivore predators or disease. She thought it was only fair to let them live out their two years and die as their cycle intended. No interruptions to the fragile order that was balancing on the pin needle of Kara’s existence.","n":185},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"Everything was happening quite quickly. Heroes were rounded up, mostly with no resistance there. It got harder when they started asking where Haderach was. Fezzik said maybe two words before they started pummeling him to the ground. Kara didn’t even have time to respond as bright light closed up her view. It weirdly felt like Fluffer Huggins when he moved her through the mansion backyard fence. Kara was too startled to resist.\n\n- What was that? - she looked around only to find her, Floats, Rein and a random chubby man in a small windowless room. She couldn’t find a door either.\n\n- Transporting beam, - Man sounded beyond reasonable, - Seems like your friends like causing trouble.\n\n- Hey, we did not do anything wrong, Quintus brought manticores on their own heads, - Rein spoke up. Kara was starting to get worried about Tallie and Fezzik, - If they didn’t try to run away and steal they would have been absolutely fine.\n\nElectric sound behind revealed Tallie and Fezzik lying down. Kara rushed to help them up.\n\n- Do you seriously have to do this? - it wasn’t anything that hadn't happened before, but Kara was seriously getting tired of things happening without any precautions or explanations. It wasn’t nice to hit heroes just because they were highly unlikely to die from simple punches.\n\n- Where is Haderach? - Rein was getting more tense.\n\n- I am not here to answer your questions, - man stood stern in his place, - I’m here to ask about the incident by the lake side. What do you know?\n\n- We just woke up and they were already dead. We only stopped because Gart was polite enough to offer to join camps for safety, - Rein didn’t seem comfortable at all during his answer, - You know with all the rogue goblins running around.\n\nChubby man really didn’t like that answer, so he turned to Kara, - And what did you see?\n\n- You mean that old hag in the forest wasn’t a nightmare? - she felt a jolt of pain that was too familiar to forget, - Hey, calm down, I have zero clue who Gart was. Didn’t really have the pleasure of meeting him. Tallie just said he was a great and honorable man, - Kara had no idea what compelled her to say everything she knew.\n\nMan sighed with a tired look and looked up to Floats, - and you?\n\n- I just slept through the night. Didn’t even hear it happening, - Floats responded nonchalantly, as always. It was really hard to believe that there was much going on in his head. He just somehow always ended up on top of things. Must have been nice.","n":186},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"There always seemed to be a subliminal pattern to all things happening around. Like bubbles in a simmering pot of soup or in a kettle. No matter how heavy the entropy moved the things around the bubbles always floated to the top, no matter where in the pot they had formed. There was always an explanation that just worked itself out once passed through the masses. People just accepted them as they accepted bubbles floating to the top.\n\nAll potatoes were now poisonous and no one could eat them. It was a pay back from Quattuor. They refused to provide fuel to support the popularity of the Potato Show. The only potatoes left in the entire nine states were now growing in one giant garden in Septum. They could have been poisonous too. She could make them poisonous too.","n":187},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"- Well, I can’t get rid of you now. After your stunt with manticores you officially entered the bidding war, so I might as well let you take over this problem for me, - Chubby man must have thought that he could control Septum. For some reason Kara wanted to call him Darius. Mostly because he seemed to give no care in the world about the death that was happening all around his little endeavor.\n\n- And why should we do as you say? Last time I checked we only answered to Septum, - Rein didn’t look too happy, but at that point it really could have been anything.\n\n- Well, mostly because you survived. Call it being haunted, - Darius smiled and disappeared in the net of light. Kara hated it when they did that.\n\nSomething opened behind them and they got access to a neat lounge with food and various simple beverages.\n\n- Anyone seen Haderach? - Kara was worried, but no one answered. It was like asking a wall, even Rein seemed to have accepted the absence of a teammate. She wondered how many times has it happened before for everybody to be this calm. All she could do is to follow suit. Guards around sure weren't paying much attention to these questions. Not like they would ever answer them, it wasn’t their job.","n":188},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"- I said no, - Toham closed the book and threw it on the table, - This is the most absurd plan I ever saw and you know that I worked with Valentines, - she walked out of the room, closing the door behind her. Kara knew that it was inevitable, but the longer they waited, the more obvious it was. She wanted to see how far people would want to rock the boat until the entire system imploded on itself.\n\n- Kara, it's just a show, - Tarik opened the door and was now shouting at a turned back.\n\n- We both know what it is, Ember. Just do it yourself, - Kara waved a hand, - I never signed up for this and you had plenty of time and opportunities to switch me out.\n\n- Kara, - Tarik wanted to continue, - You know I didn’t have to ask nicely.\n\n- And you didn’t, - Toham disappeared in dark flames.","n":189},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"It was a long ride. In the 8 hours that the heroes spent in the lounge of the plane, Kara had quite a bit of time to look out of the window. She watched as the land got covered in water and then so was the horizon. Then there were clouds. Endless and deserted sky cities made of clouds. She never saw them this close and this static.\n\nThen the darkness of the night. Kara might have dozed off.\n\nThere was an announcement thirty minutes before the landing. Something about inability to come any closer to the mountain range due to the weather conditions. There wasn’t a cloud in the sky. They landed at the little forest guard post and were asked to wait for some equipment delivery.\n\n- Who do you think it’s going to be? - Rein looked tired and slightly disappointed.\n\n- What do you mean, what did they do to Haderach? - Kara tried to clear the air, but to no avail. Even Floats didn’t want to answer.\n\n- I don’t know. I just hope they won’t be a problem, - Fezzik nervously shrugged. Kara felt like her mind was chaotically shoving the snow of thoughts. It was more of a physical activity of imagining problems reflected in the little fractals of snowflakes, too fractured to make sense, and throwing them behind your back.\n\nShe already missed him. Maybe she shouldn’t remember the name. She knew he disappeared. Maybe they killed him because he killed Grox. There really was not much else. Maybe there was nothing more.\n\nGuards came down the stairs dragging a small figure, visibly against its will. It looked like a goblin, but Kara didn’t get a proper look as he rashly pulled his disturbingly realistic fish head. Somehow now she just knew that she was about to put her life in trust of that thing. Whatever this character could have been, Kara knew that this one will for sure be hard to forget. The sheer absurdity. He could barely see out of the thing.\n\n- So did they tell you what happened to Haderach? And who is this? - Rein looked absolutely baffled at their prospects.\n\n- Something about high treason and conspiracy against the government, - Guards shrugged. Kara wondered how their regimen for today looked like. Today if heroes asked they would have one answer, - This is your new teammate.\n\nIt only made sense.","n":190},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"Kara sat at the overhang. She made sure no one would come anywhere close to it. Just like Quintus was once claiming the burned up fields of Quattour by eliminating local farms, Kara was threatening Novem tourists to keep away from this place by spreading haunting stories of wild and rare human-eating tigers. Except Kara saw these manticores with her own eyes. Novem tourists just avoided the place like one would avoid climbing Everest. Those brave enough took on the challenge to seek the infamous potato garden. Some came back alive with terrific stories of the absence of the garden, but most still lay on the forest floor to be occasionally discovered by fellow garden seekers.\n\nNovem wasn’t happy with Toham for this frivolous act of conquest, but the situation seemed stupid enough for them to close their eyes. No one really needed or cared about this land before the show anyway. No one really knew where the border was anyway. Well Toham knew for sure and Novem just disputed it silently. If she called it home and took good care of it she had every right to protect it. It wasn’t like she was the one taking their cities. They had bigger problems to worry about.","n":191},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"- Carpe Diem, - the fish spoke with bravery and cowardly posed for the presentation. Walking on two feet seemed to be out of the ordinary for this fish out of water. And judging by a voice this was definitely a goblin. Quite sophisticated, but a goblin still, - Down the river, fish swims bitter.\n\n- Wow, - Kara was caught off guard.\n\n- Was that a rhyme? - Rein got snapped out of whatever he was thinking.\n\n- Progress is a process, - Carp spoke with a weird confidence.\n\n- Nice, - Fezzik was surprisingly satisfied.\n\n- We might consider moving quicker, - Carp crouched down and started running ahead.\n\n- Well, good luck! - The guards laughed to themselves and returned onto the ship leaving behind some familiar bags. Kara had just remembered what had happened to two horses. They never took them out of their tavern stalls.\n\nFloats picked up the bags and looked through them, - Well would you look at that! - He took a little bright green pouch with some glittering celtic insignia on it, - They found my beans!\n\nKara thought she might have misheard something, but no. He indeed just found a pouch with beans. She even came over to take a look. There were seven of them.\n\nThey moved out as soon as the bags were picked. It was nice to be walking in the familiar terrain again, but this time Rein and Fezzik took the lead. They knew the area and didn’t need any explanation of what was going on. They worked in the mine ten miles away and sometimes they would be called over for the shifts. They said that it was one of the much deeper and bigger ones. It had the whole village for miners to stay over at night, a bad omen for any worker. Late shifts and ruthless chiefs. They didn’t kill people, they just had ridiculous deadlines.\n\nIf there was a murderous creature haunting these mines right now, people in mainland might actually think that there was a violation of a workspace ethics. It was already hard to fight for the market.\n\nOr so Fezzik narrowed down the problem for Kara. Things like this happened all the time with specialized workers, it was even worse if you didn’t get anything but charred lungs out of it. Sometimes they wouldn’t approve of the transfer just because they didn’t want people to see it. They were raised in a family, raised to believe that they did it so that their children would not have to and yet sometimes these radical younglings would swing by to throw a cup or sabotage the line just to send a message. Cup could have been holding nails and everyone knows what a broken chain can do in a mineshaft.\n\nBut those were little human mistakes. It was haunting what a murderous hag could do if given an opportunity. Suddenly everything about the world became quite real. People didn’t just die or disappear. And now it was happening all around Septum heroes. No one has really seen heroes, maybe just in a glimpse.","n":192},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"- So what now? - The situation was quite dire, they couldn’t hold an answer for much longer. Kara banged her head at the table. She really didn’t want to do what she was about to start building. It would have been nice if she didn’t have to sacrifice this much.\n\n- We can’t really say no now, - Cassius was sitting across the table.\n\n- That’s exactly what you said two months ago, - Kara felt where the thorn has been growing all this time. There was still an option to say no to all this, but it would mean giving up on the garden and accepting death. Or they could do the same thing they did when they burned the garden the first time. Benefit of getting older is that you learn more tricks to keep your values. The downside is that you start losing track of the net cost.\n\n- No, two months ago I told you to stop crossing the border to grow potatoes in Novem, - Cassius was furious.\n\n- Potato, potatoe.","n":193},{"chapter":"Built reputation","text":"Kara was slowly building up a small panic attack. They were about to go into the second conflict in two days and they barely had enough time to sleep. They couldn’t wait any longer. Haderach released the hag and now they had to fix a very real problem. It still didn’t explain anything. Especially the origin of their fish goblin by the name of Carpe Diem, who somehow knew only how to communicate rhyme. Someone really must have been trying to put on a show.\n\nIt made sense that they would want to separate Haderach from the heroes, but why didn’t they make any sort of background check? It probably was one of the flaws of Septum traditional hero picking. Criminal pool of candidates were meant to have real life experience of the judicial system. Quite possibly wronged by a flaw in the system and would have enough will to fight for the chance to prove themselves right. Amnesty is just a word, but sometimes it hides just enough to make life feel normal again.\n\n- So anyone wants to tell me what’s the deal with Haderach? - Kara finally broke the ice on the elephant in the room, - What exactly happened at the camp?\n\n- Well, we kind of suspected, - Fezzik took out the cigarette, but Carp suddenly appeared from the bush crawling on four feet interrupting the conversation.\n\n- I am the speed, what is our read? - Carp clearly had some kind of train of sensible thought in his head. Kara just had to figure it out.\n\n- We are going to the village in that direction, Carp, - Rein pointed in some direction. He looked up at Barrow that was circling in the distance and his look changed. He was appalled, - Well, doesn’t look like these creatures are too friendly.\n\nHe looked down at Fezzik with a hopeless expression. Fezzik just shook his head in slight disbelief, - One would figure.\n\n- If they are discreet, I will not tweet, - Carp gave a thumbs up and hastily crawled away.\n\n- You already understand him, - Kara smiled at Rein with sligh pride.\n\n- Yes, Kara. Carp isn’t that hard to understand. You just need to actually listen and think about what he means, - it was nice to hear Rein play and know it all again. It gave Kara quite a bit of comfort. She wondered if Rein felt the same or was just annoyed. It probably was bad timing for it too.\n\nKara saw the fence around the village. It was probably just barely protecting from wolves. Kara could see the creatures slimming around the houses. Humanoids. Carp ran right towards them and must have said something genius in rhyme. The slimy bipeds started heading towards him, but they stopped as they could hear Carp more clearly. Kara wished she heard these words too. It looked quite convincing from a distance. Fish goblin quickly finished chatting and returned to the team.\n\n- They want to retreat, some help would be neat, - It was as clear as day. They were the transformed miners and they needed help to return to their normal forms. Kara was quite proud of figuring this one out.\n\n- Do we know how to undo the curses? - Kara looked at Fezzik and he just shrugged. Wouldn’t hurt to try. A lot of the powers got to be established that way and there was no reason to doubt anything until they actually tried. Seems like a good motto if you have nine lives.","n":194},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"It was probably weird to make the first contact with native people after declaring colonization. History showed that people generally didn’t care for those who didn’t share their culture and had weaker technology. These people simply had less say in things that concerned ghostly papers and the agreements made somewhere behind the man with a gun. Luckily killing people was still a moral choice of a man. He could always choose to die with a spear in a chest or admit cowardice and desert the position. He could also sit down on a train and exterminate all buffaloes with a machine gun so that natives have nothing to eat and therefore no powers to fight.\n\nThat wasn’t really the problem Kara faced when she looked over the illness that covered the slimy man shapes. They didn’t look sick, but they looked like they were in a world of pain. At least they sounded like it.\n\n- We want to be free, - miner with a dark green skin, if you could call it that, spoke tensely after gulping the air mostly to make a noise rather than breathe, - It keeps the stone intact, they don’t let us back in.\n\nIt was haunting. It seemed like the man was counting every word he said. Kara shivered every time he took a breath to speak. She tried coming closer and helping him, but what helped her seemed to burn the man’s skin like fire. He paid no attention to that. Burns washed away as soon as Kara jolted her arm back.\n\n- Magic can’t fix the prisoner unless he is free to be fixed, - the man seemed to be too calm for a creature that just survived third degree burns and healed them instantly, - She protects the rock that keeps the gates open.\n\n- Ok, bud, work with me here, - Fezzic was visibly disturbed by the situation.\n\n- No, don’t tell me we will have to go into the mine, - Kara was terrified of the idea of being somewhere deep in the ground. For some reason she was way more content decomposing somewhere under the shining of the sun.\n\n- What did you expect when they said mine village, Kara? - Rein tried to reason with her quite spitefully.\n\n- Well definitely not anything like that! - she pointed at the supposed miner, - no offense.\n\nRein rolled his eyes and started moving towards the mine entrance. Kara would have never followed if she wasn’t terrified of leaving him alone again. It didn’t prove to be safe last time.\n\nThe slow mob followed the heroes in without breaking eye contact. The one that was able to speak showed them to a shaky elevator and stood by the lowering mechanism. It almost felt normal if you take out the unnerving smell of stale air and the weird look of their tour guides. They loaded without questions and started their slow descent.","n":195},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"- You said that I could do anything once this was over! - Kara was furious. Whatever she seemed to do it would upset some unknown audience that never had left her back as long as she stayed in the mansion like all heroes were supposed to, - How does going to some hero reunion party helps me to stay out of all this stupid mess that you seem to be brewing all behind my back?\n\n- It wouldn’t have been behind it if you just bothered to show up instead of running around the woods blocking all signals, - Tarik was surprisingly calm.\n\n- Why don’t you go and support Rein and his efforts, make a show out of that! - Kara didn’t like feeling cornered. It was much easier to be locked in four walls, but it felt suffocating. Maybe she should invest in a dome, but then it would feel like a coliseum all over again.\n\n- Well unless you are willing to go and hunt him down every time, - Tarik leaned back on the couch, - that’s out of the question.\n\nKara hated the fact that she couldn’t take her potatoes anywhere and without them she didn’t see the point of going anywhere. She could protect the gorge, but it still meant nothing if the government would decide to burn in once more. She could die trying to stand her ground and no one would care, but they kept pushing the compromises. She shouldn’t have ever let them touch Vincent.","n":196},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"Kara could feel the pressure changing as they moved further into the darkness. It felt like diving into a deep ocean with no visible bottom as far as the eye could reach. It took almost fifteen minutes to reach the bottom. Every now and then limp bodies would fall around making the entire experience even more dreary as the echoes would rush the sound of slimy slaps bouncing off the walls.\n\n- Why are they jumping? Can’t they wait for the cart? - Kara was terrified of the irrationality of these creatures, - What is happening up there?\n\nFezzik and Rein seemed to be unbudged. Tallie was nervously growling in the corner and Carp just gave Kara a stare with his dead eyed fish mask. Floats stood unbothered like he always did. Somehow Kara didn’t find anything out of place. It felt much safer having them around.\n\nThey landed in the total darkness and Fezzik finally remembered to take out a flashlight. Kara wished he had done it sooner because once the light came back on, the heroes were once more surrounded by the sick miners and Kara screeched at the terrifying sight.\n\n- Damn, Kara. Calm down, - Rein rubbed his ears, - don’t you think they would have attacked us already if they wanted to?\n\n- Shut up.\n\nMiners led heroes through the darkness to a narrow cave. There seemed to be something glowing in the distance.\n\n- We can not go further, - the miners tried stretching their arms into the entrance, but they seemed to be stopped by some sort of wall, - We have to go back.\n\nFor some reason they stood still instead of going back to the surface. Kara felt increasingly uneasy at this remark. It seemed like they wanted to return to the cave where they were denied access to.\n\n- Open the gates, - dreary slime man gave heroes one last terrifying look.\n\n- We got you, buddy, - Fezzik walked into a cave patting the slime on the back and immediately regretting doing so, - Sorry.\n\nKara didn’t need to look at what slapped on the ground to know what it was. She followed the team into the darkness lit by a simple flashlight. It felt weird to walk so close to each other Kara could feel the heat radiating from their bodies. She didn’t quite know if it calmed her down or disturbed her personal space. They walked out of the crevice and suddenly appeared in a very neat well lit concrete hallway. It looked more like a secret bunker than a horrific subterranean monster lair.\n\n- You must be kidding me? - Kara looked around feeling a sense of relief and slight disbelief. It could as well have been just somebody else's secret hideout, - Did you know there was an entire bunker this deep in the ground? Who would dig that far just to build a house? Into the solid rock too. These Octingetti people really have some strange desires for extreme environments. Why would they want the base in the Septum though.\n\n- We do have quite beautiful mountains, - Fezzik shrugged and brushed off the dust from his brown jacket. There was a nice fresh breeze in the hallway. The ventilation was working as if the place wasn’t quite abandoned. That was unnerving, - Lets hope our hosts are in the mood for negotiations, - he tightened up his invisible tie and walked forward.","n":197},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"Good thing they knew nothing about Bork. He was the smallest potato of the bunch and could easily be hidden in a sleeve. When she woke up in a white room filled with nothing but a bed pillow and a blanket. It wasn’t that big. Kara found the seemingly empty parcel and felt her heart falling into an endless abyss. For a second she couldn’t feel the ground. She could never think that this was ever going to happen.\n\nShe chaotically shaked the bag and felt her heart sink even lower when Bork rolled out and hit the ground. That fall could have destroyed him. Kara collapsed to her knees feeling how stupid all of her feelings were. It was just a potato. Tiny one at that too. It was excruciatingly painful to find any reasons why Kara felt like her world just rolled over in the matter of seconds just because of this puny vegetable. She lost dear friends in a heartbeat and moved on and yet this tiny plant root was a deal breaker between life and death. Kara must have been going insane. It should never have been this valuable.","n":198},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"Kara didn’t want to admit that she was terrified anymore with her stupid questions. It didn’t seem like it was solving any of their problems and distracted Rein and Fezzik from actually coming up with a solution. They came to a metal bar wall that seemed to be opened by a button on the other side. Kind of like these stupid design fences that was tightly looked unless you know that there is a button to open them right at the other side in a reach of an arm. Floats seemed to have understood the trick as he just casually appeared on the other side and pressed the button. Kara almost forgot that heroes could do that. She never tried it without Fluffers though.\n\n- Nice! - Fezzik pumped his fist and cheered up Floats. It was weird to realize that the same man had pummeled him down to the ground just yesterday. Kara smiled in sarcastic disbelief. They looked and acted just like two best friends. Although that probably just been them being stressed out of their minds. Kara did that with potatoes sometimes, it wasn’t hard to anticipate the reaction of a potato.\n\nTallie didn’t look quite comfortable either, so Kara politely took the goblin by the hand pretending to be scared. Well, not so much pretending. It felt reassuring, Kara wouldn’t even mind if Tallie would end up dragging her into the heat of the fight. Maybe then she wouldn’t have time to worry about pestering thoughts.\n\nIf Rein saw this he would have given Kara the biggest eye roll of her life. Good thing he was busy exploring ahead. They came across some room and Fezzik and Rein stopped to explore it. Kara hastily let go of the goblin hand and moved on to exploring the hallway corner. It would have been a shame if something was right behind it.\n\nShe checked the corner and was startled by a scream and muffled scrimmage. She rushed to the door only to bump into Fezzik running right into her and Rein screaming to stop him. Kara rushed a tackle, surprised by how light Fezzik really was.\n\n- Kara, they are trying to kill me! - Fezzik seemed scared out of his mind.\n\n- Calm down, if they would try they would do, - she didn’t even know what sort of a bug was this new magic, but who knows what sort of trouble Fezzik would get into running away from concerned teammates, - What happened?\n\n- I took the rod and woke up on the chair, - Fezzik was thoroughly convincing, - Now they want me to touch the rod again because they say it turned me into stone.\n\nIt checked out, but for some reason Tallie still came over to drag Fezzik towards the stone Fezzik. She looked extremely pissed and even kicked the poor demon a couple of times to stop his attempts to escape.\n\n- Please don’t make me go through this again, - Kara stared in shock as Fezzik screamed from the top of his lungs, not sure if she did the right thing.\n\n- Ok, prove me that you are him! - Rein made a brief stop before putting Fezziks hand around the rod.\n\nFezzik hesitated and Rein wrapped red fingers around the stone. This time Kara saw it first hand. Screaming Fezzik slowly stopped moving, turning a smooth gray color and stature Fezzik grasped some air and took a couple of shocked steps backwards.\n\n- Thanks, - He seemed out of breath and thoroughly terrified. He took out a cigarette and fired it up.\n\n- That was a snare, mind to share? - Carp surprisingly stood up next to him, extending his hand. Fezzik took out another one and absentmindedly gave it to a fish goblin.\n\n- What happened? - Kara asked one more time, but her glance fell on Floats going over to a statue that looked like him. He reached out his hand, but Kara rushed over and slapped his hands away, - No, no more touching anything!\n\n- I thought that I could do a much better job at posing for a statue, - Floats nonchalantly smiled, but backed away. Kara almost forgot how stupidly fanatical heroes could be. It sent chills through her bones.\n\n- I said no, - Kara sighed with relief when Floats shrugged and left the room.\n\n- Yeah, Fezzik, - Rein massaged his temples, - Please tell me that that wasn’t you. Because he sure sounded quite convincing.\n\nFezzik just inhaled a cigarette and shook his head, still too shocked to make eye contact. Tallie didn’t take too long to reconsider. She proceeded to smash all the statues in the room while everyone took a break to let her finish. Kara stepped outside to escape the hammering sounds. She walked all the way to the end of the hallway and discovered a beautiful painting of green fields. It was the size of a door. She decided to wait for her teammates there.","n":199},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"It wasn’t the same no matter how long she looked at them. Even as she would ask them questions they would just respond that they are happy living in the garden. She looked at the leaves and the flowers and she couldn’t seem to find anything new. She admired them for years, she knew every pattern of their leaves. It still wasn’t the same. It still was beautiful, but Kara couldn’t help it. It was painfully lonely.","n":200},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"There was a sense of serenity in sitting on a floor in front of a well lit painting. Kara didn’t even mind some messy strokes. They reminded her of annoying thin grass blades that were a bit too negligible to stand up and rip them from the view. After a while they just blended in with the background. It was indeed a well lit painting.\n\nFezzik appeared first out of the room, briefly opening the way for the clashing of a hammer to flood the hallway.\n\n- How do you feel? - Kara turned back around to the painting and asked a question just to be polite.\n\n- Yeah, - Fezzik started thinking about an explanation, but struggled, - You know, well, Rein said that the guy said that he was me, but I don't remember any of it.\n\n- He did call us by our names, but there’s nothing new in that, - Kara was slowly understanding why she tackled the imposter instead of helping him to hide, - I was more surprised that it was trying to run away from us. I mean you didn’t even resist when Floats knocked you out last time.\n\nThere was an awkward silence. Kara felt bad for bringing it up, it wasn’t worth it to sound smart in this situation. Although it must have been reassuring to know that his teammates would not leave him stuck in the statue for eternity. It did sound like Kara had just denied Floats to reach his lifetime dream. She wondered if she should have let him. Who knows, maybe imposter Floats would have a bit more thoughts behind his eyes.\n\n- Yeah, - Fezzik sounded sincerely grateful, - It would have sucked to be stuck there.\n\nThe phrase gave Kara shivers. Suddenly the painting lost all its charm.","n":201},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"It bothered Toham to this day. Every time she would see green field painting it would strangle her in unexplained paralysis. For a second, like waiting for something to appear. Thin grass blades. The untidy strokes. She always took a second before moving on. And that’s after she made the point of returning to the bunker and burning that particular painting to make sure that it would stop haunting her. It was an act of pure self defense. She couldn’t let the original to exist when there were so many copies around to fool her. She didn’t ever want to accidentally touch the original again. It was a silly fixation. People thought it was funny and daring. Octingetti even invited her themselves. Someone said that she should have just grind it down instead, but everyone agreed it would defeat the point and make the problem worse.\n\nToham was a livid germaphobe and antiseptics were only puny half measures for her. At least that was how they justified it. That and something about it being a symbolic ritual and that it didn’t have to be completely environmentally friendly. Toham was glad that no one knew how impulsive she could be. She really did like that painting.","n":202},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"Rest of the team joined up soon after. Kara made sure she was the one to take the painting aside and reveal the door behind it. Like a magician, she spent so much time inspecting it that it was obvious that there was a door behind it. She opened it and there sat a guard. He was scribbling something down in his notebook. It seemed like he was in charge of the entire structure because when the door opened he just yelled, - Yes, please come in.\n\nKara was so confused that if the man would stand up from his chair and reveal to have a set of four animal feet she would still question why and not what, - Why are you here?\n\n- What do you mean why? This is my job, I guard the gate and can you please tell these idiots outside that they should really come back in and stop wasting time outside. It’s not healthy for them, - man, who definitely wasn’t a centaurus, was extremely annoyed at the fact that something was not going according to his plan.\n\n- Yeah, I don’t think they can, buddy. How about you lay a bit off? - Fezzik was getting protective of miners, but it probably wasn’t his first time in this situation, - What is up with that statue room?\n\n- You mean the security office? - man became worried now, - Who are you?\n\n- What do you mean who are we? Didn’t they tell you they sent us here on the capital tournament orders? - Rein said the phrase and looked for a reaction. Kara forgot that they technically were supposed to come and help their problem.\n\n- Yeah, whatever. So you said they still can’t get in? - man scratched his head and sighed, - And let me guess, you are the exterminator group. Sorry, it’s been a long day. Get that hag out of there, it is messing with my workers and our deadlines.\n\n- Ok, understood, so which way do we go? - Fezzik loosened up. Man pointed to the door and the heroes silently walked in. It took them a second to understand what to do with a twirling in black colors portway, - Huh, so that’s what happens when they break. Who would have known that you could just hoax such an advanced technology. So much for superstitions.\n\n- This port is wobbly, what a jolly, - Carp sounded like he was stating some sort of a fact.\n\n- What superstitions? - Kara was quite new to the magical side of practical jokes.\n\n- You know, when a ghost comes through a lightbulb and does bling-bling, bling-bling, - Fezzik raised his hand and played with an imaginary switch. It made Kara chuckle. Somehow the portway didn’t stop looking terrifying, but at least Kara knew what was going on. She sure wasn’t afraid of the hag, no matter how real it felt. It was just ever so slightly unsettling.","n":203},{"chapter":"Mine Prisoners","text":"The essay asked you to write about what you were scared of and why. Kara Toham knew it was a trick question, so she didn’t write the whole truth. She wrote she was scared of a disease, war, spiders or anything that crawls or slithers. Anything that adults would teach you to be scared of, after all they were the masters of the right answers. They had more time to figure them out. Nobody ever liked to talk about the worst ones, so Kara didn’t mention them either. It was easier to focus on what already had worked.","n":204},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"It wasn’t painful until Tallie didn’t land on her back. After that it got complicated. Heroes were stuck in a pile in the middle of the room with Floats on top. Going in all together could have been more orderly if they took turns. Kara could only wonder how Fezzik felt. He cushioned her fall and now was growling in pain. It was a beautiful room.\n\nIt started with the birth of a star. At least that was the darkest corner that Kara focused on to start her investigation. It was the easiest one to mark the start and the end, an important direction identifier in a bright circular room.\n\nThe iridescent dark waves brought the star to the shore of the land and a hand picked it up. It was a beautiful green porcelain doll lying on the poppy bed who mechanically curled her fingers around a glowing little star, but she was a bit clumsy. A little chip has come off and got blown away by the winds. The doll grew pale in fear and the cracking veins on her other hand became vines and leaves as she tried to catch the chip. They glistered with blue sparkles as you stepped further. Like a bird feather.\n\nThe little chip flowed further down, growing into a racoon chasing a light firefly that burned the porcelain dress as it was trying to escape the nifty claws of a predator. Fire spread revealing a circle hole of from the depth of which a dark red mist was covering the burned out mountain as the dragons flew around tearing each other to bits and shreds.\n\nAround the burning hole little porcelain dolls were patching everything together. One like the other wearing the pattern of four outfits. Long fur coat, short blossoming dress, long flowing gown and short playful pinafore. Repeated four times and all busy with their work.\n\nThe doll with a burning dress was surrounded by giant red poppies with black buttons sawn in their centers. They looked like war hero name stones with myriads of golden lines too tiny for anyone to ever read. One of her legs was cracking with fire bursting from the crevices. It was stretching over the poppy bedding and floating over a beautiful green scenery of an apple orchard.","n":205},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"It was never clear why there was a need for potato pandemic. The so-called virus spread across all states like a wind making many fall ill in their family homes. It was a whole mess. People got addicted, delusional, aggressive and all because of the lack or excess of potatoes. They would kill their neighbors to steal a sack of precious vegetables, ignoring all other valuables in the house. Sometimes children would fight during the dinner with their own siblings to get a bigger share. Quattour was quite proud of their new study that linked all the bad deeds of a human to consumption of a treacherous tuber. Now anyone with a potato in their house was a direct threat to the community.\n\n- Why do I have to cover up the fact that they are trying to sabotage my show? - Toham raised an eyebrow and put down the paper, - The potatoes don't even have to do anything with it. They just made a very convincing scapegoat for everything that is already happening everywhere.\n\n- Well, didn’t you want people to stop eating potatoes so that you could have them all safe and sound in the garden? - Tarik seemed to be confused.\n\n- Why would anyone ever take that literally? - Toham couldn’t believe her ears.","n":206},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"The orchard was blossoming with apples, but the dolls underneath the trees did not gather or eat them. They just danced in the shade each with her own food in hand. One ate an orange surrounded by fresh peels, the other held a turnip. Tomato, giant pumpkin, avocado, carrot, exploded watermelon, some other fruits Kara never saw before. Further in the orchard dolls were happily chasing animals, one of them fished in the pond. Beyond the orchard animals chased dolls, but they were too far away to know for sure.\n\nOnly one doll with a patched dress was sitting in the shade of a tree looking upwards at the apples up above. In her hand sat an apple that seemed to soak her skin in color giving it a lively pale peach hue. Her hands looked warm and soft now. She was drawing something.\n\n- Well, this isn’t creepy at all, right? - Kara stepped away from the wall and looked back at her teammates.\n\n- I mean it is a generally accepted concept, - Floats seemed to be quite intrigued by the artwork, - It is a fancy way to immortalize one’s image. Hiding it in a bunker was a smart move. No one can destroy it if no one knows it exists.\n\n- And if a mountain collapses on top of it? - Kara was just surprised that Floats talked at all.\n\n- Well, who would care? - Floats smiled, - The paint looks so old I don’t think the artist would be still alive.\n\nHeroes each took a minute to study the painting before entering the next room. It only felt right, it would be a shame to walk through a haunted portway without enjoying some of the view.\n\n- So do you think a hero built this place? - Kara couldn’t stop thinking about the painting and why would anyone spend so much time working on something that was meant to be just washed away by time. Sounded like a job for an obsessed individual. Sounded a lot like her.\n\n- It was definitely some heroic effort, - Floats seemed to have stuck on some thought. Kara politely stopped asking questions.","n":207},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"Maybe it was for the better. Once the potato market collapsed people returned to their regular problems. Police would go around exterminating all evidence of potatoes and burning heretics on the stakes charging them with criminal offense. Even owning images of potatoes was strictly frowned upon and entire culture was cast into the shadows of surviving follower minds. Potatoes were framed for giving powers to Septum heroes and in return taking away their sanity. Kara knew that to be true for at least one. She wasn’t particularly proud of it, but she couldn’t just stop. It was one garden in the middle of nowhere. It hurt no one if they didn’t seek it.","n":208},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"It was a weird bunker. The hallway  leading up to the painting room was lifeless and bare. It almost seemed like someone wanted to clear all remaining thoughts before they entered the room. Kara felt bad for barging in with so little respect. It was hard to locate the exact logic of the building. Octingetti strictly followed the regulations for structures built in the other states, however one could only imagine what sort of ridiculous ideas could have guided their passion projects. Entire cities built for the sole reason of childish ideas to create a cradle replica of a world with barely enough people to live in them. All in hopes that one day they will be filled by a new generation of people that would take it for granted as they were raised to live in it. Everyone made fun of these projects. Sometimes so much that Octingetti held public executions to punish distinctively stupid and wasteful ideas. No one envied Octingetti heroes. Their work was destined to change through years of human mutilation and newcomers' renovation. And after all that it could still be completely destroyed in a fit of need or accidental conflict.\n\nThere was a slight incline downwards making the steps slightly lighter and the air pressure slightly denser. It was unsettling when the girl in pinafore appeared from the wall only to give heroes a brief look and calmly walk through the door at the end of the hallway. A slightly unsettling sight, but it only made sense that such structure would not be left completely unattended. Beside a slight gasp from Fezzik no one really gave it their mind. When they entered the room to which the girl had disappeared into they found a large salon filled with decorated statues and furniture organized to fit a waiting room. There were three doors on the other side of the wall. Tallie impatiently opened the first one and walked in while the rest of the team was looking around the room for some sort of a ghostly presence. After maybe a minute Fezzik opened the door through which Tallie walked through and called the team over in a slight shock.\n\n- She is not moving, - Fezzik tried to reach in with a hand, but growled in pain as something seemed to be slowing it down like a half dried wood sap.\n\n- It’s a time room, - soft voice from the side wall made everyone turn and see the same ghostly girl they have seen in the hallway, - I use it when I get bored of the time.\n\n- What do you mean? - Fezzik was thoroughly confused, rubbing his hand as if it was asleep.\n\n- It slows down time inside so that change can happen faster on the outside. Quite useful when you work with something that takes a long time to settle or dry, - girl seemed to be quite unbothered.\n\n- How do we get her out of there? - Rein looked with a slight concern in his look, but mostly he was just curious.\n\n- I guess you could just wait, just try not to break anything while you are at it, - Girl floated out of the wall and landed on one of the sofas with her light porcelain shoes, - there are few rules for all guests of my house. One, - she took off her shoes and raised them up to demonstrate, - No shoes on furniture or carpets, - porcelain shoes cracked with a clank and disappeared into the air.\n\nKara didn’t see any carpets, but the message was quite clear. It would only make sense for a local ghost to worry about the place that it haunted.\n\n- Second, - she jumped off the sofa and lightly landed on the floor with her shoes puffing into existence on her feet with a white glittering cloud, - No touching the artwork or statues with your greasy hands, - she touched one of the statutes and her hand slowly turned into porcelain and cracked.\n\nA bit extreme, but understandable.\n\n- Third, - she turned around shaking off the ghostly porcelain off her hand like powder, - If you see any critters don’t feed them and don’t leave any food unattended. That includes your lively bits and pieces, - She smiled chipperly, locking her hands behind her back, - Beyond that, enjoy your stay!\n\nGirl bowed and disappeared again. Fezzik rashly wrote down the rules. Last one seemed like the most menacing of them all.\n\n- Wait, - Rein was distracted watching Tallie slowly moving around the time room and just noticed that the girl was gone, - Have you seen a terrifying hag move around and cause inexplicable death?\n\n- Say what? - A girl appeared right behind him, forcing a little fright attack as Rein took a jump to turn around, - Did you just call my friendly guest a hag?\n\n- What do you mean, friendly guest? - Rein was quite disturbed, - You know that thing?\n\n- Of course, I know all heroes, they come through here during training season quite a bit, - girl smiled, - Are you looking for Gizellina or Knutcrazch?\n\n- I hope this isn’t a trick question, - Rein crossed his arms on his chest, - Can you tell your friend to fix the stupid portal so we all can go home?\n\n- Rein! Don’t be rude! - Kara didn’t know what the rituals of speaking to ghosts were, but a friendly spirit is better than an angered one.\n\n- Your portal? You say it’s broken? I was wondering why you guys appeared through the cellar, - girl in a pinafore smiled and shook her head, - Oh no, what a shame, was it a haunted one? Dam, sorry.\n\nSuddenly the girl dropped down to the floor as the lights dropped low and the room completely changed. It was covered in dust and the all statured seemed to have an animal growl.\n\n- Are you happy, Rein? - Fezzik was thoroughly disappointed.","n":209},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"- So your name is Kara Toham? - the party men were disgusting. They kept asking if she was who she was. By a full name. It was infuriating every time, but there was no reason for them not to. The greatest set up of Septum and most ruthless murderer the tournament has ever seen. With a perfect team record too.\n\n- And you are? - Kara resisted rolling her eyes, but still dropped them to the floor for a moment. She wondered what kind of an answer she would get and how upset they would be the next time they met. She wasn’t about to start learning new names for this gig.\n\n- Caravan, - the leading man pointed at himself and proceeded to introduce his friends, - and this is Xin, Percival and … - Kara didn’t hear the last name, but she couldn't help, but stare at Percival. There wasn’t anything special about him other than a name.\n\n- Sorry, who was the last one? - Kara snapped back suddenly feeling absolutely terrified.\n\n- Barsik, - Caravan repeated the name, - real charm to have around in a heated discussion of machine guns.\n\n- Yeah, you know the more bullets you shoot the greater the chance to get the quick ones, - Barsik seemed to speak somewhat casually. Kara didn’t like that one bit. Heroes didn’t seem to mind discussing their victories.\n\n- You know they don’t allow guns in all states, right? - nobody liked Unus heroes. All of them started with a gun and proper cradles up training. Kara hated working around bullets. Reload, counting shoots, lack of ammunition. The support system for that kind of a strategy seemed to be unnecessarily complicated.\n\n- Sorry, are we stepping on some tails already? - Caravan smiled politely and reached to pat Kara on the shoulder. She stepped out of the way.","n":210},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"Kara definitely preferred the friendly ghost version of the room.\n\n- Wow guys, what did you do to a place? - Tallie walked out of the time room looking quite shocked from the experience, - And yeah, that room is also weird, - she pointed backwards at the door still expecting explanation on what happened while she was gone.\n\n- Ghost said hi, room was a lie, - Carp spoke up, but Tallie just raised a brow. Two goblins definitely came from different tribes.\n\n- What in nine states is that? - Rein was looking at some statue with a disgusted expression. Kara came over and froze in her steps. Her heart started racing and she felt nauseous. It was Fluffer Huggins. Stuffed like a hunters trophy with glue clouding his epoxy eyes. Kara could barely stand on her feet covering her mouth trying to hide her terrified expression. She recognised every detail of a growling muzzle.\n\nRein took out his rapier and cut the statue in half, digging straight through its stuffing.\n\n- REIN! STOP IT! - Kara screamed in shock, unable to move. Her perception couldn’t allow her to come any closer to the twisted abomination that became of her childhood friend.\n\n- He is dead, Kara, - Rein tried to stay composed. He took his hand from the stuffing to reveal a small black beating heart.\n\nKara wanted to vomit, but she didn’t have breakfast. She just collapsed breathing heavily, trying to remember what was going on. She wanted to murder those who did it. How did they know?","n":211},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"It was tough to start the process. There was a reason why Kara resisted the idea until the very end. Her hands were shaking as she held the knife to a potato. It was a stupid fixation and she should have never been scared of such a simple task.\n\n- Kara, have you ever peeled a potato? - Victorian looked at her with a careful expression.\n\n- What do you think? - she put down the knife and potato on the table and buried her face in hands, - Out of all things. Why would you ever think that I could do it?\n\n- You killed people with these things, - Victorian pressed on.\n\n- That is a terrible wordplay and you sure know that! - Kara snapped, but a short zap sat her back on her seat, - That was uncalled for, - She opened her fingers to give Victorean an angry look.\n\n- Listen, those are not even your potatoes. You don’t even have to eat them, - Victorian was more than reasonable, - Sorry, I knew you would try to run away. We just need to get this over with and you are way too jumpy.\n\n- And who’s fault is that? - Kara stood up and started walking towards the door.\n\n- Kara! - Victorian shouted, but she already snapped an answer.\n\n- Zap me one more time and good luck trying to get me anywhere close to that show for another four years, - She slammed the door behind her so loudly that something cracked with a knock.","n":212},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"Kara sat in the corner for a couple of minutes while her teammates set off to check the second door. Carp stayed with her.\n\n- That’s a cat, what’s wrong with that? - the question seemed so sincerely innocent. Kara felt bad for not finding words to speak. There was nothing wrong with it. It probably was some sort of hag’s tricks to throw her out of her game. She just needed some time to calm down from the shock.\n\n- It’s just not a nice way to treat an animal, - finally answered, - You wouldn’t like that being done to… - Kara stopped as she realized that she was quite literally talking to a fish head, - For sprouts sake.\n\n- This is not a sprout, more of a trout, - Carp sounded like he wanted to cheer her up.\n\n- Why am I even talking to you, - covered her face and stretched her legs. There was no point in sitting down. Whatever memories she was trying to commemorate, they were only hurting her more and more and it was completely uncalled for. It wasn’t Fluffer Huggins and she knew it way too well. Rein saw through it right away.\n\nKara stood up and followed in the tracks of the rest of the team. It was a hallway with many open and dark rooms. Some were bedrooms, some were storage rooms, Kara enjoyed the well lit alcoves the most. The only thing they were missing were windows.\n\nSuddenly the ground shook and the hallway filled with screams. Kara broke into a sprint, suddenly worried for the team. Mostly for Fezzik, Tallie and Floats could take care of themselves and sometimes Kara thought that Rein would rather die than let her resolve a situation. Unless of course the danger were Tallie and Floats, then Rein would be the one in quite a bit of trouble. That, however, was highly unlikely. Well, fifty-fifty if you count a raw score. Kara had no idea why she settled on the prospect of the first option. Maybe because it seemed less absurd.","n":213},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"- They kill people? - Kara didn’t know why Tarik kept bringing her those fake reports just to keep her posted on the current standing of potatoes in the world. It was weird to continue shooting the show in the light of such events. Potato show never promoted eating potatoes and even mentioned once how poisonous they could be. It was purely educational. Kara usually only spoke from the experience, but lately news was starting to seep through to her.\n\n- Yes, Kara, people kill people, but everyone has potatoes. It’s just easy to throw them in the mix and people would take it as a believable story, - Tarik was really bad at making it sound any better, - It’s easier to do that than waste time explaining how somewhere in the evolution process people decided to preserve the mortal culture in order to see how much further they could keep it up without self destructing.\n\n- Can’t you just shut up? - Kara felt like a complete idiot, - I can’t believe that you, out of all people, would be pushing such fanatical words. How old are you? Fifty five?\n\n- Kara, I will snap your neck and let you sit for a day, - Tarik never joked about these things.\n\n- Oh stop it Ember, what would uncle Ben think if you did that? - Kara smiled and waved a quick apology. Ember chuckled.","n":214},{"chapter":"The painting room","text":"Kara wanted to stop at the giant open door in which Carp disappeared a moment ago. Wanted, but a wet floor carried her over and she slid past the entrance with style. Until she slipped and fell over onto her hands. In a brief moment she saw a giant white tree wailing around with leafless long branches. It looked like a creepy weeping willow.\n\n- Fezzik, what did the doll say about the critters? - suddenly Kara thought that the advice might have actually made sense.\n\n- Not to feed them with our bits and pieces. Kara, please just help, - Fezzik was holding on to a pillar with tough roots insistently pulling him over to a tree. By the water in the hallway Kara figured that she would have to dodge any second now.","n":215},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"People called it instincts, Kara called it being smart. Mainly because in her experience she only did the most or the next best thing to have survived this far. Of course Kara knew that real proper name for it would be dumb luck. Evolutionary precursors like those that told toddlers to hold their breath when they fall in water. She could have just been that one that had a bit more of the lucky genes in her system.\n\nKara jumped without even looking at the attack. It was more awkward to land straight on roots that were crushing into the wall, but by that time she was already ready to swing her ax. Fluffer Huggins lit the background on fire making the tree squeal in a haunting cry of pain. Kara didn’t expect it to burn so brightly with so much moisture around.\n\nThat, of course, didn't quite finish the deal. The roots and branches grew into an abominable frenzy slashing the air with whipping howls and earthshaking thuds. Kara was surprised by the accuracy of that thing. While she was navigating through a barrage of branches, roots tripped her and curled swiftly around her legs. It did feel kind of stupid and rash of her to run inside when it was obvious that this would happen. She looked around to discover the rest of the teammates in the similar situation. They were tangled and fighting the roots pulling them towards a very hungry looking tree.\n\n- Have you tried telling it that it’s unreal and you are not scared of it? - Kara tried to cheer up the mood. It seemed like a very likely solution to a ghost related problem. Too bad this was a very real tree.\n\n- Yes, Kara, the first thing we did was ask whether a giant homicidal tree wants to be friends! - Rein was being a bit too sarcastic for someone being so close to the tree. Fluffer Huggins raced through the chaos over to him, bit into his shoulder and they both disappeared in a fire flash to reappear next to Kara, leaving a blazing mess where they just stood.\n\n- You could do that all along? - Rein didn’t sound too grateful.\n\n- Fluffers jumps all the time, why would it surprise you? - Kara’s foot slipped from the draining ledge that she was using for anchor and fell sliding towards the tree. It was then when she saw Carp seamlessly swim around the tree like a salmon in a fight up the river. He didn’t seem to mind the situation at all as he casually kicked off the roots and branches like a fish swimming in the current.","n":216},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- Watch it, - Kara snarled as her hand slapped Caravan’s hand away. She wanted to apologize for a second, but then waited for too long to do so.\n\n- Hey, it’s all right, - Caravan must have recognized the startled look on her face, - Not a hugger, not a shooter. I’ll remember.\n\n- Like it’s going to help you, - Kara didn’t like being assessed by heroes. She didn’t like speaking to the heroes. Sometimes they were interesting to look at, but that usually mixed badly with the ones from the incompatible states. The division in common principles was too drastic for any type of friendship.\n\n- Oh no, luckily for the ones in mid ranges they created these, - Caravan took out the little dark orange charm out of his pocket and twirled it around his fingers. Oldest and stupidest trick in the book.","n":217},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"It was dragging on for way longer than Kara would have liked. No matter how much the heroes wasted time on trying to get out of the room, the tree tirelessly persisted in tangling their feet and pulling them inwards. A little fire seemed to burn, but it couldn’t match the rate of new roots and branches rushing out like an endless flow. It was indeed a reversed forest fire situation, things like that didn’t really fit in the rational world of up and down.\n\n- Well, I’m done. This isn’t even a critter, - Kara commanded Fluffer Huggins to focus on the tree instead of trying to get her teammates out and the flaming tom instantly jumped into the battle.\n\n- Yes, but it could be an art work, - Fezzik was trying to be reasonable, but Kara wasn’t about to try and follow riddle rules quite possibly made up by the creator of that tree of an art work.\n\n- I’m not going to touch it, - Kara held her hand out and imagined fire engulfing the entire tree. Every foot of root and stretch of a branch. The fire seemed to come straight from inside of the tree forcing the bark crack and ooze with flaming hot sap. Tree slowly shriveled and dried up leaving a charred reminder of a shape. Kara stopped the fire once she was satisfied with the result. Pestering tree was burnt and dead. She would never use such flexible branches for a house, so burning it only felt natural.\n\n- You! Good job, - Tallie shot a thumbs up to Kara and she suddenly felt super proud of the level of self control she has demonstrated. Stupid waste of time in the beginning, but at least everyone was safely out of the fire zone. Kara was actually quite surprised how rational her decision making has become. The tree still got burned, but at least it didn’t bother anyone anymore. Kara was officially the coauthor of the sculpture and she didn’t care one bit what her counterpart would think about the new changes. They probably were dead too.\n\n- Shame it had to resort to being a carnivore without a source of sunlight, - Fezzik looked at the black charred trunk of a tree in the middle of a white, dimly lit room.\n\n- Are you seriously saying that it could have been a critter? - Rein was taking branches out of his hair, visibly unhappy with a very real attribute of the attack, - I think the entire experience is being fabricated by the stupid regime. Oh no, a big underground bunker with no visible escape route? Kara, that could have been a man once and we wouldn't have known a difference.\n\n- You are surely not trying to make me feel bad for a tree that was trying to eat you? - Kara raised an eyebrow.\n\n- No, I’m just saying that in these situations there isn’t a point of trying to classify something that is already dead, - Rein always was good at moving forward on his own ledge. Keeping things that work and letting go of things that didn’t. It must have been a pure torture for him to be around Kara. Some things had an annoying ability to stick.","n":218},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- No way! - Kara stood in the middle of the town with miss Olive suddenly realizing what was about to happen, - You seriously want me to get a therapy cat? Have you already decided who is going to take care of it? I won’t take it into the woods.\n\n- Don’t worry, it's going to stay in the mansion, - miss Olive smiled and opened the door of a pet store and Kara reluctantly walked in. She was supposed to be settling down after the tournament and older Septum heroes were trying their best to keep her inner child happy.\n\n- All right then, back to normal, - She walked into a painfully strong scent of an animal lair. Fluffer Huggins never smelled like that and he was a stray cat that bathed in all kinds of ditches, - How legal is this?\n\n- Stop it Kara, it’s just their temporary home before they find their people, - Kara shivered from that response. Miss Olive never bothered with intermediate details, - Look, I picked this one because they said they had a perfect fit, - she pointed over to the box with half grown kittens. Half of them were ginger orange, - You can even choose one that you like most.\n\nKara felt sick to the stomach at that phrase. She never picked up Fluffers because she liked him, - I don’t care, Eve. You can choose the one that won’t cause you trouble at home or I could choose one that will make your life a living hell. We both know that there is no winning if one doesn’t lose.\n\n- Kara, if you want to stay you have to work out how to make a compromise, - Miss Olive sighed and picked up a kitten from a litter, - Look, this one was looking up to you.\n\n- Well aren’t you one poor curious cat, - Kara bent down to look into the eyes of a little kitten in the hands of a woman demonstrating that it was, in fact, a tom, - I’ll call you Mister Glasses. Eve, do you know where to get a pair of little pink glasses?\n\n- Now you are speaking my language! - Miss Olive seemed to have not picked up on a joke quite yet.","n":219},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- So youre saying that this is a dead end? - Kara looked at the wall in a pure fit of confusion. If there was no reason to venture out this far there was probably no point in burning the tree either. They were back to square one and that was an understatement. Heroes were walking back towards the waiting room. An eerie feeling of a haunted bunker has perished and Kara was left with just a slight aftertaste of disgust. It felt like they were rummaging through a dumpster looking for a haystack with a deary aura to break a needle inside of it. Maybe they had already fixed the problem, but there wasn’t a real way to tell. The waiting room didn’t seem to change even one bit. Still creepy and still full of unpleasant faces. The insides of a dead Fluffer Huggins still littered the floor. Flaming Fluffer Huggins walked out of the door and proceeded to burn the unwanted reminders by meticulously chasing the burning fluff all over the room.\n\n- Can you not? Just burn it and be done. - Rein knew what she was doing.\n\n- Why? Do you suddenly care? - Kara looked away, but Fluffer Huggins continued his game.\n\n- No, it’s just looks stupid, - He turned away and opened the last door. It led to another hallway.","n":220},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- So you never told me how you got rid of it, - Toham knew it was a sensitive topic, but there wasn’t much else to do around this place.\n\n- I just agreed to take the job, - Tarik shrugged and flipped the page he was reading.\n\n- So nothing special? How did you get it then? - she kept the conversation alive.\n\n- Different times, different rules, different management. It’s not like they had any other choices, - he was getting a bit agitated.\n\n- I bet you were quite happy to get rid of it, - Toham knew the rest of the story. Tarik chuckled.\n\n- You should have seen Eve get rid of hers, - Ember finally spoke with a smile, - If you have time I might show you some footage. And I thought she was crazy.\n\n- Watch it, - Kara didn’t like that last remark.\n\n- I said I thought. I’ve been young once too, - Ember corrected himself nervously straightening up into a more stable position.\n\n- Sorry, - Toham sighed and stretched back on a chair feeling slightly embarrassed, - Wanna talk about clouds?","n":221},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- No need for alarm, third door is a charm, - Carp rushed into the last hallway. There was lightning zapping, stone falling, flame roaring and all while five heroes watched a fish go swimming. Carp seemed to have overdosed on sugar as goblin jumped around on all fours on four walls living his best life. By the time he made it to the end he seemed to have triggered anything and everything like he knew the place by the palm of his hand.\n\n- You know what, why not? - Rein dropped his surprised eyebrows and started making his way through the slightly demolished terrain, - We might as well just get it over with.\n\nAnd on they went. Something was unsettling Kara about Carp after that incident. Why would they not release him in the first place? He seemed way overqualified and, for the better question, did he also go through the criminal feast and was it the same they went through? Did they set up a new feast and killed another hundred or so people telling them they will need just one? Maybe there was a town in Septum just for that. Kara would not be too surprised, but there must have been a better explanation. Carp was actually a fish that they turned into a goblin so that it was easier to understand a metaphor. It was easier than trying to body count option one. Weren’t Floats and Haderach friends?\n\n- Kara! - Rein shouted from somewhere in the distance. Kara instinctively ducked and rolled right out of the way of a giant serpent. She didn’t quite remember how she got into the room full of rubble and a horrifying stench of death. She must have lost herself in thoughts and wandered away. That happened before, in the pit. She didn’t exactly have time to remember everything she was thinking of.\n\n- What? - Kara made sure to sound as unsurprised as she could, - Everything is under control, - She spun around and hit the snake with an ax, but it didn’t cut through like it always did. It did make it angrier. Kara booked it towards Rein who was holding a door for her. He closed it as soon as she ran in. She wasn’t even close to feeling scared enough. It was like trying to hang on to the moment that was just slipping away too quickly.\n\n- Didn’t you see Tallie whack at this thing? - Rein definitely wasn’t too happy. Kara was going to ask what happened, but decided against that. If no one mentioned it it shouldn’t have mattered. Kara wondered if she always lived by that motto, she didn’t exactly have memory of every moment of her life.\n\n- So what is the plan? - Rein was genuinely confused. Kara wasn’t sure if he was joking.\n\n- Didn’t we come here to recapture a hag? To be honest, I didn’t really listen to Darius, - Kara still felt a bit shook.\n\n- Who is Darius? - Fezzik looked at Kara with a puzzled and terrified look.\n\nKara blinked twice trying to remember how she knew the name, - The guy that wanted us to catch a hag?\n\n- You know him? - Rein looked straight at her with suspicion. Kara started to feel a cold shower rubble down her spine.\n\n- And you don’t? - she raised an eyebrow wondering why she knew the name, - Looked like a straight up one. You know the hero that was… - Kara stopped suddenly realizing something in her head. She didn’t remember the story either, - You know what, maybe I should sit down. This air is getting into my head.\n\nIt was quite hard to breathe.","n":222},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"Heroes often changed their shapes. Toham still couldn’t wrap her head around the fact that they somehow organized themselves into tribes without actually being related. Just a cross of an interest and now instead of one Carp you have a whole school of them running on four legs wearing some sort of a mask on their heads. Perfect closed systems that didn’t need any moderation and could perfectly govern themselves independently until you throw in a disturbance. It never happened on purpose, sometimes interests clashed and boundaries were pushed. Toham did that when she declared the land around the gorge to be Septum. First it was fine, then neighbors started whining about missing people. Who would have thought that potato show would not be enough to prevent an outbreak. Toham thought it was very convincing. Septum for sure believed that potatoes that she promised were well worth fighting for. It was a perfectly closed system now. Toham didn’t know how it worked, but she didn’t care enough. It was really Alfonse's problem.","n":223},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- Kara, you ok? - Fezzik patted her on the shoulder, - Dam you are burning up, why didn’t you stop the bleeding? - he reached out to help, but a cold sensation from his hand must have triggered something. Kara snapped.\n\nNext thing she remembered was opening her eyes with a pounding headache. Nobody spoke for a couple of minutes. Kara never felt so out of place. Everyone knew what it was.\n\n- You sure have some sharp teeth, darling, - Floats spoke up first trying to lighten the mood. It looked like she bit him on the neck.\n\n- Sorry, - Kara looked down and tried to remember what could have gone wrong, - I didn’t know that it could happen again.\n\n- Wait, so you knew? - Fezzik was rubbing a bloodied hand.\n\n- I mean, they don’t exactly give out instructions, - Kara was trying to defend herself, but figured that it wasn’t really her fault she was given power. There was nothing to explain. There was just a fact that her team was just unlucky to have her today.","n":224},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"- Caravan, where did you get that? - Barsik seemed to tense up at the sight of the orange charm in the hands of his supposed teammate. Xin smiled with a knowing smile and Percival, well, Toham wasn’t looking at him to know. She was caught completely off guard.\n\n- Well we got a little chat with an old friend, pretty sure she won’t notice it gone for quite some time, - Caravan seemed to be about right. Miss Olive wasn’t the most accountable of their team. Kara was trying to come up with some kind of a plan. There weren’t many options from where she stood, it never crossed her mind that something as stupid as this would happen.\n\n- Very mature, - she smiled, but her quick look to the side probably gave away her nerves. For a second she thought that there might be someone on the balcony, but she was specifically looking for a quiet space outside, - You know that it is just a formality?\n\n- Now is it? - Caravan pressed the button and Kara felt an extremely familiar sensation. She also felt a solid strike to the head. It could have been Percival. Kara wasn’t sure what was their motivation, but it sure wasn’t going to be in her favor.\n\n- Enjoying the weather? - the voice of Victorean floated through the air like a mint breeze.","n":225},{"chapter":"Critters and guests","text":"It really was bad timing to put a team of heroes out of commission. Or maybe that’s exactly what their hosts were waiting for. The room has darkened. Kara didn’t realize how big it was until the lights took what felt like forever to be dimmed. A subtle feeling of softness of the change, less abrupt and more theatric.\n\nKara slowly stood up on her feet stepping closer to her teammates who seemed to be still quite weary of her presence. It was a weird square one situation. Fluffer Huggins slowly appeared behind her back brushing under her hand, still soft, but barely burning. Whatever had just happened it must have taken quite a bit out of her too. It didn’t occur to Kara that this could have possibly been the end of the story. Last time she met this creature it wasn’t particularly aggressive, but last time they weren’t exactly in a conflict.\n\n- Oh, come on, - Rein was done waiting for the next que, - Just drop the act and come talk to us already! Can we get through one day without this bunch of nonsense?\n\n- Yeah, whatever conflict you have, don't take it out on the miners, just fix the portal and we will be out of here, - Fezzik chimed in clearly too tired to be scared, - I mean, seriously, they have nothing to do with this.\n\nThere was not an answer for a while, but then the far end of the room lit up with a blue fire. The hag was floating right there menacingly scraping the floor with its long pale hands hanging in a dead unrest. Its feet were bent the wrong way in many wrong places and its skin looked more like an old scrap fabric hanging in an abandoned crib of a burned house. It slowly crawled towards them drying the air with its heavy breath. It did kind of resemble Haderach.\n\n- Sorry we couldn’t help your friend, but, you know, there wasn’t really a whole lot we could do, - Fezzik tried to reason with the thing once again. It didn’t actually occur to Kara that this thing might be sentient enough to have a conversation, but all of the dot’s seemed to match.\n\n- Do you think this could actually be Gizellina? - Kara was holding down a growling Fluffer Huggins. She just didn’t remember the second name, but if the hag was indeed a hero they really had a fifty fifty chance to be right.\n\n- So you met my guest? - A ghoulish voice seemed to have risen from the floor. Kara looked down briefly and jumped. Flaming tom burned up her jacket in surprise and she had to hurry to put out the fire.\n\n- What is wrong with you?! - Kara couldn’t believe the girl in pinafore.\n\n- Sorry, it was a perfect moment, - the girl floated out of the floor and stood in between the heroes, - Alright my guests, here are the ground rules.","n":226},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"Kara was never actually scared of spiders. The thought of them was terrifying only because someone always screamed when they appeared. Weird thing is that nobody actually killed them. Well, if you don’t count jumpy individuals with quick reactions and their accidental regrets. Then there were the tough guy psychos. They made it a point to be the one to come over and smash the creature to pieces for an applause of the terrified group. Kara didn’t kill spiders, if there was no paper to lure the spider on for the release she used her hands. The fear was still in her bones, but it was better than letting some daring hero smash the poor creature to pieces. It was a bad omen to kill spiders.\n\n- No shoes on the furniture or carpets, - girl started over the regular set of rules.\n\n- Excuse me, can we get a bit of the clearance on what is going on and why this so-called hero is hiding in a bunker and haunting Septum mines? - Fezzik was done listening to the most unhelpful rule list in the world, - There aren’t even any carpets here!\n\n- And why do you think that’s the case? None of you even considered taking off your shoes! - the girl tucked her hands into her sides, - Nobody follows the rules once the fighting starts and the most beautiful works end up ruined. I swear to the holy church of peacekeeping, I hate hosting heroes.\n\nNobody spoke for a second and a hag started slowly shrinking in size. The light came slightly up, but the flames remained.\n\n- Why do you keep traps and maizes then? - Rein was increasingly annoyed by the fact that the girl explained nothing of that in the waiting room.\n\n- Requested safety protocol! You think you are the first green leaf heroes that go through the tournament? - The girl in a pinafore crossed arms on her chest, too tired of explaining already, - Pinafore in my seasonal outfit, I’m not a local house maid! You barbarians get what is easiest to replace. And that includes you! - The girl turned towards a supposed Gizellina in a sarcastic bow.","n":227},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"- Why would you even take that to this place? - Toham was doing her best to stay calm. Victorian never had a fuse long enough to negotiate the terms, so she learned to be patient around him.\n\n- You know you are erratic, maybe if you were a bit friendlier around heroes she would trust you a bit more, - Victorian sighed and graciously took the lead, - You tell her nothing about this, she is pretty upset as it is, - his voice sounded commanding and yet calm. Kara always wondered if he used some spell, but it wasn’t like she really wanted to hurt Miss Olive.\n\n- Now how do you think we should return it without her noticing? - Cassius suddenly smiled and looked back at Kara as if this was a game.\n\n- This isn’t funny Cassius, they could have killed me, - Toham wasn’t about to let go of the slip this easily.\n\n- And what then? - Victorian pressed the button and Kara jolted in brief pain, - It’s the safety protocol, you can’t compromise it just because you have a special case of hoarding enemies. If this gets out and these guys get in trouble it would only cause another spiral, pretty sure you understand that yourself quite a bit by now.\n\nAnd who’s fault was that? Toham blamed the potatoes.","n":228},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"- I mean, sorry for the interruption, - the girl in a pinafore smiled gently to a hag and floated out of the room through a door. Kara wondered if she was trying to make some point or just forgot that she could go through walls. She floated into the room with a serpent, so there was clearly some message right there. That, or maybe she just needed to calm down the poor animal.\n\n- Ok, I call for a cease fire, - Fezzik briefly raised his arm to demonstrate a vote. Kara almost mindlessly raised her hand as a joke. She didn’t mind looking stupid if it meant that they could walk away from the situation without setting the place on fire. The pinafore lady seemed to be nice enough, - We can settle this situation like adults.\n\n- Well, if you insist, Alfonse, - a man suddenly appeared behind Fezzik giving him a neighborly pat on the shoulder. Kara shook at the sound of this voice. For a second she thought it was another trick of the mind, but a man stood firmly in his steps.\n\n- Dad? - Rein stood even paler than he usually was. Kara herself felt the grasp of unexplained fear. If she was to follow Reins courtesy she would have to start pummeling this vision right away, but as she swung her ax a bright blue shield glimmered at the sudden impact.\n\n- Kara, what are you doing?! - Rein shouted in confusion as she dropped her ax trying to reassemble the dots.\n\n- Sorry, I thought of Fluffer Huggins.","n":229},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"Mister Glasses was an exemplary cat. He even didn’t mind the fact that Miss Olive was constantly picking up his pink hipster glasses every time he jumped. He fought the courtesy for a while, but, after multiple failed attempts to lose them, he eventually learned to keep them on if he wanted to sit in some peace and quiet. Toham actually liked the look of him wearing the little glasses around. It brightened the mood of the room.\n\n- So we did a survey on what format would be fun for this year's recap, - Miss Olive sounded quite nervous with her pitch. Kara didn’t know that it could happen, but it surely couldn’t mean anything good, - It was suggested we do a cooking show, since your group loved it so much.\n\nIt did sound quite a rational suggestion, but for some reason Kara didn’t like the sound of it. There was always a catch. Audience was always quite ruthless and stupidly mundane in their choices.\n\n- Tarik told me, - Kara was exhausted. At least this time she had better company to discuss the bitter topic. Kara didn’t mind that compromise. Miss Olive really knew how to get what she wanted even if most of her offers sounded like the devil’s deals. Kara preferred to at least know her options, - You know what I want.","n":230},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"Mister Valentine wanted to say something, but he seemed to lose the words as he looked Kara in her eyes. It was awkward, baffling and completely unrelatable. She couldn’t find any reasons why any of this family drama should have concerned her in the first place. She didn’t know this man beyond brief hellos and some family dinners. The silence lingered, as Kara was fighting her personal ego to apologize.\n\n- Listen, Kara, I’m sorry about your parents, but before we start I want to make it clear that I have nothing to do with it, - Mister Valentine jumped to the answer a bit too quickly for Kara to believe him. Now she actually caught up to the speed.\n\n- Exactly, just like you didn’t do anything for your own family, - Rein crossed hands on his chest, - Your daughter is sick, she needs you and you are here playing some hero games for, what I can only assume, your own amusement.\n\nIt was terrifying to see Rein this upset. Kara felt terribly out of place standing anywhere near this conversation. It wasn’t enough that the dead man was alive, but it appeared that he bailed on the family for no obvious reason. Kara never heard of heroes abandoning their kids to starve and scramble for life. Leave alone the fact that they were already sick. It wasn’t something new or revolutionary in the world. It was an everyday tale of common folk, but no one expected it to ever happen so close to home. Kara was trying to understand it, but she killed people to give potatoes a chance. It was deeply against her nature to forgive such behavior. And yet she couldn’t speak, this wasn’t really her problem.\n\n- Listen, Rein, I’m really sorry about how it happened, - Mister Valentine was clearly not sorry, something about his voice just seemed like he was lying to himself for quite a while, - But I had to pull some real strings to get you out of it.\n\n- What kind of strings?! Do you know that I had to volunteer for this tournament exactly because you were too preoccupied with whatever business you came up with to stay away from us? - Rein was furious, but it seemed this wasn’t something new for him, - I will win this tournament for her and I don’t care about your suddenly awakened fatherly spirit.\n\nKara couldn’t help, but noticed the vile pattern in Valentine's behavior. They were gone for a month without a chance to contact anyone from the outside world. Kara didn’t really feel the difference because she had nothing left behind, but Rein came into it with a clear goal in mind. And for a month now he was stepping right into his father’s footprints. The only difference was that he didn’t lie and disappeared into thin air. Not yet.","n":231},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"When Kara finally got a chance to visit the gorge she rushed there the moment the gates opened. She had to be quick and evasive to make sure nobody followed her tracks. Good thing there was no mandatory surveillance after the tournament. The guards that were meant to escort her soon lost track and probably called for Tarik or Victorean for backup, so she had to be fast. It wasn’t like they didn’t know the place.\n\nShe never ran that fast for this long, but she knew this feeling like a palm of her hand. She had to get there before anyone saw it. Probably the stupidest plan of them all, but she wanted to know for herself before anyone had time to reveal her motives. She just had to get there faster than anyone could catch on. She only felt brave because the stakes were stupidly low. If she wasn’t fast enough they could destroy all remaining sprouts before she even gets there. That would have changed nothing, she didn’t really hope there to be any to begin with. She knew exactly how fire worked and how stupidly she made sure all potatoes in that forest were collected in a neat little grove. She just wanted a break from everything. As her breath started to shorten she pushed herself even faster knowing for sure that she didn’t care if it would kill her.","n":232},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"- There is a much safer way to do it, Rein, - Mister Valentine continued trying to reason with his son, but for some reason Kara knew for sure he wouldn’t listen.\n\n- What other way? - Fezzik took over speaking with adults. He stepped in front of Rein and separated the conversation.\n\n- I can get you anti tracking devices and the boat. There is an uprising brewing in Unus to end this whole tournament regime, - Valentine sounded completely delusional.\n\n- It has been a long hundred years, Novem had enough time to play around trying to make their failing system work, - the hag has finally transformed into an older woman with rags for clothing, somehow she looked quite comfortable in them.\n\nKara felt like she was stuck in a highschool square with kids talking about things that sounded quite important, but were completely irrelevant to her case. The prospect of escaping the tournament was quite tempting, however the motive behind it seemed way too unrealistic and childish. It almost sounded too good to be true. Rebellions, destruction, wars and other big words that rallied people together to do something reckless and join the mass hysteria to give their lives larger than life meaning. To be commemorated in the memorial stones with a name printed so small that nobody would ever care to read. Especially if you had no one left to remember who you were. It only felt exciting, but only the heroes were veterans of these wars, no wonder they would constantly try and recruit them from the tournament rotations.","n":233},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"Kara was completely exhausted by the time she reached the gorge. She collapsed looking at the old scorches on rocks and trees. She expected to see that, but the naive part of her hoped to see a beautiful blooming grove for one last time. She didn’t even have strength to check if there were any potato sprouts. She didn’t have to. Her fantasy died right there and then, on the day she was shipped off to a criminal fest and there was nothing anyone could do about it. Government made sure the incident would not repeat. It was all long gone. All what she came back for, all what she fought for, all to come back to this place to make sure there was no chance that a sprout would go through a spring without her. Potatoes were not people, they could not escape and survive on their own. No one could bring them back from the ashes, no one would care enough. Even Kara felt that it would only be cruel to try and bring them back. Unnatural and quite possibly inhumane if they were destined to be burned over and over again.","n":234},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"Fezzik was talking out the details and Kara took a moment to check on the serpent in the room behind. He seemed way too quiet.\n\n- Kara where are you going, - Rein seemed to be needing a break himself.\n\n- You don’t need me to choose your sides, - Kara opened the door, - Not my cup of drama, just tell me when you are done.\n\nShe walked out finding that the giant serpent had disappeared and now all there was left was a room full of rubble and a horrific reptilian stench. It still was better than being part of whatever was brewing up on the other side of the door. If she was to give up on the tournament there was no clear chance of going back to her potato garden in the gorge. She thought she was fine with this prospect.\n\nHer three potatoes were still with her. She could start a new fresh start like she did once before. Politics and power struggles were never part of her life and when they were it was never for the better. She never saw a reason to change anything as long as she had her potato garden and now she had a chance to start anew in a new far away place in a rebel state. Tough choice, but she worked with less.\n\nThe real reason she walked out was because something was bothering her mind. A little sprout of thought.","n":235},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"She couldn’t move, she couldn’t think and she was stuck with a view that in her mind equated to a literal hell. And to think that about all things she went through to get there, it was definitely something that she deserved. Not immediately when it happened, but she made her choices. She chose to fight for something that wasn’t even remotely worth it and cards have changed their meanings. It was a stupid fixation of her mind that made her believe into something so unlikely that she refused to question it. Any amount of reasoning would destroy the tiny pestering hope in her head and the fear of such collapse has blinded her as she chased a non achievable dream. She had Vincent and Bork, she could have stayed where she was. She could stay with her friends and choose to let go.\n\n- I thought I told you that you can’t run away from the guards, - Victorian stood by the tree, - You definitely didn’t need to kill anyone.\n\n- Sorry, not really used to things being so fragile, - Kara was looking straight without giving any more attention to her guest than she needed, - You shouldn’t have given them the charm if you wanted them safe and sound.\n\n- Well, I thought that we have an understanding, - Victorian probably have lost a rock paper scissors to Ember to be where he was right now.\n\n- You seem to keep underestimating my stupidity, - Kara was coldly inspecting the gorge trying to assemble an image in her mind. To the left was the little grove where she planned to replant Teresa and Vincent to surround them with their children, - They would have made it if the academy taught these idiots not to open fire with their teammates still in the field.\n\n- Well we can’t tell their families that, - Victorian seemed to be too content with the idea of shifting the blame. It’s not like Kara would ever see these people, if the kids don’t have to grow up blaming their neighbors for the death of a parent maybe they would have a chance of fitting in.\n\n- You know, if you told us ahead of time we could have made it work, - Victorian clearly haven't seen the problem that she saw. How could he? He didn’t even know which one of them was Vincent.\n\nKara didn’t answer. She was trying to scramble some thoughts. She could start a new garden here with Vincent and Bork, but she would probably have to make some changes about her view of a happy potato family. She would not change their names. Vincent might have a strong identity crisis and that would be the last thing that Kara would want.","n":236},{"chapter":"Black Heart","text":"It didn’t take too long for Rein to join Kara outside.\n\n- You alright? - Kara could only guess what her childhood friend was thinking right now. She suddenly felt like she knew absolutely nothing about him and somehow that made something unsettled in her chest. Maybe she should have reached out more.\n\n- Yeah, just discovered that my father is alive and clearly too busy to care about his family, - Rein was surprisingly calm, - To be honest I wouldn’t believe a word he says, but it seems like it’s either that or he is going to keep us here until the tournament is over.\n\n- Well that’s dumb, - Kara didn’t know where the feeling of a relief came from. If you take the tournament out of the equation of her life, she was perfectly happy to move on and hide somewhere in a rebel state, - Did you tell him that I didn’t appreciate the gesture?\n\n- Yeah, about that, - Rein took out the beating black heart out of the pocket. Kara felt a jolt of disgust, but was too surprised to come up with a reaction, - He said that this should help to control it. Something about embracing the past.\n\nKara reluctantly took the heart from Rein. It felt cold, concentrated and infinitely calm and composed. Exactly how a dead cat's heart would beat. No fear, no purpose, just a simple routine to continue beating. It was just an object that performed some action over and over again with the only relief being the reassurance that the next beat is going to follow no matter what. Kara squeezed it and felt her own heart feel the pressure.\n\n- What is this? - she was terrified now. Whatever magic was involved in creating such an object it certainly wasn’t something to play with.\n\n- It’s about Fluffer…\n\nKara didn’t hear the rest. She burned the heart instantly to make sure she didn’t.","n":237},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"To make sure your potatoes are well fried you have to turn them all to the other side. Now, how do you make sure that they all get flipped and reach the perfect golden state? Here is the deal, you either embrace the fact that some of them will forever remain al dente or you just reduce the numbers. It is much easier to look after one slice on a small pan than attempt to spread hundreds on an endlessly big hibachi table and turn them all at exactly the right time.\n\nAlthough, there is no right way to do it. People think that the crisp nature of home fried potatoes is the natural charm of the dish, however, depending on the culture, one might prefer the softer sensation with little to no salt. The dish changes depending on the way you choose to handle it, just like a book can change a mood depending on how you read it. Potatoes are just a medium to express your choice.\n\nKara wasn’t sure what had changed, the world around just felt distant and cold. It was a low shiver coming from the bottom of her heart all the way to the top. The world suddenly started making sense.","n":238},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"When Potato Show first aired it was set up as a fun way to pass time and learn some simple and sometimes absolute nonsense recipes. It mostly focused on telling a story about something that was destined to go extinct and warned citizens about certain problems that might occur due to certain behaviors. It took the majority side on general concepts and was generally useful for Septum citizens. For other states it was a noble show with an infamous reputation to gather enough attention to hit top charts among so-called truth seekers. As long as it kept the attention of some audience it was alive.\n\nAlive in a new form of life fighting for its own niche. Alive as a T-cell in the information immunity system developed to specifically guard the world from potatoes. Useless, randomly generated and yet quite potent. That was as far as the conspiracists have gotten to this day. Novem idiots.\n\nIt was vivid, loud and unrealistically relatable to everyone in Septum in the sole fact that it was the only thing they were allowed to know about what was currently happening in the world around. They were absolutely safe from the ridiculous complexity of facts and conflicts. Toham protected them in the only way she knew.\n\nWhat could have been the reason for such a harsh strategy one could only wonder. Some believed that it was a way to finalize the geographical and philosophical separation of Septum making it an independent exclusive state claimed by its heroes for their own use and entertainment. Spectacles observing spectacles. Rest of the world stood by silently as more conscious Septum citizens separated to rebuild their state to better fit the long standing institution. Toham didn’t stop them too harshly, if they wanted a different place to leave there were plenty of options. 8 to be precise.\n\nThose who stayed had a better future for them. They would get to live how they wanted as long as they followed rules. And if they didn’t there were always criminal feists to provide Novem with new heroes to fight in their informational games. Maybe one of them would join the rebellion and try to kill forty eight heroes responsible for this seclusion. Kara didn’t care if that happened. She wasn’t the one who had to do any of this killing.\n\n- Fezzik, why don’t you tell me why are we at this war? - Toham was nonchalantly cutting through the potatoes, feeling the burning in her heart and her stomach twisting in slight disgust.\n\n- Kara, it’s just potatoes, - Fezzik waved a chilly pepper, - Why not add some spice in it? This is war because you don’t want to change the traditions! At least let me add some flavor!","n":239},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"She looked up at Fluffer Huggins now floating around the room more like a ghost than a cat. It kind of reminded Kara of Carp. It really didn’t matter to her what was going to happen next. Right now she just needed to stay with her team and keep them safe to stay safe. She couldn’t trust them, but at least they had no reason to be her enemies.","n":240},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"It was painful to be blamed for things that Toham knew she couldn’t refute. Only thing she could do is bring up the counter arguments from the past. She had plenty of stories for that. So many, in fact, that she almost believed that hypocrites of opposing states were just plotting to push another great cunning exploit to make Septum suffer. Almost.\n\n- Traditions are often the only thing keeping the society from disintegrating into a complete chaos, - Toham was clearing the cutting board and sliced potatoes slid into the clear bowl, - Trying to change the original flavor when it’s already hard to get a fixed result is just frivolous.\n\n- Look, I smuggled some special spices from Unus friends. They have the best peppers in all nine states, - Fezzik was quite comfortable where he stood shaking a can of pickled jalapenos in front of Kara's face, - Would be a shame if they would go to waste without use.","n":241},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"Kara stood up and dusted off her pants.\n\n- I hope you know that trying to conspire against the state won’t look good on any of us, - Kara looked straight at Rein wondering if he fully understood what was happening. She stretched a hand to help him up.\n\n- Well, it’s not like they can do anything about it. They should have been more vigilant to make sure that we wouldn’t get trapped in the mines in the first place, - Rein shrugged and took the hand, - We can’t trust either of them.\n\n- Captain Obvious strikes again, - Kara smiled. Maybe there was still a chance for this friendship.","n":242},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"Toham never actually seriously questioned where people actually got their children from. They seemed to appear out of nowhere regardless of the fact that barely anyone felt safe enough to start a family. It was one of the greatest mysteries of Septum. People just continued their bloodlines in hope to reach salvation in the comforting argument of creating a new generation to fix mistakes of the past or propel the human race to another couple of years in the future. Something of that sort. Life finds a way and procreating was probably the easiest route to reaching the ambiguous goal of not going extinct. Goal that was so ambiguous that anyone really could contribute to it just by simply staying alive.\n\nThen there were heroes. Curve balls that took the responsibility of making the big choices for the direction of developments of means to prosper for the rest of the tiny units of their race. Animal race, however diverse it could be. Injust discrimination was highly frowned upon.\n\nIt rendered all of previous achievements quite useless. Unless, of course, there was nothing to remember to begin with.\n\nToham secluded the last remaining potatoes in the garden. The only place where they no longer had to fear being eaten or die prematurely from a disease. The garden wasn’t a secret. It was a legend. Even those who knew about it didn’t speak of it or they faced years or days of misfortune. Fortune had little to do with it. Potatoes only existed in the fictional world of the Potato Show that Kara Toham has exclusively created once to briefly summarize some highly implausible events that took place in the real world. Mostly for entertainment and some briefly educational purposes. Half baked in places, but this was only to be expected from projects funded by the government.\n\n- You really want this? - Toham was already hitting a limit of her patience. It meant that she had to take out another pan.\n\n- You can’t be serious, Kara, - Fezzik shot his arms in front of Toham, - We don’t have time for that, - he gestured the can over the potatoes on the drizzling pan. Kara swung her pan at Fezzik with a powerful gust. He fell over and rolled down the stairs. Good thing the demon was already red. Potatoes flew all around at the sudden impact that Kara suddenly felt the shiver in her back. Good thing he was a hero.\n\n- I can be serious, - Toham dropped the scorching pan on Fezzik and took another one out of the counter. Good thing that man didn’t burn.","n":243},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"They entered back into the room together, just like that one time when they were asked to come in for a lecture on responsibility. If you ignored the other creatures there was only one man in the room waiting for them. Last time it was her mom and Rein had to come over because she insisted. This time Kara felt the same way, but on the other side. It felt awkward, but it was important to Rein. Even if he wanted it to seem like it doesn’t. Fluffer Huggins walked in right behind them. Not the right one, but about a thousand times better. Still felt empty, no matter how much attention Kara put into the movement of his paws.\n\n- Thank you for understanding, Alfonse, - Reins father shook the hand of the demon and Fezzik didn’t look too comfortable with it either, - We will do our best to provide you a safe passage to the port. Here are the rings, - mister Valentine gave a zinging box to Fezzik, - They will cloak you from detection systems.\n\n- Sweet, - Fezzik impatiently started inspecting new toys while spreading them around the team, - If you can program machines with magic like this… - Something must have clicked in Fezziks head as he slowly raised his gaze at an old friend with a raised eyebrow, - Did Ember make these?","n":244},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"It was relieving to hear groans of pain behind. Toham would feel terrible if she would have knocked out Fezzik for good. They would have to stop the cameras and mark out the sequence all over again. And wait until Fezzik would recompose himself after a shock.\n\n- Kara, what on earth was that for? - he clumsily curled up on the stairs giving Toham a questioning glare.\n\n- If you don’t want to fry these separately you might as well add them after I leave the room, - Toham kneeled down and counted potatoes, - one, two, three.","n":245},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"- Yeah, he couldn’t quite do anything in front of Eve, - mister Valentine wasn’t trying to keep any secrets. Kara was quite surprised how easy it was to remember that name and yet it didn’t occur to her until now. Eve Parmentier. Too pretentious of a name for missis Olive.","n":246},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"Toham wasn’t saying much as she quickly peeled and cut potatoes focusing mostly on the sounds of Fezzik ranting about something in the background. Cameras, of course, wouldn’t pick up these words for the final cut, but Toham couldn’t help but smile at the sound of his voice. Brought up quite a bit of warm memories to fade out the counterintuitive actions she was performing. Good thing she didn’t add the onions yet.\n\n- Bet you are glad that Unus loves their canned foods more than glass jars, - Toham chuckled, Fezzik liked things that left scrap metal behind. There’s not much you can do with broken glass.","n":247},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"- It seems you two caught yourselves in a shape shifting paradox, - Gizellina creeped behind Floats. Kara didn’t know why she turned her head as if this conversation also addressed herself, - This is quite a gnarly bite, you want me to take care of it?\n\nKara felt awful at this remark.\n\n- No, thank you, - Floats spoke without even questioning what hag meant by a paradox, - I would like to keep it.\n\nToham raised an eyebrow.","n":248},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"Fried potatoes were served and left on the plate with a single parsley leaf on top. Toham threw an empty pan into the sink and turned the water on. It steamed and popped on the still boiling butter.\n\n- The spices are in the pantry, - she took off the gloves and threw them behind her back as she exited the frame. It was time to go home.","n":249},{"chapter":"Other side","text":"- What about you, girl? - Gizellina feebly pointed her finger at Kara. It was nice to finally be just a girl, but it didn’t instill any confidence.\n\n- Sorry, I don’t want any help from you, - Toham cut her losses there and then. It wasn’t worth it having any more obligations to someone new she barely knew.\n\n- I can do nothing against your choice.\n\nTable of Content","n":250}]